<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Plunges Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar plunged against the yen and the euro  
in New York Friday, dragged down by an across-the-board selloff in 
U.S. stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 105.42  
Japanese yen, down from 107.35 yen late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Currency traders abandoned the U.S. currency as the Dow Jones  
industrial average lost 266.90 points to close at 10,019.71. Stock 
markets tumbled after Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan 
warned that overvalued stocks prices could eventually hurt 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's comments were immediately taken to mean the Fed  
would likely raise interest rates at its next meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to investors' fears was the release Friday of the  
producer price index, a key inflationary guage. Producer prices 
rose 1.1 percent in September from August, according to the Labor 
Department, more than twice the increase forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	The jump in producer prices was the largest increase in nine  
years, and spurred more sales of U.S. currency by further fueling 
speculation Federal Reserve policy-makers will raise lending rates 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0889, up from  
$1.0781 late Wednesday. . 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4585 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4741, and 1.4884 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4810. The British 
pound rose to $1.6714 from $1.6642. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7962 German 
marks, down from 1.8141; 6.0824 French francs, down from 6.0844; 
and 1,778.19 Italian lire, down from 1,796.00. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
