</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell today on worries over New  
York share prices set off by comments from the U.S. Federal Reserve 
chairman. The Nikkei fell 178.69 points to close at 17,601.57. In a 
speech to bankers yesterday, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan that the decline in equity premiums that has kept U.S. 
stock prices rising in recent years could be temporary. 

</P>
<P>
	Surprises in Store for Holiday Computer Buyers  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Consumers expecting to see ever-lowering  
computer prices as they begin their holiday shopping may be in for 
a surprise. Manufacturers are beginning to pass on the higher costs 
of memory chips, known as RAM, to consumers, who have been seeking 
more and more powerful chips as they go after faster computers with 
the best graphics. Sixty-four megabytes of RAM -- a typical amount 
of memory in a $1,000 computer -- once sold for as low as $40. Now 
the same memory is retailing for about $100 and could reach $150 
next month, analysts said yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Goodyear's Gadsden Plant Plan OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) -- Union workers at Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber  
Co.'s plant here approved a plan to continue making light truck 
tires, saving at least hundreds of jobs, rather than end production 
in December as earlier planned. The decision by United Steelworkers 
members in voting this week was announced by Goodyear yesterday 
afternoon. Goodyear officials said union members voted 655-210 to 
continue making tires with a scaled-back workforce and other 
changes sought by the company, which in February had announced it 
would cease tire production in Gadsden and lay off some 1,320 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Biotech Firm Buying LeukoSite  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE (AP) -- Millennium Pharmaceuticals announced yesterday  
it will buy LeukoSite, another Cambridge biotechnology company, for 
$635 million in stock. In the deal, announced after the close of 
trading, Millennium will pay $35.86 of its own shares for every 
share of LeukoSite, a 49 percent premium to the stock's closing 
price yesterday. Shares of LeukoSite yesterday closed up $1.75, or 
7.8 percent, at $24.12 1/2 on the Nasdaq. Shares of Millennium closed 
at $83.47, down three cents. 

</P>
<P>
	Vietnam Resort Plan May Be Scrapped  
</P>
<P>
	DALAT, Vietnam (AP) -- A $706 million plan to build Vietnam's  
biggest tourist resort may be dismantled after the Singapore 
consortium slated to finance it postponed its investment 
indefinitely, according to Dow Jones Newswires. The project's 
demise would be a serious blow to Lam Dong, the central highlands 
province for which it was planned. Provincial leaders had hoped 
money spent by an anticipated 300,000 additional tourists each year 
would triple local incomes after a decade. The 5,750-acre project 
was to have included two golf courses, a theater, a botanical 
garden and a zoo. 

</P>
<P>
	Moody's Coy on Thailand Rating  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- An analyst for Moody's Investor  
Services left Thailand after a well-publicized visit this week with 
praise for the government's economic management, but without saying 
when it will upgrade the country's rating. ``We have a lot more 
confidence in the policy-makers than we did at the time of the 
crisis,'' Thomas Byrne, senior analyst of Moody's sovereign risk 
unit, told Dow Jones Newswires in an interview today. Sovereign 
risk measures the ability of a government to pay back its 
borrowings. 

</P>
<P>
	Trump Casino Holds Liquidation  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Trump World's Fair Casino prepared  
for demolition yesterday with something that resembled a garage 
sale, pawning off TVs, lamps and alarm clocks. The casino, which 
opened in 1981 as the Playboy and later operated as the Atlantis, 
has always bled money. It was forced into bankruptcy in 1989. 
Donald Trump bought it for $63 million and operated it as a 
non-casino hotel -- Trump Regency -- for years before investing $48 
million and reopening it in 1996 as Trump World's Fair Casino. It 
was losing $10 million a year by the time Trump decided to demolish 
it and start over. 

</P>
<P>
	Chips Could Get Much Smaller  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers using a computer-driven microscope  
say they can now draw a pattern with lines separated by only 
200-billionths of an inch, an advance that could lead to electronic 
chips much smaller and of different materials than those now in 
use. Chad A. Mirkin of Northwestern University said that the new 
technology is able to draw a lines that are 15 to 30 nanometers 
wide and separated by only 5 nanometers. A nanometer is 
one-billionth of a meter. A fine human hair is about 10,000 
nanometers wide. A report on the new research appears Friday in the 
journal Science. 

</P>
<P>
	Disney's Imagineering Head Leaving  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kenneth Wong, head of Walt Disney's famous  
Imagineering division, is leaving the company to pursue 
``independent'' opportunities. Walt Disney Imagineering is the arm 
of the Walt Disney Co. that creates all Disney resorts, theme parks 
and real estate developments. Wong, 44, told the Los Angeles Times 
that he also is interested in the Internet, in combination with 
``art, design, technology and real estate'' but declined to be 
specific. 

</P>
<P>
	GM, Suzuki Plan Car for Asia  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- American automaker General Motors Corp. will  
produce a small passenger vehicle it has developed with Suzuki 
Motor Corp. for sale in the Asian market starting in 2001. The new 
model, called the YGM-1, is based on Suzuki's new small car 
platform and GM's design engineering. Both GM and Suzuki, which is 
10 percent owned by the U.S. automaker, said today they haven't 
decided where in Asia the YGM will be manufactured. 

</P>
<P>
	Kmart To Open 400 New Stores  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Kmart Corp. plans to open 400 new stores over the  
next five years, including 70 stores next year. The Troy, 
Mich.-based company also announced that it would renovate 166 
smaller stores. About half of the new stores will be Super Kmarts, 
which are bigger stores that carry groceries along with wide array 
of general merchandise goods, such as clothes and home furnishings. 
But Kmart is still struggling to keep pace with rival Wal-Mart 
Stores Inc., which continues to dominate the discount store market 
with their aggressive pricing strategy. 

</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
<P>
	Producer prices rose 1.1 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Business inventories rose 0.3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Today: Industrial production  



  	   	
