<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Returns to Formula One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEPANG, Malaysia (AP) -- Michael Schumacher, injured in a crash  
three months ago, returned to Formula One racing Friday during 
practice for the Malaysian Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	He led the first of the two timed practices -- ahead by a lot in  
the rain -- and then finished fifth in the second during faster and 
drier conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``No problem, no pain,'' said Schumacher, who fractured his  
right leg in the British Grand Prix on July 11. ``The Ferrari seems 
in good shape and so am I.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Villeneuve, in a BAR-Supertec, had the fastest time  
overall. Villeneuve, a former world champion struggling with a new 
team, was timed in 1 minute, 42.407 seconds over the 3.4-mile 
course, 40 miles south of Kuala Lumpur. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car was like a little bit of magic today but we need to do  
the same tomorrow when we will have learned more about the limits 
of the circuit,'' Villeneuve said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Malaysian Grand Prix is making its debut on the world  
championship calendar, and Friday's practice marked the first time 
all the Formula One cars were on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice had an unexpected visitor. A leopard was lurking  
near the tires just off the track but was scared away by the 
roaring engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The official qualifying is Saturday, and teams are still making  
adjustments. 
</P>
<P>
	``We worked on the setup today but the car is not quite there  
yet,'' Schumacher said. ``As we are not far off the pace and have 
enough time to improve, I am confident for tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher's best was 1:42.875 after going fastest with 1:44.824  
in the morning after morning rains. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the beginning of the monsoon season in Malaysia, and it  
has rained almost every day for a month. 
</P>
<P>
	David Coulthard was second in a McLaren-Mercedes in 1:42.519,  
and Jean Alesi was next with 1:42.701. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ferrari duo of Eddie Irvine, 1:42.725, and Schumacher  
followed. Defending world champion Mika Hakkinen was eighth in 
1:43.153 in a McLaren-Mercedes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen leads Irvine 62-60 after 14 races and has a chance to  
clinch the title in this racer. A win by Hakkinen and no better 
than a fifth by Irvine gives Hakkinen at least a 10-point margin 
heading into the last race in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In case of a tie, Hakkinen would take the title because he would  
have more wins than Irvine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
