<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Banks More Than $10 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore reported today that he  
had raised $6.8 million for his presidential race from July to 
September and had $10.3 million in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign also applied for $9.2 million in federal  
assistance, which gives Gore almost $20 million to spend. The 
federal government matches the first $250 of each individual 
contribution for candidates who agree to limit the amount of money 
they spend on their campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased with our fund-raising efforts so far,''  
Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said. ``With the matching 
funds and the number of low-dollar donors, we're very close to 
completing the fund-raising portion of the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since January, the vice president has raised $24.3 million for  
his campaign and $2.5 million for his general election account. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's figures are slightly higher than the estimates his  
campaign issued Sept. 30, the end of the reporting period. At the 
time, Gore's Democratic opponent, former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley, 
reported raising an estimated $6.7 million to Gore's $6.5 million. 
In addition, the Bradley campaign said it had more than $10 million 
in the bank, while Gore's campaign said it had between $9.5 million 
and $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley and the other campaigns had yet to report their final  
figures, which are due at the end of today. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans, Texas Gov. George W. Bush has estimated that  
he raised $19 million from July 1 to Sept. 30, bringing his 
record-setting total to more than $56 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona was a distant second, raising an  
estimated $3 million during the last three months, bringing his 
total to $9.3 million. That includes $2 million transferred from 
his Senate campaign account. 
</P>
<P>
	The McCain campaign took in $64,000 over the Internet during the  
last four days of September, after sending out an e-mail seeking 
last-minute contributions. ``We must continue the momentum we have 
shown in the press and the polls by showing continued fund-raising 
strength,'' McCain wrote in the e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans Gary Bauer, Patrick Buchanan, Elizabeth Dole, Steve  
Forbes and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah each raised more than $1 
million from July to September. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain had $2 million in his campaign bank account as of Sept.  
30; Forbes had $1.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who is largely financing his own campaign, raised an  
estimated $1.4 million over the last three months, bringing his 
total to $4.2 million through Sept. 30. In addition, Forbes spent 
about $15 million from his own pocket. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
