<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Prices Spike in Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level surged 1.1  
percent in September, the biggest increase in nine years, the 
government said today in a report that sent stocks diving on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 200 points  
shortly after the opening bell as investors focused on the 
worrisome inflation news and fresh concerns voiced by Federal 
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan that investors could be 
underestimating the risk of a sudden sharp fall in the value of 
stocks and other assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said the huge runup in its Producer Price  
Index, which measures inflation pressures before they reach the 
consumer, was more than double a worrisome 0.5 percent gain in 
August. The increase was blamed on higher prices for energy and 
food. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, both bond and stock prices were dragged down by  
the inflation report and the reaction of overseas markets to 
Greenspan's new worries about high asset values. The Dow lost more 
than 200 points in the first minutes after the opening bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to a conference on risk management Thursday night,  
Greenspan said that banks ``must be careful not to overlook'' the 
threats posed by a big decline in asset values. 
</P>
<P>
	``History tells us that sharp reversals occur abruptly, most  
often with little advance notice,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Greenspan has expressed such concerns before, investors  
have been put more on edge by the fact that the Fed has already 
raised a key U.S. interest rate twice this year because of 
inflation worries and may act again. Japan's benchmark Nikkei Stock 
Average fell by 178.69 points, losing 1 percent of its value in 
turbulent trading before Wall Street opened. 
</P>
<P>
	In another economic report, the government said today that  
industrial production at the nation's factories, utilities and 
mines fell an unexpected 0.3 percent in September, the first 
decline since a 0.2 percent drop in November 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve, which issued the report, attributed the  
decline to Hurricane Floyd, which raked the East Coast in 
September. The Fed said the storm held down production of 
electricity, motor vehicles and some other goods. Excluding the 
storm's effects, industrial product would have posted a small 
increase, the Fed said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. industry operated at 80.3 percent of capacity in September,  
down from 80.7 percent the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index was the biggest gain  
since a 1.3 percent jump in September 1990, when oil prices were 
surging following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	Not counting the volatile energy and food categories, the  
so-called core rate of inflation at the wholesale level rose a 
troublesome 0.8 percent in September, the largest increase since 
December 1998, when the core rate rose 1 percent. In August, the 
core rate fell 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the Fed decided not to raise interest rates following  
quarter-point increases in June and August. But financial markets 
are worried that when the Fed next meets on Nov. 16 the increased 
inflation pressures will prompt a third rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The report ``is causing some alarm bells to go off at the  
hallowed halls of the Federal Reserve,'' said Paul Kasriel, chief 
economist for The Northern Trust Co. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an annual  
rate of 3.5 percent, compared with no change for all of 1998. The 
pickup in this year's wholesale prices is coming from big increases 
in energy costs, which had been declining for much of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For September, energy costs rose 2.2 percent, reflecting higher  
gasoline, heating oil and natural gas prices, and followed a 3.7 
percent gain in August. A 5.5 percent spike in energy prices in 
April put the Fed on inflation alert, and on June 30 the central 
bank raised interest rates for the first time in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	A 2.2 percent rise in gasoline prices last month contributed to  
the advance in overall energy costs. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a nationwide check of gasoline stations by the  
Lundberg Survey, gasoline prices, which normally fall after Labor 
Day, were rising in September as the price of crude oil jumped. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil prices rose 6 percent and residential electric power  
rose 0.8 percent. Residential natural gas increased 2.5 percent, 
the biggest gain since November 1997 when natural gas prices rose 
3.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices posted a 1 percent increase, the biggest gain since  
January, when food costs rose 1.5 percent. The rise in food prices 
comes as the East Coast and other parts of the country suffered bad 
weather last month. In August, food prices rose 0.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in food prices last month was led by a 9.7 percent  
increase in pork prices, the largest gain since a 19.3 percent 
increase in January. Fresh fruits rose 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In another report, the Commerce Department said today that the  
level of inventories held by businesses on shelves and backlots 
rose 0.3 percent in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger car prices rose 2 percent, the biggest since a 3  
percent rise in September 1990; tobacco product prices rose 8.4 
percent, the largest increase since a 26.1 gain in December 1998 
and cigarette prices rose 9.5 percent, the biggest gain since a 
30.7 percent increase in December 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 11:10:29 </DATE_TIME>
