<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Closer Rivera a Savior for Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Roger Clemens vs. Pedro Martinez is a pitching  
matchup worthy of the hype. 
</P>
<P>
	If Game 3 of the American League championship series is like the  
first two, though, it will be decided by the finishers, not the 
starters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last couple of games, the team that's had the most depth  
in the bullpen has been able to come up the winner,'' said Yankees 
outfielder Bernie Williams, whose 10th-inning Game 1 homer also had 
something to do with it. ``I certainly believe in the power of 
bullpen depth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Yankees, that means Mariano Rivera and a supporting cast  
of setup men who have helped make him one of the game's best 
closers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great pitcher and a great closer,'' said Boston  
outfielder Damon Buford, whom Rivera struck out for the final out 
in New York's 3-2 victory on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox managed to beat Cleveland in the first playoff round  
using a simple formula: Outlast the starting pitcher, and beat up 
on the bullpen. Boston scored 29 runs against Indians relievers 
while winning three in a row to rally from a two-game deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	That won't work against the Yankees.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're so strong out there. We've got guys out there with so  
much experience in these types of games,'' New York starter Andy 
Pettitte said. ``I don't foresee that happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees lead Boston 2-0 in the AL championship series, just  
as Cleveland did. But the Yankees have something the Indians 
didn't: Rivera. 
</P>
<P>
	``Different lineups, different pitching,'' he said. ``It doesn't  
mean they're going to score 23 runs in this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera had 45 saves with a 4-3 record and a 1.83 ERA during the  
regular season, his third as the Yankees' closer. He converted his 
last 22 save opportunities, and did not allow a run in his last 28 
appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Add in four scoreless postseason appearances -- including a  
victory in Game 1 and a save in Game 2 against Boston -- and he has 
pitched 36 2-3 shutout innings in 32 games since giving up a run 
against Tampa Bay on July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, he has allowed only two earned runs in 41 innings in  
postseason play -- an 0.44 ERA that's best in major league history 
among pitchers with at least 30 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre praised his closer for his consistency  
and also for putting personal statistics aside to become a better 
pitcher. Rivera's strikeout total decreased for the third 
consecutive year, for example, from 130 to 68 to 36. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of just rearing back and throwing ... now he doesn't  
really care if he strikes people out,'' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox answer with closer by committee. Derek Lowe gets  
most of the calls but also shares time with Tom Gordon and Rod 
Beck. 
</P>
<P>
	Setting up for for Rivera are Mike Stanton and Jeff Nelson. It's  
a role Rivera filled under John Wetteland, who was the Yankees' 
World Series MVP in 1996 before he left for Texas as a free agent. 
Torre then handed the closer's job to Rivera. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little different when there's nobody behind you,  
somebody cuts that safety net out from under you and you realize 
that when the ball gets by you, the game is over,'' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took him time. But we kept handing him the ball, saying, `I  
don't care how bad it is, you are going to still do this thing.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said confidence in a closer can only go so far.  
</P>
<P>
	``Once you start taking things for granted,'' he said, ``things  
can turn around for you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
