<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 08:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asarco Accepts Grupo Mexico Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Asarco Inc. today accepted a $1.24 billion cash  
takeover offer from Grupo Mexico SA de CV, following a seven-week 
bidding contest for the nation's third-largest copper producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Grupo Mexico increased its proposal by 25 cents to $29.75 a  
share, topping an offer by rival Phelps Dodge Corp. Grupo Mexico 
also will assume Asarco's $1.02 billion in debt. Phelps had 
previously said it would not raise its bid. 
</P>
<P>
	With the addition of Asarco's 1 billion pounds of annual copper  
production, Grupo Mexico will be the world's third-largest copper 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The jousting for control of Asarco underscores the pressure  
copper companies face to cut costs by consolidating. The price of 
copper has fallen by almost one-third over the past five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of New York-based Asarco were up 12 1/2 cents at $29.43 3/4 in  
morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The losing bidder, Phoenix, Ariz.-based Phelps Dodge will have  
to content itself with its $1.8 billion acquisition of Cyprus Amax 
Minerals Co. of Englewood, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge shares were up 37 1/2 cents at $57.62 1/2, also on the  
NYSE. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
