<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chimp Paternity Mystery Solved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- All the monkey business at the Los Angeles  
Zoo has been figured out. 
</P>
<P>
	A paternity test has revealed which chimpanzee fathered three  
chimps whose arrival was unexpected, to say the least. 
</P>
<P>
	The births surprised keepers because, of the six males in the  
chimpanzee exhibit, two were too young to be fathers, one was too 
old and three had undergone vasectomies. It turns out that 
11-year-old Shaun got a bum vasectomy in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``So Shaun was having a real good time,'' laughed Lora LaMarca,  
the zoo's longtime marketing director. The chimp was once described 
in a news release as being small for his age and picked on by 
females. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few years later, he was picking on them.  
</P>
<P>
	The paternity mystery drew international media attention and  
helped boost zoo attendance by 10 percent. The DNA results were 
announced on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' during a visit by 
surviving babies Jean and Jake. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterinarians analyzed blood and hair samples to prove beyond a  
reasonable doubt that Shaun was daddy to Jean, Jake and the late 
Toshi. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I went to veterinarian school, nobody dreamed of this  
kind of stuff,'' said Charles Sedgwick, the zoo's chief 
veterinarian. 
</P>
<P>
	The births came as keepers thought they had finally succeeded in  
stopping the monkey business -- at least to the extent that there 
would be no more new chimps. 
</P>
<P>
	They had tried handing out birth control pills, but the females  
passed them around and everyone chomped them down, including males 
and babies. Contraceptive implants weren't strong enough to stop 
the population boom. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was off to the operating room for the exhibit's three  
capable males to have their sperm-carrying vas deferens ducts 
snipped. It's a procedure that's virtually 100 percent effective in 
humans. 
</P>
<P>
	But apparently not in chimpanzees.  
</P>
<P>
	It's likely that the ducts weren't completely severed during the  
operation. Another possibility was that the severed tubes grew back 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean and Jake are being raised in a nursery but will be  
introduced to the troop. Later this month, a chimp born to a mother 
at a Florida park will join Jean and Jake. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
