<DOCNO> APW19991015.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 10:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Outlines Anti-Hunger Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore marked World Hunger Day  
by paying a campaign stop today at a local soup kitchen, where he 
proposed steps to help working parents feed their families. ``In 
our time of plenty there shouldn't be anybody hungry in the United 
States,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore rushed out his hunger platform ahead of a long-scheduled  
address on child poverty next week by Bill Bradley, his rival for 
the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	At the core of a ``policy paper'' Gore released today are the  
full restoration of food stamps for legal immigrants and a 
nutritious, daily school breakfast for every child. Gore did not 
detail how he would reach this goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing an apron over his crisp dress shirt and necktie, Gore  
briefly chipped in with volunteers layering bologna and cheese on 
wheat bread. He lamented that, of the 36 million Americans who do 
not get enough to eat each day, 14 million are children. 
</P>
<P>
	``That should gnaw at our conscience because we have the food,  
we have the resources, we have the means to do something about 
it,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	If elected president, Gore said he would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Give communities unspecified resources to design innovative  
strategies, such as expanding the number of schools that provide 
free meals or making sure parents know that breakfast is available 
at school for their children. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow working families to own a car without jeopardizing their  
food stamp eligibility. Under current policy, families receiving 
nutritional assistance cannot own a car worth more than $4,650. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Push for full food-stamp eligibility for legal immigrants.  
Last year, Congress restored food stamps for elderly, disabled and 
minor non-citizens, covering 250,000 of the 935,000 legal 
immigrants who had lost those benefits under 1996 welfare reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Reward states that do a ``good job'' signing up families for  
food stamps. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Support anti-hunger partnerships among local, state, national  
and religious groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a growing child, going to bed hungry, night after night,  
is more than unpleasant,'' Gore said. ``Its powerful effects will 
be felt for a lifetime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An Agriculture Department study released Thursday found that at  
least 10 percent of households in 18 states and the District of 
Columbia don't have enough food. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
