<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Criticizes GOP on Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton tested her  
national security wings Friday as a potential U.S. Senate candidate 
by criticizing Republican senators for voting down an international 
treaty banning nuclear weapons testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing her husband's sentiments, Mrs. Clinton said Senate  
Republicans shunned an opportunity to be peacemakers when they 
rejected the pact. 
</P>
<P>
	``Signing that treaty would have been taking a giant step toward  
creating a world of peace,'' she told about 100 community leaders 
and congregants at Antioch Baptist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Her comments elaborated on a written statement released Friday  
in which she said the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty would ``reduce 
the risk of nuclear war, curtail the spread of nuclear weapons, and 
help guarantee America's national security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has denounced the treaty's rejection as  
``reckless partisanship'' and warned other nuclear powers not to 
misinterpret it as a softening of the U.S. position against the 
spread of such weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., says Democrats were  
the partisans. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, however, said the Senate ``sent a dangerous  
message to people around the world, to our allies, and to Americans 
at home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also told the invitation-only crowd that the treaty should  
be important to them because ``everyone has an obligation to be a 
peacemaker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to face New York City Mayor Rudolph  
Giuliani in a bid for the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani defended Senate Republicans earlier in the week.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
