<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell today following a fresh  
warning from U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan against 
excessive optimism by stock traders. The dollar tumbled against the 
Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 178.69  
points, or 1 percent, to close at 17,601.57. The index closed up 
25.77 points, or 0.15 percent, on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 105.78 yen late today in Tokyo, down  
1.49 yen from late Thursday and also below its overnight New York 
level of 107.35 yen. During the day, it ranged from 105.73 yen to 
107.63 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to bankers Thursday night, after U.S. markets  
closed, Greenspan urged continued vigilance in managing risk at a 
time of prosperity, robust economic expansion and roaring stock 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan has warned for years against excessive economic  
optimism that can lead to risky business decisions and his comments 
Thursday followed recent warnings by federal regulators that signs 
of risk are spreading in the banking industry despite high earnings 
and hefty assets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Economists have been unable to anticipate sharp reversals in  
confidence,'' Greenspan told a Washington conference organized by 
the Office of the Comptroller. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a minimum, risk managers need to ... set aside somewhat  
higher contingency resources ... to cover the losses that will 
inevitably emerge from time to time when investors suffer a loss of 
confidence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan also said that the decline in equity premiums that has  
kept U.S. stock prices rising in recent years could be temporary. 
</P>
<P>
	The equity premium is the difference between the returns yielded  
by stocks and the returns yielded by U.S. Treasury bonds. It 
effectively reflects the reward investors demand in return for 
taking risks on stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In the speech, Greenspan waded indirectly into a debate over how  
long U.S. stock prices can keep rising, although he offered no 
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks are often sensitive to developments that could  
affect market sentiment in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market turned very cautious ahead of the opening of  
trading in New York, and the weekend,'' said Masatoshi Sato, 
manager at Kankaku Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices also got little support from a government report  
that slightly upgraded the assessment of Japan's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The country is mounting a ``modest'' recovery from its worst  
downturn in decades, but weak corporate spending and high 
unemployment are still hindering the economy, Japan's Economic 
Planning Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 26.48 points, or 1.72 percent, to 1,510.26. The 
TOPIX closed up 9.78 points, or 0.64 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 757.23 million shares, down from 841.42 million shares 
Thursday. Retreaters overwhelmed advancing issues 746 to 453, while 
137 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average  
closed up 54.45 points, at 10,286.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's comments also sent the dollar lower.  
</P>
<P>
	``Greenspan's words have heightened concerns among traders that  
the Dow Jones Industrial Average could be on the verge of a 
significant fall and we saw the dollar losing ground to the yen, 
euro, Swiss franc and the pound today,'' said Shuji Takano, 
assistant foreign exchange manager at ABN-AMRO in Tokyo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
