<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Power Goes Out at Hurricane Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The National Hurricane Center switched over to  
backup generators when the power went out Friday morning, blacking 
out computer screens as Hurricane Irene swirled to the southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The power was only out for about 30 seconds, said director Jerry  
Jarrell, but a system designed to bridge the gap between commercial 
and generator power failed, bringing down most of the center's 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	It took about 90 minutes to reboot all the machines.  
</P>
<P>
	During that period, which began shortly after 11 a.m., the  
center was not able to process satellite data. However, forecasters 
were able to get all the data they needed from National Centers for 
Environmental Prediction computers in Kansas City, Mo., and 
Washington, Jarrell said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as communications are working, we can work,'' Jarrell  
said. ``It was more a delay than a loss of data.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
