<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Tech's Hawkes Seeks Vindication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Probably more than anyone else, Virginia  
Tech's Michael Hawkes has suffered the memory of last season's 
last-play loss to Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because he also absorbed most of the blame.  
</P>
<P>
	Hawkes wasn't the Hokies defender assigned to Stephen Brominski  
on the final play of the Orangemen's 28-26 victory, but as the 
nearest defender when the tight end pulled in Donovan McNabb's 
13-yard TD pass, he sure looked the part. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everywhere I went, people were bringing it up to me, blaming  
me,'' Hawkes said this week as the fourth-ranked Hokies prepared to 
play the 16th-ranked Orangemen on Saturday night. ``When I was out 
downtown, at a store or even in class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech's players and coaches have refused to identify the  
player who did blow the assignment on the touchdown, and over time 
Hawkes' refusal to defend himself and set the record straight have 
made it his cross to bear. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you make the play, you're the hero and when you don't,  
you're looked down on,'' said Hawkes, seen rushing toward Brominski 
on the play. ``Even if he wasn't my responsibility, I should have 
gotten there and made the play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was one of three Virginia Tech suffered last season,  
all in dramatic fashion and all with an apparent goat. Ricky Hall 
dropped a potential game-winning touchdown in the final seconds of 
a 28-24 loss to Temple, and Anthony Midget was beaten for a 47-yard 
TD pass as Virginia rallied to beat the Hokies 36-32. 
</P>
<P>
	For Hawkes, Saturday night is a chance to enjoy his revenge.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't just want to get back at them for that one play,'' the  
linebacker said. ``I want to get back because this is another step 
toward our goal of winning the Big East. All the criticism has made 
me work to be a stronger, more mature person. And a better player. 
That's what I want to show Saturday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orangemen (5-1, 2-0) have been beaten 31-7 and 31-3 in their  
last two visits to noisy Lane Stadium, so this week coach Paul 
Pasqualoni tried to simulate the noise of 52,000 fans with speakers 
blaring as the Orange offense practiced. 
</P>
<P>
	The players said practice was so loud they couldn't hear a  
thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasqualoni said last week's victory at Pittsburgh, when the  
Orangemen took a 24-0 lead and had to hang on to win 24-17, could 
help against the Hokies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We kind of got tested there in the fourth quarter, had to keep  
our poise,'' Pasqualoni said. ``We can make something positive out 
of that experience.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
