<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Technology May Spur Tiny Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers using a computer-driven microscope  
say they can now draw a pattern with lines separated by only 
200-billionths of an inch, an advance that could lead to electronic 
chips much smaller and of different materials than those now in 
use. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad A. Mirkin of Northwestern University said that the new  
technology is able to draw a lines that are 15 to 30 nanometers 
wide and separated by only 5 nanometers. A nanometer is 
one-billionth of a meter. A fine human hair is about 10,000 
nanometers wide. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the technique eventually may be used to build very tiny  
electronic circuits, or to store vast volumes of information in a 
very small space. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this technique, we can put 80 million words in a square  
inch,'' said Mirkin. It may be possible, he said, to store a whole 
library in a wafer and then retrieve the information for use. 
</P>
<P>
	A report on the new research appears Friday in the journal  
Science. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirkin said the technique combines the ancient technology of the  
quill pen with the precision of a computer-driven atomic force 
microscope to draw lines on a surface. 
</P>
<P>
	Ink flows down the microscope pen tip onto a surface, just as  
ink flows onto paper from the hollow of a dipped quill pen. 
</P>
<P>
	Water, which collects naturally on the microscope tip, is a key  
part of the process. The water forms a tiny hollow tube, like a 
capillary, that allows the ink, or other materials, to flow to the 
surface. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northwestern researchers demonstrated drawing single lines  
with the system earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, they have improved the technique so that it can draw  
multiple lines, one after the other, and create a pattern in 
nanometer proportions. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a sense, we have transitioned dip-pen nanolithography from  
a single ink process to a four-color printing type of process on a 
nanometer scale,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirkin said that instead of using ink, the technique could use  
any of a variety of useful molecules that would be assembled into 
pattern lines just 30 molecules wide. This would make it possible, 
he said, to build electronic circuits of organic materials that 
some experts believe will be the heart of computers in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next frontier is determining what type of molecules that  
could be used for circuits,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nanometer drawing might also be used to create DNA arrays, a  
type of organic assembly that can be used to identify genes in 
blood or other medical specimens. By building such arrays on a 
nanometer circuit scale, said Mirkin, it might be possible to 
screen for thousands of genes with just one DNA chip. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
