<DOCNO> APW19991015.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Cracks Down on Rave Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- It's a typical rave -- loud, throbbing  
dance music, hundreds of young people and drugs, lots of different 
kinds. Synthetic and potent substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Fade Kainer and his friends are here. The 23-year-old musician  
doesn't see anything strange in the all-night dance party on South 
Beach: ``I don't know if it's any worse than living in the '60s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Florida authorities say the parties and their problems are  
among the worst in the nation. They are cracking down. 
</P>
<P>
	Statewide raids this month at 57 raves netted 1,219 arrests and  
nearly $9.4 million in drugs, weapons, vehicles and cash. As of 
June, nearly 1 million pills had been confiscated across the state, 
according to the Florida Sheriff's Association. Agents seized 
nearly 49,000 doses during the recent Operation Heat Rave, with an 
estimated value of $1.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a big problem in the state,'' state drug czar Jim  
McDonough said. ``It exceeds the rest of the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonough blamed Florida's popularity on the state's  
international connection and the flow of tourists, especially from 
Europe where raves are very popular. 
</P>
<P>
	``Florida is on the cutting edge of focusing on this as a public  
health issue,'' said Rob Housman, a spokesman for White House drug 
policy coordinator Gen. Barry McCaffrey. ``Their coordinated effort 
is a model for other states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey's office lauded the recent crackdown and said that law  
enforcement officials across the country were beginning to pay more 
attention to the scene and synthetic drugs popping up everywhere 
from desert parties in Arizona to clubs in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	The current alphabet soup of designer drugs with names such GHB,  
MDMA and Special K are more potent, more available and in some 
combinations, more deadly than some of the substances floating 
around during the '60s. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida officials say there have been six rave-related drug  
deaths around the state, including two this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lollipops and baby pacifiers are used by some in the rave drug  
set because any product containing methamphetamine, as the 
hallucinogen Ecstasy does, causes one's teeth to grind. You need 
something in your mouth to avoid biting your tongue or your lips. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always think about how many brain cells I'm killing, but  
I'll go back and do it,'' said Josh Mangual, 21, a graphic design 
artist. He added: ``It's not the scene that causes drug use, it's 
the individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Ecstasy, also called Adam, is the drug of choice  
for those involved with the club music and rave scene. Many raves 
attract a younger crowd by advertising that alcohol is not sold on 
the premises. 
</P>
<P>
	The young people who enjoy raving say it isn't fair to reduce  
their culture to a mere drug fest. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny Margolis, 17, said the scene promotes peace, love, unity  
and respect. But she acknowledges it is overshadowed by excessive 
drug use. 
</P>
<P>
	``The music brings people together and the drugs pull them  
apart,'' she said. ``I don't go out to get messed up anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several Florida cities have taken steps to regulate or ban  
raves, including Orlando and Tampa. Some say the efforts have 
merely forced the parties to move to warehouses, homes and other 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they put an all-out ban on these shows, things are going to  
get a lot more dangerous,'' said Jason Donovan, an organizer of the 
Zen Festival in Coconut Grove last month. ``If you try and tell a 
young person not to do something, they're going to want to do it 
even more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 06:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suit Says Marines Jailed Wrong Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Arrested for jumping a commuter train turnstile,  
Martin L. King was shocked to find himself shackled and taken to 
the brig at Camp Lejeune, N.C., charged with deserting the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	King said he told authorities they had the wrong man; he'd never  
been in the military. Still, he was held for 40 days, during which 
he claims he was sexually assaulted by another inmate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a nightmare,'' King said Thursday. ``It basically felt  
like I was being terrorized by the government. That was very, very 
scary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King, 33, is suing the Marines and the U.S. government for  
unspecified damages, alleging he was falsely imprisoned. The suit, 
filed in federal court in Atlanta, is awaiting a trial date. 
</P>
<P>
	According to King's suit, his ordeal began when someone stole  
his Social Security number and used it to enlist in the Marines. 
The unknown man finished basic training in 1992 at Parris Island, 
S.C., then disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in early 1996, King was fired on his first day as a YMCA  
counselor because a background check showed he was wanted for 
desertion. When he went to a Marines recruiting office in Atlanta 
to clear up the error, he said, he was laughed at and sent away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here was an innocent guy who told everybody he possibly could  
that he was innocent, that they had the wrong man,'' said Marc 
Bardack, one of King's lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, King, a former college student, had a  
late-night janitor's job, no money and was living in a shelter. 
That's when he was arrested for jumping the turnstile and sent to 
Camp Lejeune. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marines could have solved the problem quickly by looking at  
their own records, King's lawyers say. The impostor's file 
contained his medical and dental records, fingerprints, 
handwriting, and most importantly, his picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Camp Lejeune released King the day after he told his story to a  
television station. King now lives in Oakland, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Marine Corps officials confirmed King was in the brig at from  
Aug. 23 to Sept. 13, 1996, and declined further comment. A 
spokesman Assistant U.S. Attorney William Traynor also declined 
comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:57:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Says Tax Delay Could Be Costly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service says it must  
spend up to $11.5 million extra to print and mail forms and 
probably will perplex taxpayers because of congressional delays on 
a tax bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to act now to assure timely delivery of tax forms and  
instructions to individuals,'' IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti 
said in a letter to congressional leaders. ``Unfortunately, despite 
our best efforts, some taxpayers still may be confused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of middle-class taxpayers who claim personal credits  
such as the $500 per-child credit could be required to calculate 
both their regular income taxes and alternative minimum taxes 
unless Congress acts to exempt those credits from applying to the 
latter levy. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 1 million of those taxpayers could get hit with  
unexpectedly higher income taxes -- and those numbers will only get 
higher in the future because the alternative minimum tax is not 
indexed for inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax was created in 1969 to ensure the wealthy did not escape  
income taxes through legal loopholes. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-year exemption passed last year has expired. The House and  
Senate are far from agreement on legislation extending the 
exemption -- included in bills that would renew several popular 
business tax breaks -- and President Clinton is threatening to veto 
any tax bill that spends some of the future non-Social Security 
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The morass on Capitol Hill is causing big headaches at the IRS,  
which is preparing tax forms and instructions that assume the 
personal credits exemption for the alternative minimum tax will be 
continued. 
</P>
<P>
	But just in case the exemption lapses, the IRS is prepared to  
print up a 16-page supplement of forms and instructions that would 
be mailed to taxpayers by Jan. 15. A notation explaining the 
situation will be included in the original package and on the IRS 
Internet site. 
</P>
<P>
	If the provision is extended, the IRS may send a follow-up  
postcard to assure taxpayers of that fact. Total cost is estimated 
at between $7.5 million and $11.5 million, Rossotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will do our best to provide help to every taxpayer who  
needs it, given the uncertain legislative situation,'' Rossotti 
said in the letter dated Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	There is broad bipartisan support on Capitol Hill for extending  
the alternative minimum tax fix. But there is disagreement about 
how to pay for it and how long the exemption should last. 
</P>
<P>
	A $23.3 billion bill approved by the House Ways and Means  
Committee would make permanent the fix and extend other expiring 
tax provisions for five years. It has drawn opposition from 
Democrats and a veto threat from Clinton, however, because it would 
spend surplus dollars in four of its five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're for the extenders,'' House Minority Leader Dick  
Gephardt, D-Mo., told reporters Thursday. ``We just think you have 
to pay for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The alternative minimum tax would have been abolished gradually  
by the $792 billion Republican tax cut vetoed by the president in 
September. Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the Ways and Means 
Committee, blamed the higher IRS costs on the administration's 
opposition to using any surplus dollars for both the big tax cut 
and the slimmed-down bill of extensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got that bill out of committee in plenty of time,'' said  
Archer, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Finance Committee, meanwhile, is struggling for a  
bipartisan agreement on a more modest package of tax extensions 
currently estimated at $7.8 billion. A draft of that bill, which 
would be paid for with a variety of revenue raisers, would extend 
the alternative minimum tax fix for two years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:57:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Prosecutor Admits JonBenet Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Prosecutor Alex Hunter says the decision  
not to indict anyone in the murder of JonBenet Ramsey left him with 
``an aching heart,'' and he declared the search for her killer is 
not over. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the girl's parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, have not  
been eliminated from the investigation. Police Chief Mark Beckner 
said the Ramseys remain ``under an umbrella of suspicion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two men spoke on Thursday, a day after Hunter announced that  
a 13-month grand jury investigation into the 1996 slaying did not 
find enough evidence to charge anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Hunter said the four prosecutors and their  
advisers working on the case unanimously agreed there was 
insufficient evidence to warrant charges in the death of the 
6-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
	He refused to discuss the grand jury's investigation, including  
why JonBenet's parents were not called to testify. He also said the 
case is stronger as a result of the grand jury's work, though he 
acknowledged that ``mistakes were made'' in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have an aching heart about where we are with this case, but  
by no means do I or any of the men who you see at this table feel a 
sense of failure,'' said Hunter, flanked by other prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to follow the evidence in this case as long  
as there is work to be done. We find no reason to give up heart, we 
find no reason to quit and we plan to continue with diligence the 
effort we believe has been under way since the beginning of this 
case,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Gov. Bill Owens said a team of attorneys,  
including Attorney General Ken Salazar, will review the case and 
recommend whether a special prosecutor should be named. Owens said 
he would decide within a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Early on Dec. 26, 1996, Mrs. Ramsey told police she found a  
ransom note demanding $118,000 for her daughter's safe return. 
Eight hours later, JonBenet's father said he found his daughter's 
body in the basement. 
</P>
<P>
	Six weeks later, Hunter assembled a dream team of prosecutors  
and advisers, but the investigation soon became bogged down with 
infighting between his office and police. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were accused of mishandling the evidence and allowing too  
many people to have access to the crime scene; Hunter was accused 
of trying to protect JonBenet's wealthy and influential parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter turned the case over to the grand jury in September 1998.  
The grand jurors heard from investigators, the police, Ramsey 
friends and associates, JonBenet's brother Burke and her 
half-siblings. 
</P>
<P>
	After the decision not to charge anyone was announced, the  
Ramseys asked police to continue the investigation to find a 
``child killer'' still on the loose. 
</P>
<P>
	At his own news conference, Beckner said he agreed that ``there  
are things that we should have done differently and wish we would 
have done differently.'' But he added: ``To say that mistakes have 
made this an unsolvable case is not accurate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This case is not dead in the water,'' Beckner said. ``We still  
have things to do, still have evidence that is being processed and 
examined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During morning radio talk shows, angry callers lambasted Hunter,  
demanding to know why no one has been charged in the nearly three 
years since JonBenet was killed. Some defended Hunter and accused 
police of bungling the case and mishandling evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hunter got stuck with a bad case, and so did the grand  
jurors,'' said Emily Brown, who was playing with two children 
outside the Boulder County Justice Center, where the grand jury 
met. ``It upsets me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:57:40 </DATE_TIME>
