<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopefuls John McCain  
and Gary Bauer on Friday accused Vice President Al Gore of 
politicizing the Senate's defeat of the Comprehensive Test Ban 
Treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately after the Senate rejected the treaty Wednesday, Gore  
filmed a campaign ad criticizing the 51-48 vote. President Clinton 
also criticized the Senate's GOP majority for its handling of the 
treaty vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Both McCain, a U.S. senator from Arizona, and Bauer said Gore  
had politicized the treaty's defeat for his own benefit in the race 
for the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who voted against the treaty, said Clinton and Gore were  
wrong to accuse the Senate of ``politicizing national security.'' 
He also said he knew of no effort by Gore to lobby senators to vote 
to ratify the test ban treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a former senator, surely the vice president knows that it  
is best to support a treaty before it is actually voted on,'' 
McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer also said Clinton was trying to use the vote to aide  
Gore's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a desperate attempt to revive Al Gore's floundering  
campaign, Bill Clinton has politicized the Senate's nuclear test 
ban treaty vote,'' Bauer said. ``It is no coincidence that Al Gore 
was filming campaign commercials on the test ban within hours of 
the Senate vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Campaigning in the home state of her  
husband's rival, Tipper Gore told reporters Friday that Bill 
Bradley's strong challenge for the Democratic presidential 
nomination was not a surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore complimented Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New  
Jersey and a native of Crystal City, Mo. But she said she prefers 
to focus on Vice President Al Gore's accomplishments and his 23 
years of service to the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been a very good vice president, doing the business of  
the country,'' Mrs. Gore said after addressing the 48th annual 
convention of the Girl Scouts of the USA. ``He's offering a real 
change that would work for working families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore earlier told the Girl Scouts she fondly remembered her  
scouting days, particularly the projects and camping. 
</P>
<P>
	And she urged the scouts to take personal responsibility, help  
the homeless and get involved in their communities. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican National Committee launched a  
refurbished Web site Friday, which chairman Jim Nicholson said will 
allow ``one-stop shopping'' for anyone interested in the Republican 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The site has been redesigned for easier navigation, daily  
opinion polls of visitors and to provide access to other GOP 
information, such as its weekly ``GOP-TV'' broadcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	The new site also will make it easier for supporters to make  
donations to the RNC. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Delaware's presidential primary next year  
will attract more candidates than magazine publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner, plans to run  
hard in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has had a virtual monopoly on primary campaigning here  
since the state created a primary vote in 1992, but Bush has 
announced he will visit on Nov. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	His appearance is expected to give some relevance to the Feb. 8  
GOP primary, now third in the nation behind Iowa and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush visit also signals the settling of a feud that simmered  
between Delaware and New Hampshire these last two primary seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Delaware's law dictates that its state-run primary fall four  
days after New Hampshire's. But New Hampshire politicians, 
protective of their status as first in the nation, has warned 
candidates not to campaign in Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the last primary, everybody opted out of coming here,  
except for Forbes,'' said W. Laird Stabler Jr., chairman of the 
Bush campaign in Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Bob Dole didn't step foot in Delaware during the 1996  
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, Forbes won.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press Writers Douglas Kiker, Jim Bagby and  
Christopher Thorne contributed to this report. 
  	   	
