<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Wins No Matter What </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	No matter what happens, NBC can't lose.  
</P>
<P>
	The network, which hypes itself as the channel of storytelling,  
has the World Series this season and will have no shortage of tales 
to tell. 
</P>
<P>
	For starters, how about a Subway Series.  
</P>
<P>
	Or the Atlanta Braves return to the city they left 47 years ago  
and face the Boston Red Sox, who look to break ``The Curse'' and 
win their first title since 1918. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe a rematch of the series in 1986 when the New York Mets --  
and Bill Buckner -- ended Boston's chances. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's not even taking into account the most likely scenario  
-- a rematch of the 1996 World Series when the New York Yankees beat 
the Braves in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter who makes it because there's such appealing  
clubs and each has something different to offer,'' said Fox analyst 
Tim McCarver, who did last year's World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarver would have been the ideal person to do this year's  
finale, especially if the Mets get past the Braves and face the 
Yankees. He was fired by the Mets before the season after 16 years 
as the team's analyst and worked Yankees games instead. 
</P>
<P>
	But fans won't hear McCarver once the Series begins. Instead,  
it'll be NBC's Bob Costas and analyst Joe Morgan. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan, who worked an amazing seven games in seven days in seven  
different cities to begin the postseason, has clicked with Costas 
this season after admittedly struggling a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, the duo went into the League Championship Series  
without having worked together all season. Morgan also works for 
ESPN and was used to partner Jon Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an adjustment for me working on both networks,'' Morgan  
said. ``NBC is more traditional baseball while both ESPN and Fox 
have more pizazz and color. Jon and I take more chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ESPN agreed to allow Costas to work two regular-season games  
with Morgan this year as a tuneup to the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	It helped ESPN get a big name for a couple of telecasts -- and it  
benefited NBC, too. The viewers also win because Costas and Morgan 
are in sync, something lacking in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't have to get reacquainted on the air,'' NBC  
producer David Neal said. ``Last year was not an ideal situation. I 
can't overstate the importance of those two games on ESPN. Now Bob 
and Joe have picked right up and we have one of those rare 
situations where you can't miss -- any of the four matchups you get 
are all great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FOOTBALL PUSH:* Even the rash of injuries to NFL stars can't  
stop the ratings from climbing. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN has made the biggest jump, a 27 percent increase from last  
season. Fox is up 11 percent and CBS increased 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' was up 13 percent before the  
Jacksonville Jaguars lackluster win over the New York Jets. But 
that game, going up against Game 5 of the Red Sox game against the 
Indians, fell 38 percent from last year's Packers-Vikings game. 
</P>
<P>
	``MNF'' is still up for the season, but barely -- at 1 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	The pregame shows have also done well. Fox is up 10 percent; CBS  
ahead 5 percent and ESPN up 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LIVE BAIT:* The first live network fishing championship is  
about three weeks away and Fox has made a change. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Buck is in. Terry Bradshaw is out.  
</P>
<P>
	Actually, Bradshaw, who was originally going to be a co-host  
with baseball analyst Bob Brenly, will still do some taped 
segments. However, Brenly and Buck will share the hosting duties. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know nearly as much compared to the guys in this  
competition,'' said Brenly, who took up the sport about 10 years 
ago. ``It's like the weekend softball player going to the Yankees 
game. I'm just a novice fisherman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox decided to scrap the idea of taking Bradshaw away from its  
rating-winning football pregame show for a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Terry figured out fishing is not hand-to-hand combat,'' Brenly  
said. ``Terry would have probably jumped out of the boat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea for the show came from Fox sports president David Hill.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's an avid fisherman and is the inspiration,'' Fox's  
executive producer Ed Goren said of the Nov. 7 telecast. ``This is 
a very complicated technical shoot -- more so than a golf tournament 
where you have to be everywhere. This covers more area and you 
can't cable it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* Fox will forgo commercials in the middle of the  
first inning Saturday when Yankees pitcher Roger Clemens walks in 
from the bullpen against his former team at Fenway Park. ... Former 
Georgetown coach John Thompson has joined Turner Sports as an NBA 
analyst. ... CBS will televise Sports Illustrated's 20th Century 
awards show, with host Bryant Gumbel, Dec. 2 at 9 p.m. ET from 
Madison Square Garden in New York. ... ESPN2 will air a one-hour 
America's Cup 2000 preview Sunday at 2 p.m. ET. ... ESPN's Dan 
Patrick, doing his radio show from ESPN Zone in Manhattan on 
Wednesday, lured Spike Lee into the booth before the moviemaker had 
lunch. ``Boston stinks. They bite,'' Lee yelled. ... NBC's Bill 
Walton on Wilt Chamberlain's death. ``We always thought Wilt was 
immortal. He will live on forever in our hearts and minds. ... He 
had absolutely no regrets. He did more in his one life than anyone 
else could do in a million lifetimes.'' ... CNN-SI will air a 
30-minute segment on Pete Rose on Sunday at 7:30 a.m. ET with 
replays at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. 
  	   	
</P>
