<HEADLINE> Disney's Imagineering Head Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kenneth Wong, head of Walt Disney's famous  
Imagineering division, is leaving the company to pursue 
``independent'' opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Glendale-based Walt Disney Imagineering is, among other things,  
the arm of the Walt Disney Co. that creates all Disney resorts, 
theme parks and real estate developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to pursue his personal interests, and we at Disney  
wish him well,'' Paul Pressler, president of Walt Disney 
Attractions, said in a statement Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time is right for me to explore independent, creative  
endeavors,'' Wong said in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Wong joined Disney in 1991 as senior vice-president for Disney  
Development Company and became head of Imagineering when the 
divisions merged in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	He will remain available as an advisor, Disney said.  
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Sotto, one of Imagineering's top designers, and Jake  
Winebaum, head of Disney's Internet operations, recently left the 
company for Internet ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wong, 44, told the Los Angeles Times that he also is interested  
in the Internet, in combination with ``art, design, technology and 
real estate'' but declined to be specific. He also said he is 
leaving on friendly terms with Pressler. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Wong, the ``Imagineers'' developed Animal Kingdom,  
DisneyQuest, The New Amsterdam Theatre, Times Square Studios, and 
two Disney cruise ships. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, however, Wong scolded the division for embarrassing  
delays in three high-profile projects. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to 2,000 employees, Wong said the division set  
unrealistic schedules because it underestimated the risk of 
problems with the Disney Magic cruise ship, Disneyland's Rocket 
Rods and the Test Track thrill ride at Florida's Walt Disney World. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney also announced several other personnel moves Thursday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
