<HEADLINE> Drug Charge Against Boxer Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Former heavyweight boxing champion  
Tommy Morrison won't lose his Corvette to the impound lot as a 
result of a decision to reduce one of the drug charges pending 
against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Morrison, a former World Boxing Organization champion, was  
arrested last month on numerous drug and driving charges, including 
a felony charge of possession of cocaine with the intent to 
distribute it. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Terry Jones said Thursday that the charge was reduced  
to possession of cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could not be established that he had any intent to  
deliver,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The omission of the intent to deliver allegation saves  
Morrison's 1999 Corvette from being impounded, Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morrison is to be arraigned Monday in Washington County Circuit  
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the cocaine possession charge, Morrison also is charged  
with simultaneous possession of drugs and firearms, being a felon 
in possession of a firearm, possession of drug paraphernalia, 
misdemeanor possession of marijuana and driving while intoxicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Other misdemeanor charges of careless driving and failure to  
provide proof of insurance likely will be handled in Fayetteville 
Municipal Court. A city court clerk said Morrison's file had not 
been received. 
</P>
<P>
	Fayetteville police stopped Morrison's car Sept. 17 after  
noticing him driving erratically. Police said the guns and drugs 
were discovered during a search of the vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 10, Morrison received a two-year suspended sentence for  
drunken driving in Tulsa County, Okla., after pleading guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, a Delaware County, Okla., jury convicted Morrison of  
driving under the influence and other charges related to a 
chain-reaction traffic accident that injured three people. He was 
ordered to spend time in treatment. He also avoided jail time on 
charges of drunken driving and speeding in Kansas in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Morrison became the WBO's heavyweight champion in 1993 by  
defeating George Foreman. He had 40 knockouts during his career, 
the last in 1996 -- just after testing positive for the virus that 
causes AIDS. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
