<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 06:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Fined for Selling Financial Info </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A state judge has ordered a New York information  
broker to pay $500,000 after finding the broker obtained and sold 
private financial information of Massachusetts residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Easton, 45, and his company, Source One Associates of  
Poughquag, N.Y., were ordered to pay the civil penalty by Superior 
Court Judge Gordon Doerfer, the attorney general's office said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge found that Easton and his company had violated the  
state's consumer protection, financial privacy and fair credit 
reporting laws, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Clements, an assistant attorney general who handled the  
case, said similar cases were pending in other states. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really the first time a judge, having heard all the  
evidence, has made it very clear this conduct is illegal,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	When contacted in New York, Easton referred comment to his  
Boston lawyer, Steve O'Malley, who didn't return a telephone 
message Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bench trial in the case lasted one month and ended Sept. 20.  
Doerfer then took it under advisement, issuing his verdict 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This office will not stand for anyone violating the most basic  
financial privacy rights of consumers,'' Attorney General Thomas 
Reilly said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Clements said two ``asset search'' firms, which might be hired,  
for example, by lawyers seeking information about a spouse's assets 
in a divorce case, hired Easton to get information about people's 
bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with the name and Social Security number of a person,  
Easton would check their credit reports and try to identify where 
their accounts were, Clements alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Clements said, Easton would use ``false statements,''  
claiming to be a fellow bank employee or the account holder 
himself, for example, to get information. The judge found at least 
1,000 violations, Clements said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear you can't use false statements and other trickery  
to obtain this information from banks,'' Clements said. ``And it's 
clear that consumers and banks view this information as private and 
it is, in fact, private.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 10:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seinfeld Creator Gets HBO Special </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Larry David, so misunderstood.  
</P>
<P>
	A funny guy? Sure. ``Seinfeld,'' which he co-created and often  
wrote, proved it. So does ``Larry David: Curb Your Enthusiasm,'' 
his HBO special premiering Sunday at 10 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	But what about the accompanying stigma -- that he's  
mega-neurotic, hypersensitive or simply odd? Where does that kind 
of nonsense get started? 
</P>
<P>
	If a recent interview proves anything, Larry David is in fine  
psychic fettle. For example, even after his triumph with 
``Seinfeld,'' there's no swelled head for him. ``I maybe have just 
a little more confidence in my work now,'' he allows, ``but not 
that much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nor has his ``Seinfeld'' payday -- a reported $242 million -- made  
a material difference in his world. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do have thoughts occasionally like, 'Holy cow! I have a  
lot of money!''' he admits. ``But it's not like, 'I must be 
great.''' 
</P>
<P>
	At age 51, David knows exactly who he is: the same as he was a  
long time ago, plus years of experience to seal it. ``I really 
don't think that anything about me has changed since I was, I don't 
know ... 12?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps his biggest life change: the onset of baldness.  
</P>
<P>
	``But I like how I've taken to it,'' he declares with a  
mirthless laugh. ``No toupees. No beard to offset it. I'm quite 
proud of how I've adjusted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I ever did for it was try the Chinese Bald  
Cure. We did an episode about it on the show.'' (That would be 
``Seinfeld'' No. 25, ``The Tape.'') 
</P>
<P>
	``But it actually happened. We asked the guy bringing the  
Chinese food to call China on the phone from my apartment, after we 
tried and couldn't get anybody who spoke English. And the stuff 
came. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's worked great.''  
</P>
<P>
	Consider that last remark an exercise of comic license. And  
expect more on ``Curb Your Enthusiasm.'' David's first brush with 
TV since the May 1998 ``Seinfeld'' finale, this is a very funny 
special about Larry David putting together a Larry David special. 
</P>
<P>
	During ``Curb,'' he kvetches to his manager, frets to his wife,  
stews during meetings at HBO, and wonders why he said OK to cameras 
stalking him to get it all. 
</P>
<P>
	On the program, David is a hybrid form of volatile  
impassiveness, someone capable of juggling stubbornness with 
cautious indecision. Meanwhile, as any ``Seinfeld'' fan would 
expect, he has a tendency to deconstruct life's every passing 
moment. 
</P>
<P>
	After waiting for his manager to get off the phone, David lodges  
a complaint about the office-greeting policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know I'm in the room, how come you don't pick up your head  
and say, 'One second?''' David asks. ``All you have to do is: `One 
second.''' His right hand cradles an invisible receiver. ``When I'm 
on the phone, I go, `One second.' Or you don't have to SAY `One 
second,' just --'' he hoists the index finger of his other hand -- 
``like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beside such telling glimpses, this ``mockumentary'' includes  
insights from David's friends, Jason Alexander, Richard Lewis and, 
of course, Jerry Seinfeld. 
</P>
<P>
	Best of all, it captures him doing stand up for the first time  
in 9 1/2 years (who knew!), seen in snatches from club dates he books 
to steel himself for his big HBO concert. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who do you think has more freedom -- the married men in America  
or the single men in Communist China?'' he asks the room. ``I gotta 
go for the single guy in Communist China, no contest. I'm a married 
guy in America. I can leave the country -- but I can't leave my 
house.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was David's real-life itch to get back onstage that led to  
this ``Curb Your Enthusiasm'' spoof: Somebody suggested he should 
film his practice sets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I very reluctantly said, `Oh ... OK,''' recalls David, sipping  
his nonfat decaf cappuccino. ``That's exactly the way I make up my 
mind to do anything: a reluctant OK. I never go, 'Yeah! Great idea! 
Let's do it!' Never. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I thought, `Well, maybe this needs some narrative around  
the stand up.' It became more and more of a comedy film, and less 
and less of a stand-up film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David says he made seven or eight unannounced appearances at  
clubs in Los Angeles and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	And how did it feel? ``I was as anxious as I was 10 years ago.''  
</P>
<P>
	So why did he want to go back? Among comedy cognoscenti, David  
is as well-known for his hatred of stand up as for his mastery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hated it and loved it, all at the same time,'' he explains.  
``When it goes badly, you have one of two attitudes: either, `Well, 
everyone is stupid, but I'm great,' or, 'People are really smart 
and I stink, I have no talent, what am I doing?' 
</P>
<P>
	``But when it goes well, everyone is brilliant and I'm the  
greatest thing on the planet!'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other words: David doesn't hesitate to assume that the  
consensus of everyone on Earth is reflected by 100 people in a 
comedy club. ``They're a very representative group,'' he insists. 
``A scientific sample.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The funny thing is, he's got proof.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`MARTIAL LAW': Sammo and Terrell scramble to recapture a  
world-renowned thief, Alistair Temple (guest star Joe Bologna), who 
disappears while in police custody, on ``Martial Life.'' Temple is 
abducted by a band of criminals who need him to commit a robbery. 
Although he is uninterested in helping them, he is forced to comply 
when the felons kidnap his granddaughter. Sammo and Terrell must 
decide how to save her and return Temple to jail. ``Martial Law'' 
airs Saturday at 9 p.m. EDT on CBS. Sammo Hung and Arsenio Hall 
star. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
