<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 18:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Hero To Be Sold in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Sea Hero, winner of the 1993 Kentucky  
Derby, will be part of the dispersal of the late Paul Mellon's 
thoroughbreds at the 13-day November Breeding Stock Sale at 
Keeneland. 
</P>
<P>
	A near-record 4,862 horses and two stallion shares are cataloged  
for the sale, which begins Nov. 7 and concludes Nov. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The total number of lots is 65 less than cataloged last year.  
</P>
<P>
	The November sale has become the world's largest thoroughbred  
breeding stock auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The first day will include four major dispersals -- Georgia  
Hofmann and her Wycombe House Stud, Robert and Bea Roberts, 
Mellon's estate and Silverleaf Farms. 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, Satish Sanan, who has become a major influence in  
the thoroughbred industry, will sell 14 horses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanan will sell two mares who are pregnant to A.P. Indy; mares  
in foal to Gone West and Woodman; and weanlings by Sadler's Wells, 
Mr. Prospector and Seeking the Gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lot of quantity in the sale, but we think that  
there is a lot of quality, too,'' said Geoffrey G. Russell, 
Keeneland's assistant director of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are quality mares and quality foals. There's some very  
nice racing prospects and horses currently in training and racing. 
We are very hopeful that the strong market will continue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UPS' Net Income Increases 29 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service reported Friday that its  
net income rose 29 percent during the third quarter, the final 
quarter before the package delivery giant expects to go public. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS said its net income for the quarter ending Sept. 30 was $577  
million or $1.03 per diluted share, compared with $449 million or 
81 cents per share for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The privately held company credited the growing U.S. economy,  
combined with volume growth and higher rates, for the quarterly 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the quarter totaled $6.72 billion, up 9 percent  
from $6.16 billion in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, UPS earnings took a $1.44  
billion hit from a tax assessment that resulted from a court fight 
with the Internal Revenue Service. A federal judge ruled in August 
that UPS set up a Bermuda company to avoid paying income taxes. UPS 
may appeal, but it set the $1.44 billion aside from second-quarter 
earnings to keep the tax assessment from ballooning further with 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-month net income was $222 million or 39 cents per share,  
compared with $1.26 billion or $2.28 per share for the same period 
in 1998. Nine-month revenues were up 8.2 percent, from $18.12 
billion last year to $19.6 billion this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the end of this year, UPS expects to offer about 55  
million shares to the public, using the money to buy out an equal 
number of shares from employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea is to create a pool of publicly held stock that UPS can  
use in acquisitions and other business deals, UPS spokesman Norman 
Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said its international operating profits improved to  
$38 million in the quarter, compared with a loss of $15 million for 
the same period in 1998. Domestic packaging profits rose 16.1 
percent to $879 million from $757 million during the same period 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said a cost-management program the company implemented in  
late 1997 also contributed to the quarterly gains. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 13:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue QB To Face Surging Spartans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- October has been a disappointing  
month for quarterback Drew Brees and Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	That can change Saturday with an upset of undefeated Michigan  
State, which has climbed from unranked in the preseason to No. 5 in 
this week's Associated Press poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Already this month, No. 20 Purdue had a 10-game winning streak  
ended by Michigan in a 38-12 loss, followed by a 25-22 setback at 
Ohio State. Now Brees will be going against a veteran defensive 
unit that limited him to 196 yards passing last year -- his lowest 
total in a game he started. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Brees completed TD tosses of 9 and 6 yards in the final  
5:07 to produce a 25-24 victory. It was the second consecutive year 
Purdue came from 11 points down in the fourth quarter against the 
Spartans to win by a point. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up front they've always got some great players,'' Brees said.  
``Last year even with the absence of Dimitrius Underwood and 
Robaire Smith ... they still had other defensive ends step in and 
play a great game. It seems no matter who their starters are, 
they've always got great depth. Whenever you're good up front, it 
makes it a little bit hard on the quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to get rid of the ball faster, and with the talent  
they have at defensive back and linebacker, even if you had time to 
throw it's still tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5, 269-pound Smith has six sacks this season, triple  
his total from last year. The Spartans have 25 sacks, compared with 
30 all of last season. If defenses try to double-team Smith, 
opponents have to contend with ends Hubert Thompson and Nick Myers, 
who have combined for three sacks and 40 tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys help him tremendously,'' Spartans coach Nick Saban  
said. ``Last year when we flip-flopped our ends with Julian 
Peterson, they would flip-flop the tight end on us all the time and 
run the ball away from Robaire. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't getting the same opportunities to make plays, and I  
think that he is this year. I think it's a compliment to the entire 
front seven that he plays with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Brees will be hoping Purdue solves its problems  
inside an opponent's 20-yard line. The Boilermakers have scored 
touchdowns 46 percent of the time they've gotten inside the 20, 
compared to 58 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably a mental thing. Last year we were so successful,  
that whenever we got inside the red zone we were going to score,'' 
Brees said. ``Now, since we haven't been so successful, I think 
we're willing to settle for field goals. ... In the past there were 
times when we were inside the red zone and we turned the ball over, 
and we were not getting any points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State's Bill Burke threw for a school-record 400 yards  
in Saturday's victory over Michigan, while Plaxico Burress 
accumulated a school-record 255 yards on 10 receptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's doing a great job of making decisions with the  
ball,'' Purdue coach Joe Tiller said. ``Burress and (Gari) Scott 
are the type guys, if you put the ball up in the air they've got a 
better than 50-50 chance they're going to end up with it. That's 
regardless of the type of coverage you have on. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (4-2, 1-2 Big Ten) is averaging 447.3 yards and 33  
points. Michigan State (6-0, 3-0) is averaging 434.2 yards and 35.2 
points. Brees leads the conference by averaging 302.2 yards 
passing, while Burke is third at 218.2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans have allowed 36.7 yards a game rushing and only one  
rushing touchdown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 13:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tells U.N. Torture Rare in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration told a U.N.  
committee Friday there were sporadic instances of brutality in the 
United States, but they were rare and the legal system provided 
punishment for offenders and compensation for victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, prepared by the State and Justice departments, was  
the first in what is likely to be a periodic accounting under a 
1994 international agreement against torture approved that year by 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fully acknowledge in this report there continue to be areas  
of concern, contention and criticism,'' Assistant Secretary of 
State Harold Koh said. ``But we note that torture does not occur in 
the United States except in aberrational situations and never as a 
matter of policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Areas of concern include instances of police abuse, excessive  
use of force, brutality and death of prisoners in custody, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others are overcrowding in prisons, physical and sexual abuse of  
inmates and lack of adequate training and oversight for police and 
prison guards. 
</P>
<P>
	Because capital punishment is legal in the United States, unlike  
in many other Western countries, there was no obligation to report 
on it, Koh said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a thick appendix, the report offered assurances that U.S.  
law provides ``unique protections'' to defendants who are 
confronted with a possible death sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, the report said, in the 38 states that permit death  
sentences most use lethal injections, only one in about 100 
convicted murderers ends up on death row and fewer than 10 percent 
of the sentences are carried out. 
</P>
<P>
	They are meted out to blacks disproportionately, the report  
said. In 1996, for instance, of the 45 men executed 31 were white 
and 13 were black, although blacks comprise 10 percent to 12 
percent of the population. 
</P>
<P>
	``The right to be free from torture is an indelible element of  
the American experience,'' Koh said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, the report said, ``no government can claim a perfect  
record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The beating of motorist Rodney King by four Los Angeles police  
officers in 1991 and the violent treatment recently of Abner 
Louima, a Haitian immigrant, by New York City police were among the 
incidents cited. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, concerns were raised about the use of force by federal  
agents at Ruby Ridge, Idaho, and in Waco, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report assured the U.N. committee that torture is a  
criminal offense, perpetrators are prosecuted and victims are 
entitled to compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the federal government may take civil action against  
police misconduct under a 1994 law. As a result, the Justice 
Department's Civil Rights Division filed lawsuits against the 
Philadelphia and Steubenville, Ohio, police departments. 
</P>
<P>
	This led to consent decrees requiring reforms in the  
supervising, training and disciplining of police officers, as well 
as in investigating complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has contributed more than $12.6 million to the  
U.N. Fund for the Victims of Torture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every unit of government at every level within the United  
States is committed, by law as well as by policy, to the protection 
of the individual's life, liberty and physical integrity,'' the 
report said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 08:03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russian Troops Drive Towards Grozny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian tanks and armored vehicles  
advanced toward the capital of breakaway Chechnya today, and the 
top commander said his troops were readying a decisive offensive 
against the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	A column of about 100 Russian armored vehicles moved deeper  
inside Chechnya from the west, clashing with Chechen fighters near 
the village of Pobedinskoye, some 16 miles west of the capital, 
Grozny. 
</P>
<P>
	Arbi Barayev, a Chechen commander in the area, said his men  
destroyed four of the armored vehicles in combat today. 
</P>
<P>
	As rebels fired from forested hills on Russian tanks below, six  
Russian helicopter gunships pounded their positions. Barayev, his 
head bandaged from a fresh wound, said just two of his men have 
been killed in fighting so far. 
</P>
<P>
	The move toward Grozny today was the first time Russians  
advanced deep inside western Chechnya south of the river. There was 
no indication they would try to enter the city. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian command says it launched its campaign three weeks  
ago to cut off militants who twice invaded neighboring Dagestan in 
August and September. 
</P>
<P>
	Worried about a repeat of the 1994-96 war in which Russian  
troops were routed by a small but determined militant force, Moscow 
has been reluctant to engage the Chechen fighters in street or 
mountain fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Russians have relied on a continuous barrage of air  
and artillery raids. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, the top federal commander in  
Chechnya, said today that his troops had finished creating a 
security zone in the north and will start a second phase Saturday 
to destroy rebels throughout Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	``They must be waiting for us all the time and everywhere, and  
will suffer losses,'' Kazantsev said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Chechen headquarters said its forces shot down an  
Su-25 attack plane Thursday, the third since Russia began bombing 
the region several weeks ago. Russian officials immediately denied 
the claim. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Kazantsev said today that Russian forces had lost three  
aircraft, one of which was shot down by rebels and two of which 
crashed because of equipment failures. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia had previously admitted to losing an Su-24 and an Su-25  
over Chechnya in the first few days of October. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazantsev said the Russian troops in Chechnya have seen 47  
people killed and 33 wounded since Sept. 25. He claimed at least 
1,500 rebels have been killed. Chechen officials said that hundreds 
of Russian soldiers have been killed, and put their own losses at 
just a few dozen. Neither side's claims could be independently 
confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has fanned anger toward Russia within Chechnya,  
with Chechens not associated with the Islamic militants taking up 
arms to fight the Russians. An estimated 170,000 refugees have fled 
the conflict. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0086 </DOCNO>
