<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singer Takes Jab at NYC Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- A little bit of New York City turmoil has  
made it to the heart of blues country. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer-songwriter Jill Sobule of New York wrote and performed a  
song Thursday at the Associated Press Managing Editors conference, 
tweaking Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for his fervent opposition to an 
exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum of Art that includes a painting of 
the Virgin Mary decorated with dung. 
</P>
<P>
	The song, titled ``Call Rudy,'' includes the lyrics: ``Call Rudy  
if your art's a little queer, call Rudy, election year is near. 
Don't call the Whitney, don't call the Met, don't call MoMa, lest 
you forget. You can be a sensation on every news station, lines 
round the block to see your degradation. It's your duty, call 
Rudy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sobule performed the song during an APME panel discussion on  
music censorship. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobule, who scored a hit with her 1995 song ``I Kissed a Girl,''  
says she plans to record ``Call Rudy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 15:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Puts Off Hurricanes' Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- For the second year in a row, a game involving the  
Miami Hurricanes was postponed Friday because of a hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game between No. 24 Miami and Temple was postponed  
until Dec. 4 because Hurricane Irene prevented the Owls from 
arriving for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous disappointment for us not to be able to  
have a home game this weekend,'' Hurricanes athletic director Paul 
Dee said. ``But our first concern is for the safety of our players, 
fans and opponent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Temple planned to fly from Philadelphia to Miami on Friday  
afternoon, but most airlines suspended service to South Florida 
after Irene hit the area with strong winds and more than 16 inches 
of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Miami's past four home games have been threatened by  
hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's Miami-UCLA was postponed from Sept. 26 to Dec. 5  
because of Hurricanes Georges. Miami won 49-45. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Floyd threatened Miami's showdown last month against  
Penn State, but the game was played as scheduled at the Orange 
Bowl. A week later, the Hurricanes' game against East Carolina was 
moved from Greenville, N.C., to Raleigh because of floodwaters 
resulting from Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's postponement means the Hurricanes (2-3) will delay  
their Big East Conference opener until next Saturday, when they 
travel to Boston College. 
</P>
<P>
	Temple (1-5, 1-1 Big East) will play at West Virginia next  
Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 21:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glavine Puts Braves on Brink Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tom Glavine has pitched a lot of big games in  
his career. This one just might be one of the best. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine scattered seven hits in seven scoreless innings to help  
the Atlanta Braves beat the New York Mets 1-0 Friday night and take 
a 3-0 lead in the NL championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's up there,'' Glavine said of where this start ranks among  
the 25 postseason games in his career. ``Obviously the game against 
Cleveland is a better game for different reasons. That game brought 
us a championship. This just brought us one game closer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That game against Cleveland came in 1995, when he allowed one  
hit in eight scoreless innings of a 1-0 victory that clinched 
Atlanta's only World Series title of the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty similar,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``They had more  
hits off him tonight, but I'm not sure he didn't throw harder. He 
was just excellent. He really moved the ball around and changed 
speeds at perfect times and did a super job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After winning his second Cy Young Award last season, Glavine had  
his worst year since 1990 -- the year before Atlanta began its run 
of eight straight postseasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 14-11 with a 4.12 ERA, leading the NL in hits allowed  
and struggling at times with a new strike zone. But he had no 
struggles against the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had an off year,'' he said. ``It was a struggle at times.  
But you have to keep plugging away and hope you can figure it out, 
so when the stretch run comes you can be a factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, was he a factor. The Mets had at least one baserunner in  
every inning, but he was effective enough in the clutch to hold 
them scoreless in seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
	He made an unearned run in the first inning stand up, working  
out of his only two jams to snap a three-game losing streak in the 
NLCS. He struck out eight, including Al Leiter on a pitch below the 
knees to get out of a first-and-third threat in the second inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I ever anticipate having to pitch a shutout,''  
Glavine said. ``I knew Al's been pitching well. I didn't anticipate 
our guys having many opportunities to score runs, so I knew I had 
to limit their opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The success in this year's NLCS contrasts with Glavine's history  
in this round. He lost twice to San Diego, including the decisive 
sixth game, last year and fell in Game 6 in 1997 against Florida to 
end the Braves' season. He was 3-8 with a 3.93 ERA in 12 NLCS 
starts before beating the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	But just like Greg Maddux in Game 1 and Kevin Millwood in the  
second game, the Braves' starting pitching again proved too tough 
for New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets have managed only five runs and 18 hits in three games.  
</P>
<P>
	``These guys are in a category where they are expected to throw  
shutouts every time and it's not humanly possible,'' Cox said. 
``But it's amazing to see what they can do in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even shuffling the lineup couldn't break the slump against  
Glavine. Mets manager Bobby Valentine moved John Olerud from No. 3 
to No. 2 in a switch with Edgardo Alfonzo, and Robin Ventura 
dropped one spot to sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite two singles by Mike Piazza and one by Olerud, the Mets'  
usual 3-4-5 hitters -- Olerud, Piazza and Ventura -- are 4-for-31 
with one RBI in the series. Leadoff hitter Rickey Henderson is 
1-for-10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves always seem to shut down the opposition's big hitters  
in the playoffs, from Barry Bonds and Bobby Bonilla of Pittsburgh 
to Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	After Edgardo Alfonzo and Melvin Mora, none of the other Mets  
picked up the slack. With runners on first and third and two outs 
in the fourth, Glavine got Rey Ordonez on a weak groundout to 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine didn't allow another runner to reach second base.  
</P>
<P>
	``He threw ace after ace for called strikes,'' Valentine said.  
``A couple of guys had good at-bats of him, but they weren't real 
solid at-bats.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
