<DOCNO> APW19991015.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Schedules Earlier Caucuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Ending a fight over the political  
calendar that could reshape future presidential campaigns, Iowa 
officials have decided to move their precinct caucuses to Jan. 24 -- 
one week earlier than had been planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came about after New Hampshire refused repeated appeals  
from Iowa to reschedule its Feb. 1 presidential primary and 
preserve the traditional eight-day grace period between the 
nation's two leadoff political contests. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by Iowa also will renew debate over the national  
political calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republican Chairman Kayne Robinson said officials need to  
find a way to bring stability to the political calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't get a handle on this among the states that are in  
this first-in-the-nation area and have some stability here, yes, we 
will be threatened,'' said Robinson. ``We don't want that 
uncertainty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire officials welcomed the news.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased that Iowa is moving its date back,'' said  
Pamela Walsh, spokeswoman for New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, a 
Democrat. ``We believe it's important to maintain the eight-day 
window ... because it enhances the unique status of both states and 
gives candidates the opportunity to campaign intensely in both 
states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republicans and Democrats use different methods to set  
caucus dates, but work together to have them on the same day. Iowa 
Democrats today won approval from the national party's rules 
committee for the change in date. The panel also approved New 
Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republicans are free to set a date without national party  
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's move comes after days of private discussions about the  
2000 political calendar of primaries and caucuses that yield 
presidential nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa caucuses had been set for Jan. 31, but New Hampshire  
officials unexpectedly scheduled their primary on Feb. 1 and 
refused to push it back to Feb. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa originally set the caucuses for Feb. 21 but gradually moved  
them forward as other states set earlier and earlier primary and 
caucus dates. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly 75 percent of the delegates will be picked by March 7,  
and both parties are virtually certain to have a nominee within six 
weeks of Iowa's opening test. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisiana Republicans had planned their regional caucuses for  
Jan. 28 -- to be first, and a state GOP official said Thursday that 
Iowa's decision will lead them to pick a new date. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa decided it had no choice but to move the caucus date to  
Jan. 24 -- the earliest they have been held since 1980 -- to preserve 
its leadoff status, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a difficult thing and it's a terribly inconvenient  
thing,'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, it's a massive logistical chore.  
</P>
<P>
	Each party will have to find more than 2,000 caucus sites across  
the state. They also will have to reshuffle the logistics of 
totaling the votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, Iowa's political leaders concluded that holding  
the caucuses on the eve of the New Hampshire primary likely would 
dilute their impact and jeopardize their role in the presidential 
selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight between Iowa and New Hampshire also is certain to  
spark a review of the lineup for the next presidential election. In 
past election cycles the two states have banded together to fend 
off challenges from other states seeking some of the attention paid 
to states that open the nomination process. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
