<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Blames Clinton for Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *PAUL CHAVEZ   	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve  
Forbes on Friday blamed President Clinton and Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan for the current turbulence on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their misguided policies are putting the American economy at  
risk,'' he said during a campaign trip to Los Angeles. ``High 
taxes, high interest rates, more big government spending and 
busting the spending caps is a recipe for a serious economic 
slowdown. The first to get hurt will be families, farmers, young 
people and minorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes commented after the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped  
266.90 points Friday to close at 10,019.71, its worst finish since 
early April and its biggest point drop in more than a year. The 
biggest jump in wholesale prices in nine years and new worries by 
Greenspan about the sky-high stock prices apparently jolted the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes told about 350 people at a Los Angeles Rotary Club  
luncheon that climbing interest rates, Washington's failure to cut 
taxes and declining consumer confidence are jeopardizing the 
pensions and retirement plans of working families. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Federal Reserve and the White House ``are ruining a  
good thing or at least discombobulating it. I hope they see the 
error in their ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also cited the Gettysburg Address' call for a ``new birth  
of freedom,'' saying the United States could reach its potential if 
Americans have ``freedom of choice'' in matters ranging from 
education to taxes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
