<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 19:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Health Officials Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- California health officials should have  
released a study showing higher-than-normal lung cancer rates among 
residents living near a Rocketdyne Propulsion and Power laboratory, 
investigators said in a report released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by the state Environmental Protection Agency also  
faulted the Department of Health Services for failing to launch a 
new study to learn the cause of the cancer, or at least explain to 
the public why further study was not needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis ordered the state EPA to investigate the  
department last May after a lawmaker accused Health Services 
personnel of suppressing the 1997 survey of cancer rates. The 
survey found that the rate of cancer in neighborhoods around 
Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Field Laboratory were 17 percent higher 
than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's parent, the Health and Human Services Agency,  
is studying the report and its recommendations, which include 
establishing clear guidelines for followup study and requiring that 
all cancer incidence research be released to the public and to 
other researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report does point out that some poor decisions were made,  
but no guidelines or statutes were violated,'' said Anita Gore, a 
spokeswoman for Health and Human Services. ``It provides a series 
of recommendations that at first blush appear to be reasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Rocketdyne spokeswoman did not return a call for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Rocketdyne International Corp. ran 10 nuclear reactors at its  
Santa Susana Field Laboratory, 50 miles northwest of Los Angeles 
along the Ventura and Los Angeles county line, from the 1950s to 
the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigators' report said there appears to have been no  
deliberate effort to suppress the 1997 study. Two researchers who 
received the report did not feel the 17 percent spike was 
``significant or unusual,'' investigators wrote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
