<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Vasco Advances in Hoops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Rogerio Klafke scored 21 points to lead  
Brazil's Vasco da Gama to a ragged 92-86 overtime upset of European 
champion Zalgiris Kaunas on Friday, putting a South American club 
in the McDonald's Championship final for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Klafke had just two points at halftime, but hit a 3-point shot  
in the final minute of regulation and another in the extra period. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brazil, Klafke is considered the heir to retired superstar  
Oscar Schmidt, who torched the United States for 46 points in a 
120-115 Brazilian victory in the 1987 Pan American Games at 
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	American guard Charles Byrd played 51 of a possible 53 minutes  
for Vasco da Gama and contributed 18 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA champion San Antonio Spurs faced Italian League titlist  
Varese in Friday's second semifinal game. 
</P>
<P>
	The title game of this unofficial world club championship is  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, the final is not going to be America vs. Europe,'' said  
Vasco da Gama center Jose Vargas, who had 19 points and nine 
rebounds. ``How do you like that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zalgiris Kaunas led Vasco da Gama by as many as 12 points in the  
second half, but fell apart late with turnovers and poor foul 
shooting. The Lithuanian club got little help from 7-foot-1 
Eurelijus Zukauskas, whose NBA rights are held by the Milwaukee 
Bucks. Zukauskas managed just six points and two rebounds before 
fouling out with 6:37 left in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't the only player who played poorly.  
</P>
<P>
	Zalgiris Kaunas shot 38.3 percent for the game, while Vasco Da  
Gama hit 44.9 percent of its shots. The 152 points at the end of 
regulation represents the lowest combined total for a McDonald's 
game. Spain's Real Madrid and Germany's Bayer Leverkusen combined 
for 160 in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The second semifinal gave Varese guard Andrea Meneghin a chance  
to do something his father wasn't able to: share the basketball 
court with NBA players. 
</P>
<P>
	Meneghin failed to land a spot with the Toronto Raptors after a  
three-day tryout with the NBA team in August. His father, Dino, 
generally considered the finest Italian basketball player ever, had 
a similar opportunity turn out the same way with the New York 
Knicks 25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it caps a long-term dream,'' the younger Meneghin said  
Thursday, when Varese beat Asian champions C.S. Sagesse of Lebanon 
98-88 to advance. ``When I was little, I always thought about 
playing in the NBA, and now I have a chance to see what that would 
be like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meneghin, 25, had a sub-par game Thursday, scoring just four  
points in the first half before finishing with 12. But he did hit 
two 3-pointers during a 14-2 run that decided the game in the third 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't feel like all eyes are on me, like this is another  
test for me,'' the 6-foot-7, 216-pound guard said. ``I had my 
chance this summer, and I tried. It just didn't work out at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs, who received a first-round bye, were trying to extend  
the NBA's 16-0 record in the 12-year history of the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``Honestly, what they do doesn't matter,'' said Spurs guard  
Antonio Daniels, who attended Varese's victory over C.S. Sagesse. 
``It's all about us and how we play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
