<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 01:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Fire Ready To Defend MLS Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- All year, Chicago Fire coach Bob  
Bradley has been waiting to see a little attitude from his players. 
</P>
<P>
	No, he doesn't want them partying and hanging out with rock  
stars. This isn't Manchester United. But a little of that hunger, 
that feistiness, that, well, fire Chicago showed in its improbable 
run to the MLS title last year would be nice. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with the playoffs beginning Saturday, Bradley is liking  
what he sees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been easy for this team to go off track because  
nothing has come easy,'' he said Thursday. ``I believe it's taken 
all year to get to that point, but yes, now we have the same hunger 
we had last year to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still believe we're a team that can win the championship.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Fire (18-14) begin their defense of the title they won their  
first year with a conference semifinal matchup against the Dallas 
Burn (19-13), a best-of-three series that begins Saturday night in 
Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Rapids (20-12) play the Los Angeles Galaxy (20-12)  
in the other Western Conference semifinal. In the Eastern 
Conference, it's two-time champion D.C. United (23-9) against the 
Miami Fusion (13-19), and the Columbus Crew (19-13) vs. the Tampa 
Bay Mutiny (14-18). 
</P>
<P>
	Winners of the conference finals will meet Nov. 21 in the MLS  
Cup at Foxboro Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling, walking on the stage and holding up that  
trophy, celebrating in the locker room,'' said Frank Klopas, one of 
the Fire's veteran members. ``Last year was last year, but that 
feeling comes back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perfect timing, too. The regular season wasn't exactly how the  
Fire wanted to defend its title. They fell to third place in the 
MLS Western Conference when Dallas won its final game last weekend. 
They had a tough loss in the CONCACAF Champions Cup, and they were 
beaten by an A-League team, the Rochester Raging Rhinos, in the 
U.S. Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	They lost five of their eight shootouts, including one to the  
Burn in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The season took a toll physically, too. Josh Wolff, the No. 2  
scorer with 10 goals and one of the team's top young players, is 
out with a torn ligament in his left knee. Midfielders Diego 
Gutierrez and Jesse Marsch and defenders Francis Okaroh and Tommy 
Soehn are ailing, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of things that could have brought us down, but  
we got through them,'' said forward Ante Razov, whose 14 goals led 
the Fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, everything starts over. And even though Dallas and Los  
Angeles have better records, the Fire have something no other team 
but D.C. United has. They've been there, done that and took home 
several free T-shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always harder to repeat, but the positive thing is we've  
been through it,'' Klopas said. ``We realize how hard we worked 
last year and the demands and sacrifices we had to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to have that same hunger and attitude we had last  
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Getting by Dallas won't be easy. The Burn ended the regular  
season strong, winning their last five games and eight of the last 
nine. Dallas and Chicago split four games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Jason Kreis had an MVP-like season, leading the league  
with 18 goals and 15 assists. He won player of the week honors for 
a second straight week after scoring the game-winner in Dallas' 
last game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're expecting some tough games,'' Razov said. ``But if we do  
the things we're capable of and the things we do well, I don't see 
why we can't get to Foxboro and win it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we're on a roll, we're hard to stop.''  
</P>
<P>
	Now that's positive attitude.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
