<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 279.57 at 10,007.05 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials briefly plunged below 10,000  
today as stocks tumbled amid news of a spurt in inflation and 
another warning about market exuberance by Federal Reserve Chairman 
Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	With about an hour left to the session, the Dow was down 279.57  
at 10,007.05. Moments later, the barometer of 30 major companies 
dipped below 10,000 for the first time since April, slipping to 
9,998.18. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop yanked the Dow's gain for the year below 10 percent and  
put the average about 1,300 points below its Aug. 25 closing high 
of 11,326.04, when the Dow was up more than 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also suffered heavy damage. The Nasdaq  
composite index was down 87.59 at 2,719.25, and the Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500-stock index was down 38.14 at 1,245.28. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff followed a morning report that revealed prices at  
the wholesale level spiked 1.1 percent in September, the largest 
increase in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures  
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was much worse 
than expected. Many analysts were anticipating that prices would 
rise 0.5 percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in a speech to bankers Thursday night, Greenspan  
issued his latest call for investor sobriety at a time of robust 
economic expansion and roaring stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Both developments aggravated market fears that the Federal  
Reserve will raise interest rates for the third time this year in a 
bid to fight inflation by slowing the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	This afternoon, in a prepared speech on the Year 2000 date  
change, Greenspan made no mention of today's inflation report or 
the overall financial backdrop. Fed policy makers hold their next 
meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, which could see demand for loans hurt by  
rising interest rates, led today's decline. Among the Dow's 30 
components, American Express was down 7 at 135, and J.P. Morgan was 
down 4 3/32 at 93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the day's downward trend, Sun Microsystems surged 4 3/32  
to 93 3/4 in Nasdaq trading after the maker of powerful business 
computers posted better than expected profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumber advancers by nearly a 4-to-1 margin  
overall. Trading eased from the morning's hectic pace, with 696.19 
million shares changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange, down 
from 715.12 million at the same point on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 5.00 at  
414.31. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets also took a big hit today. In Europe, Britain's  
FT-SE 100 fell 2.2 percent, Germany's DAX index fell 0.7 percent 
percent and France's CAC-40 fell 1.3 percent. Japan's Nikkei stock 
average fell 1.0 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
