<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Banks More Than $10 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley held a slight  
fund-raising lead over Vice President Al Gore over the last three 
months, with both Democrats taking in more than $7 million during 
the period. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republican front-runner George W. Bush continued to surpass  
the rest of the fund-raising field, taking in $20.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley had more money in the bank at the end of September than  
Gore did, $10.7 million to $10.3 million. Bush had a larger bank 
account than both Democrats put together, $37.7 million as of Sept. 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports filed with the Federal Election Commission today show  
that Bradley took in $7.4 million between July 1 and Sept. 30, as 
compared with $7.3 million for Gore. Bradley had $10.7 million in 
the bank as of Sept, 30, while Gore had $10.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	To date, Gore raised $24.9 million to Bradley's $18.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased with our fund-raising efforts so far,''  
Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said. ``With the matching 
funds and the number of low-dollar donors, we're very close to 
completing the fund-raising portion of the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's average donation was $187, while Bradley's was $334. In  
addition, the former senator reported raising more than $472,000 
from his campaign web site over the last three months, bringing his 
Internet fund-raising total to more than $772,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The steady growth in fund-raising support we have received,  
particularly through our direct mail program and our web site, is 
indicative of the increasing enthusiasm we are seeing at the 
grassroots level across the country,'' said Bradley campaign 
chairman Douglas Berman. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has raised more than $57 million, more than any  
presidential candidate has ever had to spend on a campaign for the 
White House. His average contribution was $386. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am honored that so many Americans are supporting my message  
of rebuilding the military, modernizing Social Security and 
Medicare, improving America's public schools and cutting taxes,'' 
Bush said today. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, Sen. John McCain of Arizona was a  
distant second, raising $3 million during the last three months to 
bring his total to $9.4 million. That includes $2 million 
transferred from his Senate campaign account. He had $2.1 million 
in the bank as of Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The McCain campaign took in $64,000 over the Internet during the  
last four days of September, after sending out an e-mail seeking 
last-minute contributions. ``We must continue the momentum we have 
shown in the press and the polls by showing continued fund-raising 
strength,'' McCain wrote in the e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans Gary Bauer, Patrick Buchanan, Elizabeth Dole, Steve  
Forbes and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah each raised more than $1 
million from July to September. Alan Keyes raised $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who is largely financing his own campaign, raised an  
estimated $1.4 million over the last three months, bringing his 
total to $4.2 million through Sept. 30. In addition, Forbes spent 
about $15 million from his own pocket. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
