<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Helps Gore on Animal Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration took steps this  
week to minimize animal testing after animal rights protesters 
demanding the change had dogged Al Gore's presidential campaign 
since July. 
</P>
<P>
	The Environmental Administration Agency sent a letter Thursday  
to 900 corporations saying, among other things, that no animal 
experiments should be performed when other test methods are 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	It also called for a delay in the testing of several chemicals  
while new methods are developed and said federal funds will be 
dedicated to finding more alternative testing methods. The letter 
was released Friday by the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've taken a number of steps, including clarifying that  
certain tests that animal rights groups were concerned about will 
not be performed, approving other valid tests that don't inlcude 
animal testing, and encouraging companies involved in this program 
to minimize tests on animals,'' said EPA spokesman David Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
	People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals had run TV and  
newspaper ads accusing Vice President Gore of supporting the EPA 
program that tests the toxicity of chemicals on animals. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also deployed a man in a bunny suit to trail Gore on  
his campaign travels. 
</P>
<P>
	PETA said the change would save the lives of as many as 800,000  
animals. It also issued a statement saying it had ``agreed to call 
off its national grass-roots campaign against the vice 
president....'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Gore referred queries to the EPA.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
