<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Tourists Telling Tall Tales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the city of a million scams, police say  
tourists are finally taking their turn by spinning tales of 
muggings that never happened in a bid to collect travel insurance 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Phony victims ``give us a Hollywood version,'' explained Capt.  
James O'Neill of the New York Police Department's Central Park 
Precinct. ``Something corny, like the perp said, `Stick 'em up.' 
Nobody says that anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police say they've heard tall tales from visitors from England,  
Germany, Japan, Australia and the United States. Tourists seem to 
believe the 840-acre Central Park is akin to the Wild West, and a 
few are determined to cash in. 
</P>
<P>
	Police know of 10 tourists who've filed false mugging reports  
this year in the park, along with six New Yorkers. Filing a false 
report can cost $500 to $1,000 in fines and jail time of 60 days to 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We arrested a man from Wales in March, and he said it was a  
well-known fact in Wales that you can report a robbery in Central 
Park and no one would question you because so many robberies happen 
here,'' O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wrong on both counts.  
</P>
<P>
	Crime is down 30 percent this year in the park. As of Oct. 10,  
there were 53 robberies there this year, compared with 66 to the 
same time last year. The Central Park Conservancy says 20 million 
people visit the park annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are used to separating fact from fiction.  
Sometimes, the stories take on Indiana Jones proportions. A few 
favorites around the precinct: 
</P>
<P>
	--The armed-to-the-teeth tale: ``One guy from England said he was  
robbed by three men, and one guy had a knife in his belt, up his 
arm and up another sleeve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--The ``robbers on Rollerblades ruse,'' involving two purported  
victims and three scofflaw skaters. 
</P>
<P>
	--The ``robbed in broad daylight surrounded by hundreds of  
people'' scenario. (This one really had cops rolling their eyes.) 
</P>
<P>
	European insurance companies have cracked down on travel  
insurance fraud, said Suzanne Moore, spokesperson for the 
Association of British Insurers. Travel insurance fraud costs Great 
Britain 50 million pounds a year -- about $82.5 million in U.S. 
currency, Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Often, the ``victims'' claim that some time has lapsed since the  
purported crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``They come in and say they're leaving that night to go back  
home and all they need is the complaint number for the insurance 
company,'' O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Often, he said, they crumble under questioning.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some people plan it before they get here,'' he said. ``Others  
say they spent too much money here and wanted to get some back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 09:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Arena Has Widespread Faults </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Construction problems on a new  
civic arena are more widespread than initially thought, as tests on 
10 additional beams found that all had flaws. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the faults with the arena's upper deck supports, Arena  
board chairman Bob Russell remained confident today that the Alltel 
Arena will open safely for an Oct. 23 Arkansas RiverBlades East 
Coast Hockey League game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are most concerned with safety and solutions,'' Russell  
said at a news conference. ``I have RiverBlade hockey tickets for 
the 23rd and my family and I will be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The building was scheduled to open Tuesday night with an NBA  
exhibition game between Washington and the Los Angeles Lakers. But 
the board opted to cancel the game when engineers said they had 
questions about beams supporting the upper deck. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety questions about the $80 million arena originated when  
workers discovered a crack in one of the beams about a month ago. 
After chipping away some of the cement, engineers discovered that 
metal reinforcement bars within the beam were 12 inches lower than 
intended. 
</P>
<P>
	The rods' poor placement made the beam less able to withstand  
stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers using a high-tech imaging system worked overnight to  
look inside the beams and found problems in all 10 tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell said all 10 of the beams had reinforcement rods lower  
than they were supposed to be, though none were as badly off as the 
cracked beam that forced the arena to cancel the NBA game. 
</P>
<P>
	Arena officials said Thursday that any additional problems could  
be quickly fixed, likely by using metal support posts, which was 
done Tuesday with the cracked beam. 
</P>
<P>
	A preferred but more lengthy solution would be to place a  
carbon-fiber wrap around the beams, similar to what is done in 
buildings in earthquake zones. 
</P>
<P>
	A post would obstruct the view of the arena floor while a  
carbon-fiber wrap would not. 
</P>
<P>
	The arena was funded in part by taxpayer dollars after a  
temporary one-cent sales tax was approved in 1995. The state 
chipped in $20 million and private sources contributed $17 million, 
including $7 million from Alltel to put its name on the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Arena general manager Michael Marion said about 1,000  
ticketholders got refunds for the canceled Lakers-Wizards game on 
Thursday, the first day refunds were available. He said he still 
trying is to reschedule the game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goodyear's Gadsden Plant Plan OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) -- Union workers at Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber  
Co.'s plant here approved a plan to continue making light truck 
tires, saving at least hundreds of jobs, rather than end production 
in December as earlier planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by United Steelworkers members in voting this week  
was announced by Goodyear in a news release Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear officials said union members voted 655-210 to continue  
making tires with a scaled-back workforce and other changes sought 
by the company, which in February had announced it would cease tire 
production in Gadsden and lay off some 1,320 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the company nor the union would say how many employees  
might be retained or how long tire production would continue if 
union members accepted the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Tire operations at the Gadsden plant had been scheduled to shut  
down in December, with no more than a couple of hundred employees 
to be kept on to mix rubber compounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Already about 1,050 people have been laid off from the plant,  
with another 700 still on the job making tires. Of those who lost 
their jobs in Gadsden, 365 have gone to work in other Goodyear 
factories. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal for continued tire production emerged from a series  
of meetings between union leaders and the company. Goodyear said it 
was considering maintaining production at the plant because of 
higher-than-anticipated tire demand. It said the new plan would 
also make the factory more efficient and competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	Last February, the company said the Gadsden plant was one of its  
oldest and most inefficient factories. Opened in 1929, it was the 
first major tire factory to be built in the South and, prior to 
cuts in its workforce, the driving economic force in this city of 
some 43,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mickey Williams, president of USWA Local 12, had said the new  
proposal ``would be good for our membership if they want to 
continue building tires in Gadsden.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 00:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plummer: I'm Playing Against 'Skins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- With help from an injection to numb the  
pain, Jake Plummer expects to play against the Washington Redskins 
on Sunday night despite a hip pointer that has kept him out of 
practice this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not big on using pain-killers, but with the importance of  
this game, us going into the bye week with an even record is very 
important for us, and that's something I want to do,'' the Arizona 
Cardinals' quarterback said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be able to play Sunday, because I think it helps the  
team's chances. Right now, I think with the pain-killer I will be 
able to play,'' Plummer said. ``I came back in the game last 
weekend after taking the pain-killer, and the pain went away in my 
hip, so I know that the pain-killer does work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer was hurt when he was tackled while scrambling early in  
the third quarter of last Sunday's 14-3 victory over the New York 
Giants. Sandwiched between two defenders, he hurt his hip and ribs. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury came just as he finally was recovering from a  
sprained right thumb that severely limited his practice time since 
the preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've played a lot of football and until now I've been  
injury-free,'' Plummer said. ``These things are going to happen in 
the sport we're in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer said the injury affects him whenever he tries to throw  
with any authority. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hips, that's where you make your money throwing the  
ball,'' Plummer said. ``You get the torque and you get the twisting 
and the motion there. It's all generated from that left hip, the 
one that leads, and that's the one that's hurting me now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can stand and throw it 15 or 20 yards, but that's when I'm  
standing flat-footed. If I step into it, that's where I feel a 
little pain. We'll just have to keep getting treatment on it, and 
by Sunday hopefully it goes away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants game was Plummer's best of the season. After throwing  
13 interceptions and two touchdowns in his first four games, he 
completed 13 of 19 for 156 yards and a touchdown in a little more 
than one half of play. He did not throw an interception. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Vince Tobin said Plummer seems to be feeling better each  
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He missed two very valuable days of practice, which you don't  
like to see, but sometimes that happens, because the objective is 
to get him healthy enough to play on Sunday,'' Tobin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer might have his favorite target, wide receiver Rob Moore,  
who missed the last two games with a strained hamstring. Moore 
participated in part of Thursday's practice. 
</P>
<P>
	However, cornerback Tommy Knight sprained his left ankle. Knight  
was the projected starter because Corey Chavous has a sprained 
knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be OK,'' said Knight, bothered by injuries  
throughout his NFL career. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive ends Simeon Rice and Andre Wadsworth also sat out the  
practice -- Rice with a bruised thigh and Wadsworth with a sore toe 
-- but both are expected to play Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Cardinals said defensive tackle Mark Smith has  
told them that noted knee specialist Dr. Richard Steadman will 
perform arthroscopic surgery on Smith's right knee. The surgery 
won't be done until Oct. 25, because Steadman isn't available until 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	Steadman performed the second surgery on Eric Swann's arthritic  
right knee last year after Swann was dissatisfied with the results 
of his first surgery, done by team doctor Russell Chick. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
