<HEADLINE> Cardinals Sign Minor Leaguers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Cardinals signed right-hander  
Mike James and outfielder Steve Bieser to minor league contracts 
Friday and rehired a former general manager as a scout. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals said James and Bieser would be invited to next  
year's spring training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Bing Devine, who was general manager from 1958-64 and 1968-78,  
also rejoined the team Friday as special assignment scout. Devine 
was responsible for the Cardinals acquring Lou Brock in a 1964 
trade with the Chicago Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Devine most recently worked as a scout for the Houston Astros  
and Philadelphia Phillies. He also has held top executive posts 
with the New York Mets and the St. Louis Cardinals football team. 
</P>
<P>
	Devine will be responsible for scouting spring training games,  
National League clubs and the Cardinals' minor league system. He 
will report to general manager Walt Jocketty. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Burris, who pitched for the Cardinals in 1986, also was  
hired as a scout/minor league pitching instructor. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Cardinals sent six players outright to their  
Triple-A Memphis team, right-handers Mike Busby, Larry Luebbers, 
Curtis King and Clint Sodowsky; catcher Marcus Jensen; and first 
baseman-outfielder Eduardo Perez. 
</P>
<P>
	James, 32, missed most of this season, recovering from surgery  
on his right elbow and shoulder. He played eight games with the 
Anaheim Angels' Triple-A team in Edmonton, then worked out with the 
Cardinals in late September. 
</P>
<P>
	James is 13-10 with a 3.52 ERA in 184 career games with the  
Angels. He led the club with 81 games pitched in 1996, the 
third-highest total in Angels' history. 
</P>
<P>
	Bieser, 32, played for the Mets (1997) and Pittsburgh Pirates  
(1998). He split time last year between Triple-A Nashville and 
Memphis and Double-A Altoona. Bieser hit .264 with 42 RBIs and 
eight home runs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
