<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 17:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plot Leader Gets 11 Years in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Calling terrorism ``evil and ungodly,'' a man  
once characterized by prosecutors as the architect of plots to kill 
Egypt's president and blow up the United Nations was sentenced 
Friday to 11 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Siddig Ibrahim Siddig Ali said he was ``arrogant, immature and  
foolish'' in 1993 when he designed the plots and discussed them 
with a government informant who was secretly taping the 
conversations. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Michael Mukasey credited Siddig Ali with  
providing intelligence information to the United States that ``to a 
certain degree made up for what you did and helped the government 
not only in this case but perhaps to prevent future cases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Siddig Ali of Jersey City, N.J., had pleaded guilty shortly  
after the start of a 1995 trial of Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman and 
others in a plot to blow up New York City landmarks and assassinate 
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
<P>
	In pleading guilty to all charges against him including  
seditious conspiracy, Siddig Ali, 38, said the blind sheik had 
given him a fatwa, or religious edict, to kill Mubarak and bomb the 
landmarks. 
</P>
<P>
	He and other Islamic militants then plotted to blow up the  
United Nations, two tunnels and a bridge connecting New Jersey to 
Manhattan and FBI headquarters in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The attacks were to take place just months after the Feb. 26,  
1993 World Trade Center bombing that killed six people and injured 
more than 1,000 others. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to extend my sincere apologies to the people of  
New York, to the American people for my actions,'' Siddig Ali said. 
``My actions in no way reflect the peaceful spirit of Islam nor do 
they reflect the majority of decent and peace-loving Muslims around 
the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I know now more than ever that only through peaceful dialogue  
can we resolve our differences. Terrorism is evil and ungodly,'' 
Siddig Ali said. 
</P>
<P>
	A transcript of the sentencing, which was conducted secretly by  
lawyers and Mukasey, was released late in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the sentence ``balances the enormity of what you  
did and intended to do against the substantial cooperation you 
provided.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Siddig Ali did not testify at the trial of the sheik,  
the cleric was convicted of conspiracy and sentenced to life in 
prison without parole. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
