<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 158.62; Nasdaq Down 55.73 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks tumbled today, nearly sending the Dow  
Jones industrial average below 10,000, amid news of a spurt in 
inflation and a warning by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
against excessive optimism by investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow was off 158.62 at  
10,127.99, partially recovered from an early 241-point plunge. 
Still, the drop pushed the Dow to the lowest level since April and 
about 1,200 points below the Aug. 25 closing record of 11,326.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also bounced from their morning lows,  
but continued to hold sharp losses for the day. The 
technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index was down 55.73 at 
2,751.11 after halving an early 102-point plunge. The Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500-stock index was down 22.67 at 1,260.75. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff followed a morning report that prices at the  
wholesale level spiked 1.1 percent in September, the largest 
increase in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures  
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was much worse 
than expected. Many analysts were anticipating that prices would 
rise 0.5 percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in a speech to bankers Thursday night, Greenspan  
issued his latest call for investor sobriety at a time of robust 
economic expansion and roaring stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Both developments aggravated market fears that the Federal  
Reserve will raise interest rates for the third time this year in a 
bid to fight inflation by slowing the economy. The central bank's 
policy makers hold their next meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, which could see demand for loans hurt by  
rising interest rates, led today's decline. Among the Dow's 30 
components, American Express was down 4 3/4 at 137 1/4, and J.P. Morgan 
was down 3 at 107 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the day's downward trend, Sun Microsystems surged 4  
23/32 to 94 1/8 in active Nasdaq trading after the maker of powerful 
business computers posted better than expected profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumber advancers by more than a 3-to-1  
margin overall. Trading was heavy, with 426.52 million shares 
changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange, up from 393.49 
million at the same point on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets also took a big hit today. In Europe, Britain's  
FT-SE 100 fell 2.2 percent, Germany's DAX index fell 0.7 percent 
percent and France's CAC-40 fell 1.29 percent. Earlier, Japan's 
Nikkei stock average fell 1.0 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
