<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 15:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force at Crossroads Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- Through five games last season,  
Air Force had a 4-1 record and, with some difficult opponents 
remaining, was poised to either fashion a standout season or slouch 
toward mediocrity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons chose the former, winning their next eight games,  
including a bowl victory over Washington, in a glittering 12-1 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	They're in precisely the same position this year. And with a  
Saturday night game against Utah and, after an off week, another 
toughie against BYU, the Falcons face a crossroads. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is in a place now where it really needs to make up  
its mind which direction it's going to go,'' coach Fisher DeBerry 
said. ``We've got the potential to be a fine football team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a lot of adversity, just like the Utah team has had.  
We don't have our quarterback. We've lost several guys who were 
proven players for the season, just like Utah has. Every team has 
that type of adversity. Players have to step up whenever they get 
an opportunity and elevate their level of play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Cale Bonds sprained his right ankle early in the San  
Diego State game two weeks ago and missed a 19-14 victory over Navy 
last week. Backup Mike Thiessen bolted 53 yards for a third-quarter 
touchdown to help spark the victory against Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBerry believes Bonds is ready to return but insists he must be  
``100 percent to play in such an important game like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah also faces some quarterback uncertainty.  
</P>
<P>
	In the second quarter of a 42-0 romp over Louisiana-Monroe last  
week, starting quarterback Darnell Arceneaux re-injured the foot he 
sprained the previous week. His availability on Saturday night 
probably will be a game-time decision. T.D. Croshaw replaced him 
and completed 9-of-17 passes for 166 yards and four touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah and Air Force have played some classic games in the past,  
but because of the overinflated, 16-team Western Athletic 
Conference and resulting realignment, the teams didn't meet in 
1996, 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	That was one of the factors in Utah, Air Force and six other  
schools breaking away from the WAC to form the Mountain West 
Conference, ensuring the survival of such rivalries. 
</P>
<P>
	Their last two meetings have been memorable.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1994 at Falcon Stadium, Air Force rallied from a 17-0 deficit  
behind quarterback Beau Morgan, who was making his first career 
start, to beat the 12th-ranked Utes 40-33. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995 in Salt Lake City, Utah rallied in the final minute,  
scoring 15 points in 10 seconds to upset Air Force 22-21. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some unbelievable games with them,'' DeBerry said.  
``It's always been very, very competitive. I think it's going to be 
a great football game. It always is when Utah and Air Force play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah coach Ron McBride recalls the most recent meeting as being  
``kind of a dull game'' until the closing minutes. ``They kind of 
had it under control, then we made a couple of huge plays: the 
onside kick and then (receiver Kevin) Dyson going down the sideline 
(on a 50-yard touchdown play). All of a sudden we just took the 
game. That was a pretty interesting finish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not having played since 1995 is a problem for the Utes more than  
it is for the Falcons, McBride insisted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest problem we have is we haven't seen it (AFA's  
wishbone offense) for a few years,'' McBride said. ``When you see 
it every year, you have your package and you go up and you're ready 
to play. Your players kind of get into the rhythm. The recall is 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't seen it for a couple of years. To simulate the  
speed of it and make sure your (defensive) package is correct is 
difficult the first time around. In practice, it's hard to get the 
speed down of what they run. Ideally, you'd like to have a bye week 
before you play Air Force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah, also 4-1 overall, is 1-0 in the conference, having downed  
UNLV 52-14 three weeks ago. Air Force is 1-1. The Falcons bowed to 
Wyoming 10-7 but edged San Diego State 23-22. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
