<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 09:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FedEx pilots win Seniority Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Ten pilots for Federal Express Corp. have  
won a $3.59 million jury verdict in a work contract dispute with 
the cargo airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots argued the company violated rules on seniority for  
its flight crews after acquiring another airline, Flying Tigers, in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	FedEx said it will appeal the judgment handed down Thursday by a  
Chancery Court jury. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not believe there is any basis whatsoever in fact or in  
law in this case for this verdict,'' said company spokesman Greg 
Rossiter. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert L.J. Spence Jr., an attorney for five of the pilots,  
called the verdict ``a complete and total victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 140 other FedEx fliers have made similar complaints but  
have not yet gone to court with them, said M. Scott Willhite, 
co-counsel with Spence. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute centers on the company's rules for setting pilot  
seniority, which can affect promotions and pay. 
</P>
<P>
	FedEx bought Flying Tigers for $880 million. That acquisition  
added 940 pilots to the 1,100 already working for FedEx. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations over work rules for the combined pilot corps led to  
a new ``master seniority list.'' Some veteran FedEx fliers said 
that list wrongly put hundreds of Flying Tigers pilots ahead of 
them in seniority. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
