<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Dive; Dow Ends Down 266.90  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrials briefly fell below  
10,000 today as a whiff of inflation and a warning to investors by 
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan sent stocks tumbling. The 
Dow ended down 266.90 at 10,019.71 for its worst close since early 
April. The selloff followed a report revealing that prices at the 
wholesale level spiked 1.1 percent in September, the largest 
increase in nine years. Greenspan issued his latest warning about 
investor exuberance at a time of robust economic expansion and 
roaring stock markets. Both developments aggravated market fears 
that the Fed will raise interest rates to fight inflation by 
slowing the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Officer Charged With Marine's Death  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine captain was charged with  
negligent homicide in the killing of a corporal who died after 
completing an eight-mile hike at the camp in July. Capt. Victor A. 
Arana, 28, of DuPage County, Ill., was accused of marching his unit 
too fast with not enough time for breaks. Camp Lejeune spokesman 
Capt. James Rich said today that temperatures were 80 to 85 degrees 
when began Cpl. Giuseppe Leto, 21, of Milford, Conn. began the 
hike. Arana also was charged with dereliction of duty and failing 
to obey a lawful order. If convicted, he could get more than 3 1/2 
years in prison and be dismissed from the Marines. 

</P>
<P>
	Schindler's Original List Said Found  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- The original ``Schindler's List'' of  
Jewish workers reportedly has been found in a suitcase full of 
papers left to a German couple. A newspaper reported today that the 
Stuttgart couple, relatives of close friends of Oskar Schindler, 
found among the papers the list of 1,200 employees who were to be 
saved from Nazi death camps. Schindler wrote the names of 1,200 
Jews at the Plaszow concentration camp and gave it to the Nazi SS, 
saying the people on the list were needed for employment at his 
factory in Krakow, Poland, Mordechai Paldiel said. He added 
fictitious jobs for each worker to convince Nazi officials that 
they were vital to the war effort and should live. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Investigate Korea Massacre  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Defense Department's investigation of an  
alleged mass-killing of civilian refugees by U.S. soldiers during 
the Korean War will seek to find the truth ``no matter where it 
leads,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen pledged in a letter to 
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung. The letter, dated Oct. 8, was 
made available to reporters today at the Pentagon. On Sept. 30, The 
Associated Press reported accounts by American veterans and South 
Korean villagers who said they saw U.S. soldiers kill up to 400 
civilians at No Gun Ri, South Korea, early in the war. 

</P>
<P>
	Crocodiles Creep Into Mexican City  
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- First the floods, now the  
crocodiles. Residents say the reptiles are crawling into the 
streets of the flooded city of Villahermosa, seeking higher ground 
to rest and sun themselves. ``Last night, one came out and stopped 
in the middle of the street, blocking traffic,'' taxi driver Ruben 
Mendoza said. ``It was very big. No one wanted to move it. It was 
frightening.'' Local environmental officials are warning residents 
to call authorities rather than try to move or overpower the 
crocodiles, which range in size from 3 feet to 8 feet. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Urges Calm Y2K Attitude  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
today he doubts the millennium computer bug would disrupt nation's 
economy. But even though the public's understanding of the matter 
has grown and fears of widespread disruptions waned, he said, ``We 
are not as yet home free.'' Greenspan admitted he still is 
apprehensive over the potential for economic impact of hoarding or 
other significant changes in traditional spending patterns. 
Greenspan also repeated his warning that banks will remain safe for 
people to keep their cash. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Rally at McDonald's Tourney  
</P>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs flirted with making  
history of the most unenviable sort tonight before their little 
guys saved the day. Trailing almost throughout their semifinal 
against Italy's Varese Roosters, the NBA champions used a late run 
for a 96-86 victory and avoided becoming the league's first team to 
lose at the McDonald's Championship. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves, Mets Play Game 3 Tonight  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets send ace Al Leiter to the  
mound tonight as they try to narrow the gap in Game 3 of the NL 
Championship Series against the Atlanta Braves. The Braves won the 
first two games in Turner Field. Atlanta counters with lefty Tom 
Glavine. It will be the first NLCS game at Shea Stadium since Game 
7 in 1988 against Los Angeles. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
