<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 00:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wrong Place Dangerous in Talladega </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) -- The key to staying out of trouble at  
Talladega Superspeedway is being in the right place when the 
inevitable happens. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it is where you are when it gets ready to hit the  
fan,'' said Ward Burton, one of five drivers in Sunday's Winston 
500 with a shot at a $1 million bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	To earn the money, offered by series sponsor Winston, Burton has  
to win on a track where he has had more than his share of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been on both sides of it,'' Burton said. ``I've caused  
one accident here. I made one error that turned into a huge problem 
for a lot of drivers. Then I've been caught up in a lot of problems 
that weren't of my making, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you can be really careful and still make a mistake and  
cause a big wreck, too. The cars are just so bunched up here. It's 
almost inevitable that it's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is restrictor-plate racing.  
</P>
<P>
	``You wake up in the morning with an ache in the pit of your  
stomach,'' said Jeff Burton, Ward's younger brother. ``I don't get 
nervous before any races with the exception of Daytona and 
Talladega.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those are the two longest and fastest ovals on NASCAR's top  
circuit, and the only tracks at which the sanctioning body requires 
carburetor restrictor plates to keep the cars under 200 mph in the 
interest of safety for both the drivers and the spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	The plates reduce airflow to the carburetor, thereby cutting  
considerable horsepower. 
</P>
<P>
	It works as intended, but the consequence is that cars all have  
about the same horsepower, keeping them bunched up. That, added to 
a slower throttle response, virtually guarantees at least one 
multi-car crash during each race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult when you're running 20th and the leader is a  
second ahead of you and you're sitting there just hoping to miss 
the wreck,'' said Jeff Burton, also eligible for the $1 million, 
along with Mark Martin, Jeremy Mayfield and Kevin Lepage. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the danger lurking on Talladega's 2.66-mile oval, Dale  
Earnhardt says the plates have taken some of the racing fun here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoy racing on the big tracks, but it used to be more fun  
than it is now because we could run wide open with no restrictor 
plates,'' said Earnhardt, who won the spring race in Talladega, as 
well as last year's Daytona 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before the restrictor plates, you would carry so much speed  
going into the corners that you had to lift to make it around. Now, 
it's straight leg, foot to the floor all the way around the track, 
and the first one that lifts goes back to the end of the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, as much success as Earnhardt, known as a master of drafting  
in Daytona and Talladega, has had at the big tracks, he knows how 
fast they can bite you. 
</P>
<P>
	He was caught up in a 21-car crash in Talladega in April 1998  
that relegated him to a 36th-place finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward Burton said, ``You've got to be good and you've got to be  
lucky to win at Talladega. You can't be one or the other. You have 
to be both. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll give you a good example. In April, we had a really good  
car, a top-five car that had a chance to win the race. Bad luck is 
another car running into us on pit road and doing enough damage to 
completely take us out of the running for anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, it's on the track where most of the problems arise in  
Talladadga. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big wreck is the thing that's on everybody's mind once the  
race starts,'' Ward said. ``If you're going to win the race, you 
have to finish. You start figuring that big wreck is going to 
happen at some point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The older Burton noted Talladega is one of the few tracks where  
running near the rear of the field early could become an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at the big wreck in the first Talladega race last year.  
There were a bunch of guys struggling a little bit during the day, 
but then a bunch of cars starting running into each other with 
about 40 laps to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ones who missed the wreck ended up with, at the worst,  
halfway-decent finishes. The wrecks went to the garage and had a 
terrible day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
