<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower against other  
major currencies in European trading today. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0880 in late European trading, up from  
1.0785. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at 
$1.0881. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 105.54 Japanese yen, down from 106.91; 1.4590 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.4741; 1.4866 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4800. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6698, up from $1.6567.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 105.63 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6686. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar was worth 1.7975 German marks, down from 1,8131; 
6.0279 French francs, down from 6.0821; 2.0249 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0435; 1779.50 Italian lire, down from 1,795.17. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $315.00 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$319.00 on Thursday. In Zurich the bid price was $315.00, down from 
$318.50. Gold fell $7.25 in Hong Kong to close at $316.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.38 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.65. 
  	   	
</P>
