<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Inspect Visitors' Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Plans for perhaps the biggest Capitol  
construction project since the 1850s moved a little closer to 
reality Friday as a panel of lawmakers took their first official 
look at a model for a $250 million underground visitors center. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Sen. Strom Thurmond,  
R-S.C., co-chaired the first meeting of the Capitol Preservation 
Commission, which will decide whether to accept, alter or reject a 
general design plan submitted by the Architect of the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to lay out what the steps are and to get an  
agreement that we can support,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll also need to consider how we might proceed to raise the  
additional funds necessary to complete the visitors center,'' 
Thurmond said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has spent a decade considering the idea of a center to  
give up to 18,000 tourists a day access to historical displays, 
bathrooms and food as they wait to begin tours, freeing them from 
long lines in the winter cold and summer heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican opposition to the cost put the plan on hold in 1991.  
It was revived only after a gunman shot his way into the building 
last year and killing two police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Current plans foresee a three-level underground structure  
totaling 558,000 square feet set into the east side of the Capitol, 
across the street from the Supreme Court and one of the Library of 
Congress' buildings. The Capitol contains 775,000 square feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The next step will be development of a detailed design and  
engineering, a process expected to take more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Constructing the U.S. Capitol Visitor Center remains one of  
our highest priorities, and today's meeting brought us one 
significant step closer to making that vision a reality,'' said a 
commission statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 federal budget included $100 million for planning,  
engineering, designing and constructing the center but also made 
provisions for private donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they are planning for the center to open in  
January 2005. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
