<DOCNO> APW19991015.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Help Bush's Campaign Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Employees of MBNA Corp., a major bank and  
issuer of credit cards with two major issues before Congress, were 
the biggest contributors to Gov. George W. Bush's presidential 
campaign in the last three months, an analysis shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former Sen. Bill Bradley's biggest donors during the  
period were employees of the same Wall Street investment houses 
that have supported him throughout his campaign, according to an 
Associated Press computer analysis of contributions to the 
presidential candidates. Bradley is a former consultant to 
financial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore's top givers were lawyers.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Republican front-runner, raised another $20.2 million  
between July 1 and Sept. 30, bringing his record-setting total to 
$57.4 million. He raised $77,400 from employees of MBNA Corp., the 
nation's second largest issuer of credit cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is considering legislation to allow banks, insurance  
companies and investment houses to enter each other's markets -- a 
measure sought by all three industries -- and a credit card 
industry-backed bill to overhaul bankruptcy laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also raised $54,750 from employees of Ernst &AMP; Young, an  
accounting firm that lobbies on behalf of electric utilities and 
the high-technology industry, among other clients. Ernst &AMP; Young 
also has been a big financial backer of Gore's presidential 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley outraised Gore in the third quarter of 1999, taking in  
$7.3 million compared with $6.8 million by the vice president. Gore 
also received $534,293 from his general election fund for legal and 
accounting expenses to pay a share of fund-raising costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, Gore's only rival for the Democratic presidential  
nomination, raised $167,200 from employees of Goldman Sachs, 
$75,450 from employees of Lehman Brothers, and $63,440 from 
employees of Merrill Lynch, which also is pushing for the banking 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore took in $21,750 from members of the law firm of Mayer,  
Brown &AMP; Platt, which lobbies on behalf of such companies as Boeing, 
General Electric and United Parcel Service; and $20,750 from 
members of the law firm of Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi, whose 
clients include Honeywell. 
</P>
<P>
	``They represent a pretty elite and rarefied group of  
interests,'' said Sheila Krumholtz, research director for the 
Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan research group. 
``These players are among the top bundlers cycle after cycle and, 
of course, they have specific legislative agendas that they are 
pursing. Their giving represents all of the reasons their clients 
are hiring them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush not only raised more money than any other presidential  
candidate, he also spent more. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent $12.8 million in the period, more than doubling his  
campaign expenditures. Overall, Bush has spent $19 million, 
including $7.1 million on fund raising and $2.9 million on travel. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have to watch his money,'' said Candice Nelson, an  
associate professor of political science at American University. 
``He can spend as much as he needs to. Even doing that, he will 
have enough left over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush even has spent more money than Steve Forbes, who has pumped  
$16.3 million of his own money into the campaign and raised another 
$4.5 million. Forbes spent almost $19 million, including $4 million 
on advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col said much of the money has  
gone to build campaign operations in 10 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to have grassroots organization,'' Dal Col said.  
``We're the only campaign that's organized in all the early 
states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the Democratic side, Gore has spent $14.6 million to  
Bradley's $8.5 million. And Bradley had more money in the bank as 
of Sept. 30, $10.7 million compared with Gore's $10.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has spent as much on salaries -- $2.2 million -- as Bush has  
spent to run his campaign headquarters, including rent, office 
equipment and taxes in addition to payroll. Bradley, spent $1.5 
million on salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also has spent twice as much as Bradley on polling,  
$387,844 to $173,189. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
