<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leaky Defense Costs Mets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the beginning, the New York Mets couldn't  
handle the baseball. In the end, that was the difference that cost 
them Game 3 of the National League championship series against 
Atlanta Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The sure-handed Mets defense led the majors with just 68 errors  
all season and was a cornerstone of the team's dash to the 
playoffs. Their .989 fielding percentage was the highest in major 
league history and the 68 errors were the fewest ever by a team in 
a season. New York went 38 consecutive games from May 26-July 6 
without allowing an unearned run. 
</P>
<P>
	But that changed suddenly in the first inning and contributed to  
a 1-0 Atlanta victory that left the Braves one victory away from 
the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta scored an unearned run without benefit of a hit --  
something that almost never happened to the Mets this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets starter Al Leiter walked leadoff man Gerald Williams and  
then Bret Boone tapped a ball back to the mound. It looked like a 
double play opportunity, but Leiter turned it into a disaster 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	First, the pitcher looked at second base, where it seemed he had  
a good shot at Williams. Then he changed his mind and threw high 
and wide to first, pulling John Olerud off the base for an error. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of two out and none on, the Braves had none out and two  
on. 
</P>
<P>
	After Chipper Jones popped up, Atlanta manager Bobby Cox forced  
the issue, sending the runners. Catcher Mike Piazza's throw to 
second sailed into center field, allowing Williams to score and 
Boone to reach third. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time all season that the Mets made two errors  
in an inning and it came from two of the team's few weak links 
defensively. Leiter led Mets pitchers with four errors and Piazza 
led the team with 11. 
</P>
<P>
	The miscues seemed to wake up New York's defense.  
</P>
<P>
	When Brian Jordan flied to center, Boone tried to score and was  
thrown out at the plate by rookie Melvin Mora. Piazza grabbed 
Mora's throw and held onto the ball as Boone bowled him over. The 
catcher suffered a slight concussion on the play 
</P>
<P>
	In the second inning, with runners at first and second and none  
out after Leiter's wild-pitch third strike to leadoff man Andruw 
Jones, the Mets cut off the rally when Robin Ventura turned Brian 
Hunter's line drive into a double play. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth, Chipper Jones singled leading off but was thrown  
out trying to stretch the hit by left fielder Rickey Henderson. In 
the fifth, Eddie Perez tried the same thing with the same result. 
Henderson, who did not have an assist during the regular season, 
tied a playoff record with the two throws. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Rey Ordonez contributed a sliding stop in the hole to  
throw out Boone in the sixth and grabbed Hunter's line drive to end 
the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense was back in business. But by then, it was too late  
to do the Mets any good. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
