<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chandler Return Will Boost Falcons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- With Chris Chandler likely to start Sunday,  
the Atlanta Falcons improved their chances of getting back into the 
NFC West race. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dan Reeves upgraded the quarterback's status to probable  
after practice Thursday. A Pro Bowl selection the last two years, 
Chandler has missed three of the last four games with a strained 
right hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say he's been upgraded from questionable to  
probable,'' said coach Dan Reeves, whose Falcons (1-4) will face 
the St. Louis Rams (4-0) at the Georgia Dome. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks pretty good. He's had two good days of practice. I  
think he'll be able to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chandler, a 12-year veteran, was injured at the end of the  
season opener. After sitting out the next game, he tried to come 
back too soon in the Falcons' 34-7 loss at St. Louis on Sept. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	He played only the opening quarter and completed 5 of 9 passes  
for only 28 yards and one interception. Chandler, who was not 
available for comment after practice, has not played since. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta is 17-4 when Chandler has started and finished a game --  
including 10-1 last season when the Falcons went to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	With Chandler out and running back Jamal Anderson sidelined for  
the season with a knee injury, the Falcons' offense has stalled. 
They are averaging 12.2 points per game -- third-worst in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating because we know we're a better football team  
than the numbers show,'' center Robbie Tobeck said. ``It's not an 
excuse for us to say we've missed Chris and Jamal -- it's a fact. 
Those are the kinds of players you can't replace. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that doesn't mean we can't be a good football team. There  
are still enough players left from a team that went to the Super 
Bowl to get out of the mess we put ourselves in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Backup quarterback Tony Graziani has thrown for only 509 yards  
and two touchdowns. The running game hasn't done much either. Byron 
Hanspard is averaging only 3 yards per carry, Ken Oxendine 2.7 
yards and neither has scored a touchdown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
