<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Furniture Sellers Believe in Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) -- When Jay Busey's son suggested he take  
his Shaw Furniture Galleries online, his initial reaction was, ``No 
way, you have to touch it and feel it to buy furniture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he thinks differently.  
</P>
<P>
	``Customers do want to buy on the Internet. They're buying every  
day,'' said Busey, president and chief executive officer of Shaw 
Furniture Galleries, a living.com company. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief reason consumers log onto his site is convenience.  
</P>
<P>
	``When a customer wants information, they want it quickly,'' he  
said. ``This is why they turn to the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While e-commerce represents a minuscule segment of furniture  
sales at the dawn of the new century, it is expected to grow 
steadily, a panel of furniture sellers and industry experts agreed 
Thursday as the International Home Furnishings Market opened its 
nine-day fall run. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real key is helping local retailers understand that this  
is just a small piece of the total pie,'' said Steve Antisdel, 
president of FurnitureFind.com, which expects to finish the year 
with $12 million in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	That's just a tiny fraction of the amount of sales posted by  
traditional furniture stores. The U.S. retail market is $55 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``My belief is that it (e-commerce) will grow the industry  
rather than take away from the traditional retailers,'' said 
Antisdel. ``It will help consumers educate themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Jerry Epperson isn't a believer just yet, but  
admitted he was intrigued by the number of people at the market who 
want to talk to him about e-commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet is the gold rush of our age,'' he said Thursday.  
``The last time we had a gold rush, the ones who made money were 
those people who were selling picks and shovels. Not too many 
people found gold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other words, he said, online retailers that deliver solid  
customer service along with slick Web pages and computer graphics 
will be the ones who survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry officials estimate e-commerce now represents about $100  
million of the total retail furniture market, but by 2003, the 
amount of goods sold over the Internet will grow to $1.5 billion -- 
still just 3 percent of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	But some are strongly resisting the push by some to take the  
industry online. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Cutler, furniture analyst with BDO Seidman L.L.P. in High  
Point, touched upon the dissension within the industry over the 
value of e-commerce when he introduced three panelists, whom he 
described as pioneers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of these people are hated and reviled by the full-service  
furniture stores. In fact, they are called `dot-commies,''' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest furniture trade show, which runs through  
Oct. 22, draws about 70,000 people from all 50 states and more than 
100 foreign countries. Buyers can choose from more than 2,400 
exhibitors that fill more than 8 million square feet of showroom 
space in High Point and nearby Thomasville. 
</P>
<P>
	The mood at the start of the show was upbeat.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite a recent rise in interest rates, Epperson said consumers  
are continuing to buy new homes along with the things they need to 
furnish them. That signals good things for people in the industry, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry officials expect overall 1999 furniture shipments to  
eclipse last year's record figures. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the American Furniture Manufacturers Association's  
latest quarterly forecast, 1999, furniture shipments should 
approach $25 billion -- an 8 percent increase over 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail sales will exceed $61 billion this year, the forecast  
says, a 5.5 percent increase over 1998. Retail sales are expected 
to be nearly $63.9 billion in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFMA forecasts shipments of wood furniture to increase 8.7  
percent to nearly $12 billion; shipments of upholstered furniture 
are expected to rise 10.3 percent to $10.5 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
