<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BoSox Stanley Hopeful for Game 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Boston Red Sox first baseman Mike Stanley had his  
injured right wrist wrapped in ice Friday but felt he'd be able to 
play Saturday in Game 3 of the AL championship series against the 
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley's wrist was bruised in the eighth inning of Thursday's  
3-2 loss that put New York ahead 2-0 in the best-of-7 AL 
championship series. He was hit by a pitch from Jeff Nelson and 
Damon Buford came in to run for him. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury is in the same spot where Nomar Garciaparra was hit  
by a pitch from Baltimore's Al Reyes on Sept. 25. That bruise 
forced Garciaparra to miss Game 3 of the AL division series against 
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obviously sore at the point of impact,'' Stanley said  
Friday. ``I've never been hit in the wrist. I know in that area the 
bones aren't as strong or durable as in other areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had been worried the wrist might be broken, but  
X-rays were negative. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Daubach, the designated hitter in the first two games  
against New York, probably would play first base if Stanley can't. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston relief pitcher Rich Garces, who pitched Wednesday night  
but wasn't available Thursday night because of a painful arm, said 
he'd be ready Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CATCHING ON:* After spending most of the season as a backup to  
Jorge Posada, Yankees catcher Joe Girardi is getting most of the 
playing time in the ALCS. 
</P>
<P>
	Posada started Game 1 against Boston, but Girardi caught Game 2.  
And manager Joe Torre said Girardi would start Games 3 and 4, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I am a Joe Girardi person, not to say that I am not a  
Jorge Posada person,'' Torre said Friday. ``Jorge has got a ton of 
ability. One thing he doesn't have that Joe has is the experience. 
Joe has done it in postseason play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a great deal of confidence in Joe Girardi, as far as  
using the fingers behind the plate, having a sense of what is going 
on and I sense the pitchers are comfortable with him,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Posada played 112 games during the regular season, batting .245  
with 12 home runs and 57 RBIs. Girardi played 65 games, hitting 
.239 with two homers and 27 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is nothing more than experience,'' Torre said. ``Jorge  
Posada caught most of the games this year. He will catch even more 
next year, and he is the future of the organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO WORK, ALL PLAY:* Boston manager Jimy Williams wanted to give  
his players the day off, but baseball rules required them to be at 
the park on Friday for the media. 
</P>
<P>
	So the players milled around the clubhouse, got treatment and  
talked to reporters. But they didn't work out. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said earlier in the week that he would ask the league  
for permission to skip the workout. ``If they say we all have to be 
there, we'll all be there,'' he said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the team was reportedly fined $50,000 for not making  
an off-day workout mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HE AIN'T HEAVY:* Boston's Game 2 starter, Ramon Martinez, said  
his brother, Pedro, who will start Game 3, won't be affected by the 
circus atmosphere surrounding the matchup against Roger Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're going to see is the same Pedro,'' said Ramon, who  
is four years older. ``I don't think even Game 7 of the World 
Series he's going to change anything.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
