<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Ginsburg on the Mend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said  
Friday she is still ``a little wobbly'' after her surgery last 
month for colon cancer, ``but I progress steadily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, the second woman to serve on the nation's highest  
court, spoke to the International Women's Forum, an organization of 
female leaders from around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I accepted the invitation to be with you at this  
conference, I did not know how thankful I would be just to be 
here,'' said Ginsburg to loud applause from the audience. ``I am 
still mending, but I progress steadily since my Sept. 17 surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Your invitation, though I remain a little wobbly, was  
irresistible,'' the justice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg, 66, had part of her colon removed, and afterward  
doctors reported the cancer had not spread to any lymph nodes. 
</P>
<P>
	She had fallen ill over the summer and initially was treated for  
a gastric disorder. A court spokeswoman said that led doctors to 
discover the cancerous tumor. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg told the members of the women's organization she is  
proud to call herself a feminist. 
</P>
<P>
	She said there are ``too many people who regard feminism with  
suspicion, people who are uncomforted by the very word, and even 
people who call it the f-word.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The best advice she ever received, Ginsburg said, came from her  
mother-in-law on her wedding day: ``It pays sometimes to be a 
little deaf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she has followed that advice at home and at work,  
sometimes ``even in relating to my colleagues at the Supreme 
Court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing with Ginsburg were Israeli Supreme Court Justice Dalia  
Dorner and Philippines Supreme Court Justice Consuelo 
Ynares-Santiago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ynares-Santiago said her nation's highest court has taken the  
lead in combating sexual harassment in the workplace. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorner said Israel does not have an overall equality law, but  
her court has sought to fill the gaps ``by finding a broader right 
to equality'' in a basic law that guarantees human dignity and 
freedom. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
