<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ramblin' Wreck Heads to Duke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- It's little comfort to Duke that the first  
team to stop Georgia Tech's offense this season was, well, Georgia 
Tech. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 8 Yellow Jackets turned the ball over six times last  
Saturday in a 31-24 overtime victory against North Carolina -- the 
first time in five games Georgia Tech hasn't reached the 35-point 
plateau. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke coach Carl Franks doesn't expect his team to get much  
charity from the Yellow Jackets (4-1, 2-1 Atlantic Coast 
Conference) on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The turnovers, which is very unusual for them, gave North  
Carolina a tremendous opportunity to have a chance to win that 
game,'' Franks said. ``If they don't have the turnovers it may not 
be close. I know they have worked like crazy all week to correct 
those things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils (1-4, 1-1) gave up 51 points to No. 1 Florida  
State two weeks ago. However, Franks isn't sure the Yellow Jackets' 
offense -- with a variety of formations that can drive a defensive 
coordinator dizzy -- isn't better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what Georgia Tech does is much more difficult,''  
Franks said when comparing the two high-scoring teams. 
``Defensively, you have to adjust everything to their formations 
and sets. You could call a blitz but you don't know what they're 
going to come out in and move guys around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia Tech has pretty much had its way with the Blue Devils  
this decade, going 8-1. That includes four straight wins in which 
the Yellow Jackets have scored at least 37 points in each game. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke's biggest fear is getting into a shootout. That's unlikely  
since the Blue Devils' highest scoring output in 1999 was their 
24-17 double-overtime victory at Virginia last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're probably not real worried about our offense or our  
defense as well as they've been playing,'' Franks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary admits he worked his team hard  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you are pleased with where they are at, you are  
sending the wrong message,'' O'Leary said. ``My job is to get them 
to do things they don't want to do. There is no comfort zone. I try 
to make them understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defenses have been searching for possible ways to slow down  
Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton, the nation's top-ranked 
passer who has become the top target for opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	The diminutive Hamilton enters this weekend's game with 18  
touchdowns in five games for the nation's best offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's exciting like Charlie Ward,'' Franks said, comparing him  
to the 1993 Heisman Trophy winner from Florida State. ``When he 
can't find somebody open that's when the excitement really starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you've got everybody covered and you think you've got him  
in the pocket he can bust out of there and it's hard to grab his 
flags and get him down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Leary said he's starting to see teams using eight or nine  
defenders near the line of scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It stops the power run game,'' O'Leary said. ``They have an  
extra guy to where you can't block him. But if you're doing that 
then you better be solid in your coverage. You can't be good on 
both in the same down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has been outscored 34-3 in the first quarter this season,  
and 77-19 in the first half. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
