<HEADLINE> Griese To Start at QB for Broncos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Brian Griese -- not Bubby Brister -- will be the  
starting quarterback for the Denver Broncos in Sunday's home game 
against the Green Bay Packers, coach Mike Shanahan said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan said earlier in the week that Brister, sidelined by a  
strained oblique muscle on his left side, needed to practice by 
Friday if he expected to play this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Brister tried to throw before Friday's practice, but said he was  
still suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will not be able to go, so Brian will be No. 1 and Chris  
(Miller) will be No. 2,'' Shanahan said, adding that he hoped 
Brister would be ready to play again next week. ``It keeps on 
improving,'' Shanahan said. ``He just can't torque it. He can throw 
it, but to go in his normal full rotation it's bothering him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griese found out before Friday's practice that he would be start  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old started the first four games for Denver, but was  
benched and replaced by Brister after an 0-4 start. 
</P>
<P>
	Griese got his job back when the Broncos learned shortly before  
last week's game against the Oakland Raiders that Brister would be 
out with injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL said it has fined the Broncos $25,000 for not promptly  
reporting Brister's injury to the league. Brister was hurt on 
Friday, but the Broncos didn't list him as injured until Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Griese led the Broncos to a 16-13 win, their first of the  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't pretty by any means, especially on my part. There  
are a lot of things I could have done better, and I plan to do 
those things this week,'' Griese said. ``I have more confidence, I 
think the team has more confidence, and I know they have more 
confidence in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Running back Derek Loville, who had been listed as questionable  
on the Broncos' lengthy injury report with a strained hamstring, 
also will not play Sunday, Shanahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That hamstring is still tight, I'd say it's about 80 percent,  
hopefully with four to five days' rest he'll be able to go next 
week,'' he said of Loville, the designated starter after Terrell 
Davis' season-ending knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Rod Smith, who has a strained groin, returned to  
practice Friday but is still listed as questionable for Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Center K.C. Jones and tight end Shannon Sharpe have been  
declared inactive. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
