<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners Appeal Newspaper Shutdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- The owners of The Honolulu Advertiser and  
Honolulu Star-Bulletin on Friday appealed a federal judge's order 
blocking the scheduled Oct. 30 shutdown of the Star-Bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Alan Kay had issued an injunction Wednesday  
pending a trial in the state's lawsuit alleging that an agreement 
between Gannett Co. Inc. and Liberty Newspapers Limited Partnership 
to close the Star-Bulletin violates antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett owns the Advertiser, a morning newspaper, and Liberty  
Newspapers owns the Star-Bulletin, an afternoon paper. The state 
claims that Gannett in effect paid off Liberty to create its own 
monopoly, which the papers deny. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett purchased the Advertiser and sold the Star-Bulletin to  
Liberty Newspapers in 1993, but agreed to continue a joint 
operating agreement between the two newspapers until 2012. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett reached a deal to pay Liberty Newspapers $26.5 million --  
an amount based on the savings Gannett could expect from ending the 
papers' joint operating agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay said Wednesday the public interest to preserve separate  
editorial voices in the community is great enough to keep the 
Star-Bulletin running until the state's lawsuit is settled. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay's order is a ``First Amendment violation because it requires  
a newspaper to publish when it does not wish to do so,'' the 
Advertiser and Star-Bulletin owners said Friday in the appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing date for the appeal has not been scheduled.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
