<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Radiation Tally Up to 69 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The tally of people exposed to radiation in Japan's  
worst-ever nuclear accident was increased by 20 to 69 today, the 
government said, acknowledging that an inadequate monitoring system 
was behind the undercount. 
</P>
<P>
	The new figure appeared in a report on the Sept. 30 accident  
submitted today to the Nuclear Safety Commission, a government 
panel appointed by the prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20 new readings came from badges the workers wore to monitor  
radiation levels, the report said. Investigators only belatedly 
checked the badges. Of those exposed, 59 were workers at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident at a uranium-processing plant in northeastern Japan  
set off an uncontrolled atomic reaction. Employees mixing nuclear 
fuel in a bucket added too much uranium, spewing radiation into the 
air and sending three workers to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said previously that seven people working near  
the site and three firefighters who rescued the three most 
seriously injured workers were also exposed to radiation. 
</P>
<P>
	Other workers were exposed to radiation levels 50 to 100 times  
higher than what is considered safe to receive over the course of a 
year, the report found. At least one worker was exposed to more 
radiation than the legal limit allowed for emergency situations. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident raised serious doubts about the safety of Japan's  
nuclear power policy. An investigation disclosed that workers at 
the facility routinely violated safety procedures, were under 
pressure to get the job done quickly and had not received proper 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety requirements at nuclear facilities will be beefed up,  
Labor Minister Takamori Makino said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to now, only nuclear power plants were inspected by the  
ministry, and they only once a year. 
</P>
<P>
	From now on, the 20 other facilities nationwide that handle  
nuclear fuel will also have to be inspected, and the inspections 
will take place once every three months, said ministry official 
Hiroyoshi Hatanaka. More workers will also be required to receive 
special training. 
</P>
<P>
	Three officials from the International Atomic Energy Agency, who  
arrived in Japan on Wednesday, inspected the site of the accident 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more experts were due Monday from the United States,  
science agency spokesman Yoshio Abe said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
