<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albanians Clash With Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- French and Italian  
peacekeepers clashed with ethnic Albanians trying to push their way 
across a bridge today in this divided Kosovo city, injuring dozens 
of people. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers fired tear gas and stun grenades for more than an  
hour at ethnic Albanians trying to cross into the Serb-held half of 
the city. Cannons also were used to unleash a stream of tear gas 
into the crowd, which numbered several thousand. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 people poured into the city's small, Albanian-run  
hospital, seeking treatment. The most seriously hurt was a 
12-year-old boy, who was knocked unconscious and suffered a 4-inch 
head wound, according to hospital officials. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 20 others were to undergo surgery, and dozens were  
suffering from the effects of tear gas. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't clear how many peacekeepers -- who wore helmets and  
bulletproof vests, and wielded plastic shields -- were injured in 
the clash. One French soldier was seen holding his eye, which 
likely was injured by stones or sticks hurled by Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	The clash began after ethnic Albanians launched what is planned  
to be six months of daily protests. After peacefully marching to a 
local mosque and a Catholic church, more than 1,000 protesters 
attempted to cross to the Serb side of the city, as Serbs gathered 
on the other side. 
</P>
<P>
	French peacekeepers, along with some Italian carabinieri, first  
tried to use barbed wire to block their progress. They then rolled 
out eight tanks, and began firing tear gas and stun grenades. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serb woman who had been at the scene said ethnic Albanians  
made it halfway across the bridge spanning the Ibar River before 
being pushed back. 
</P>
<P>
	Armored vehicles were parked on the bridge, and French snipers  
took up positions on buildings overlooking the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of Serbs gathered on the other side and hoisted the  
Serbian flag. 
</P>
<P>
	``The French seem to be keeping the situation under control for  
now,'' said the woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Serbs on the other side of the bridge are ready to defend  
our part of Mitrovica,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	After the clashes, ethnic Albanians continued to pack a 700-yard  
stretch of road leading to the bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in an attempt to restore a degree of normality in  
Kosovo, U.N. police began issuing license plates Friday to drivers 
across the province, where many cars are thought stolen either from 
Westen Europe or fleeing Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, drivers have until January to register their  
cars. After that, any vehicle without plates or proper papers will 
be seized, and U.N. police will use the registry to check for 
stolen vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Pristina's airport reopened to receive its first  
commercial flight today -- an Adria Airways jet from Slovenia 
carrying 155 passengers, most of them ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	That move comes a day after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's  
first visit to the province. Speaking Thursday, Annan rebuffed 
ethnic Albanian hopes of quick independence, saying Kosovo will 
remain a part of Yugoslavia as long as it is under U.N. 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not here to prepare the people for independence,'' he  
said. ``That is not my mandate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians, the province's overwhelming majority,  
fervently support independence from Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant 
republic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
