<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 07:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moody's Coy on Thailand Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- An analyst for Moody's Investor  
Services left Thailand after a well-publicized visit this week with 
praise for the government's economic management, but without saying 
when it will upgrade the country's rating. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot more confidence in the policy-makers than we did  
at the time of the crisis,'' Thomas Byrne, senior analyst of 
Moody's sovereign risk unit, told Dow Jones Newswires in an 
interview Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sovereign risk measures the ability of a government to pay back  
its borrowings. 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipation of Moody's three-day visit to Thailand, which ended  
Thursday, spurred rallies by the Thai stock market and the baht 
currency in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Moody's currently has a foreign currency ceiling of Ba1 on  
Thailand, one notch below investment grade. 
</P>
<P>
	Any upward revision would open the gates to foreign capital  
inflows, especially from institutional funds which are bound by 
their own rules to put money only in countries with sovereign 
investment grade ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne praised the Thai government's handling of the economy, but  
deferred comment on what Moody's ratings plans are. 
</P>
<P>
	``It (an upgrade) could happen anytime between now and over the  
next year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Standard and Poor's and Fitch IBCA, two other ratings agencies,  
have already raised Thailand's sovereign rating to investment 
grade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
