<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Reorganizes Business Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. announced a wide-ranging  
management shuffle today, aimed at giving more power to lower-level 
executives and making the world's second-largest automaker more 
nimble. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves announced by Ford President and CEO Jac Nasser give 14  
vice presidents new titles and reorganizes their responsibilities 
along brand and regional lines effective Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The new units ``allow Ford to preserve the strengths of Ford's  
global scale and collective knowledge while creating smaller, more 
agile business units,'' Nasser said. ``They will allow Ford to 
consistently deliver innovative products and services that delight 
customers by focusing on brands and consumer needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No executives lost their jobs in the moves. Henry D.G. Wallace  
was chosen as Ford's new chief financial officer. Wallace ran 
Ford's Asia Pacific operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ford name will be handled by units in North America, Europe,  
Asia and South America. The Mercury division was moved into the 
company's Premier Automotive Group that manages its luxury brands -- 
Lincoln, Jaguar, Volvo and Aston Martin -- around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda, which is 33 percent owned by Ford, and parts maker  
Visteon Automotive Systems will operate separately. The company 
will also have four business groups dealing with consumer services 
-- including one aimed at Internet commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said the changes were an ``evolution'' of a  
previous management effort, Ford 2000, started by former chairman 
Alex Trotman. Under Ford 2000, the company cut $5 billion in costs 
by having more cars and trucks share engines, transmissions and 
other parts, and by getting better deals from suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford 2000 gave more power to central managers. The new plan  
pushes more decisions out into the field, and by doing so, Ford 
hopes to give its middle managers better training. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're going to become the kind of company we talk about in  
terms of business acumen, we have to have a pipeline of really 
great business leadership coming through,'' said David Murphy, 
Ford's vice president of human resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy said it would be a year before consumers would notice any  
changes in the way the company operates, and then only in 
marketing. Changes in products are two or three years away, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But over time, ``we really believe this will get us a lot closer  
to our consumers,'' Murphy said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
