<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Allow Iowa, N.H. Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iowa and New Hampshire will be allowed to move  
up on the political calendar next winter, a Democratic Party panel 
said Friday without deciding whether several other states can move 
up their presidential primaries, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa will hold its leadoff caucuses Jan. 24 and New Hampshire  
will hold the nation's first primary Feb. 1, the Democratic 
National Committee's rules panel decided. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa caucuses had been set for Jan. 31, but New Hampshire  
officials unexpectedly scheduled their primary on Feb. 1. They 
refused to push it back to Feb. 8 in recognition of the traditional 
eight-day period between the two state contests. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' rules panel adjourned until Oct. 22 without  
deciding what to do about four other states whose requests to move 
primaries into February it had rejected. Democratic rules assure 
that New Hampshire is seven days ahead of any other state and Iowa 
is 15 days ahead. The party tries to keep other states from holding 
primaries and caucuses until March 7 or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington state's request to move its primary to Feb. 29 will  
be reconsidered, and the panel may hear similar requests from 
Arizona, Michigan and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that you will see some of those four ... approved  
and move up,'' said panel member Gary LaPaille of Chicago. ``But 
they should think it through, and we should think it through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	States have been jockeying for earlier positions on the calendar  
-- and increased influence -- ever since California decided earlier 
this year to move up to March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the states, representing three-fourths of party  
convention delegates, will hold primaries and caucuses between the 
end of January and March 14 -- before many voters typically start 
paying attention to the November election. 
</P>
<P>
	Several panel members complained that the confusion this year  
over the primary schedule has been caused by Republicans' refusal 
to set limits on when states can hold primaries. State Democrats 
complained frequently to the panel that they wanted to hold 
primaries the same day as Republicans in their state to remain 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP spokesman Mark Pfeifle said it was just like Democrats to  
complain when Washington ``is not getting its nose into the 
business of absolutely everything, including the primary and caucus 
calendar.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
