<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roth IRA Change Deadline Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service is giving  
taxpayers a little more time to make some changes in their Roth 
IRAs. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS said Thursday that taxpayers will now have until the end  
of the year, an extension of 2 1/2 months, to change the retirement 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadline is being extended from today because many taxpayers  
have had difficulty figuring out the rules for the Roth IRA, which 
was created by Congress in 1997 and became effective last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike a traditional individual retirement account, Roth IRA  
contributions are made on an after-tax basis, but qualified 
withdrawals are generally tax-free. Taxpayers had until the end of 
1998 to switch to a Roth IRA and pay any taxes over four years, but 
the IRS has allowed more time for people to convert to a Roth IRA -- 
or to switch back to a traditional IRA. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS also announced it is sending letters to 20,000 taxpayers  
who appeared to be ineligible for Roth IRA conversions they 
reported on 1998 returns, many because they earned more than the 
$100,000 income limit. 
</P>
<P>
	If they don't convert back by the end of 1999, they could have  
to pay taxes on the money withdrawn as well as early distribution 
penalties. Amended tax returns would have to be filed by April 15, 
2002. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
