<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Targets Day Trader for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators have won a restraining  
order and asset freeze against a day trader they say raised $6.2 
million from investors by fraudulently promising them big returns 
in trading stocks with their money. 
</P>
<P>
	The day trader, Mark Drucker of Atlanta, failed to tell  
investors he has lost hundreds of thousands of dollars in the 
rapid-fire computer trading, the Securities and Exchange Commission 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge in Atlanta granted the temporary restraining  
order and a freeze of Drucker's assets. The SEC also is seeking an 
unspecified fine against him and an accounting of his use of 
investors' money, so that he can be compelled to repay the 
allegedly ill-gotten gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Drucker couldn't be reached for comment at three telephone  
numbers Friday. He was not represented by a lawyer, SEC attorneys 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC also named in its complaint Michael Weinstock, an  
Atlanta attorney, saying he fraudulently made some $1.6 million 
from participating in Drucker's scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinstock's lawyer, Pat Huddleston, said his client ``was an  
investor and at no time did he have any knowledge that there was 
anything illegal'' in Drucker's scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinstock ``has cooperated fully with the SEC's investigation,''  
Huddleston said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC alleged that from at least July 1998 through September  
1999, Drucker raised some $6.2 million from an estimated 80 
investors, telling them he was a successful day trader and 
promising them returns on their investments of 50 percent or more, 
in two months or less. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the SEC said, Drucker had consistently lost money  
day-trading with the investors' money, losing more than $630,000 
this year. Drucker used the money from recent investors to pay 
returns to earlier investors, the SEC alleged, in the classic 
formula of a Ponzi scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said Drucker, 32, also used the investors' money to  
pay for lavish parties at a big Atlanta hotel and his personal 
expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Drucker is operating a Ponzi scheme and has consistently lost  
money through his trading,'' the complaint says. ``Without 
disclosure to investors, Drucker has siphoned off substantial sums 
for his own private use, including hundreds of thousands of dollars 
... to finance elaborate parties at a local hotel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC and state securities regulators have expressed concern  
in recent months about the risks of day trading. In the practice, 
now engaged in by several thousand people nationwide, traders ride 
the tiniest ups and downs of the stock market, trying to squeeze 
out profits by rapidly buying and selling shares. They pay their 
host day-trading firms commissions on each trade. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt said last month that several  
day-trading firms have used deceptive advertising to lure investors 
and have been lax in complying with securities laws. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer another Atlanta day trader, Mark Barton, shot and  
killed nine people at two day-trading firms there before killing 
himself. Barton is believed to have lost nearly half a million 
dollars in his day trading -- including $153,000 in one three-day 
``binge.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
