<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Can Akili Do It Again for Bengals? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Can Akili Smith do it again?  
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Bengals' rookie quarterback knows it's easy to  
dismiss his game-winning drive against Cleveland because it came 
against a winless expansion team with a horrible defense. 
</P>
<P>
	If he looks good in his second start Sunday against Pittsburgh,  
then Smith's career really will be off and running. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's motivation, to show that last week wasn't a fluke,''  
Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's going to be a lot harder the second time around.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals (1-4) picked the perfect setting for Smith's NFL  
debut as a starter. The Browns give up a lot of yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan was to run Corey Dillon a lot, taking the pressure off  
Smith. The plan worked perfectly as Dillon rushed for 168 yards and 
Smith relied on short, low-risk passes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The play calling was good,'' guard Brian DeMarco said. ``I  
thought it was wise. We cut down on a lot of plays and what we did, 
we did right. To be fundamentally sound on 10 plays like we did was 
fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals rushed for 152 yards in the first half and threw for  
only 62. Smith made his debut memorable by going 5-of-7 for 51 
yards on the final drive of the game, culminating in a winning 
touchdown pass to Carl Pickens with 5 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	The way he coolly led his team 80 yards is what everyone  
remembers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't teach that,'' offensive tackle Willie Anderson said.  
``It's just something you're born with. They said all along he was 
a born leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing makes him nervous. He's not going to tense up. If he  
had started to think about it (being his first NFL start) and got 
caught up in it, it could have been a disaster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith got carried away afterwards, pounding his chest at the  
Browns bench and taunting the Dawg Pound that had taunted him 
during the game. It was his moment and he enjoyed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bruce Coslet hasn't gotten carried away by Smith's  
performance -- 25-of-42 for 221 yards and two touchdowns with four 
sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no problem with the way he played,'' Coslet said. ``For  
the first outing, it was really phenomenal, to tell you the 
truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Coslet also is quick to point out his mistakes. Smith missed  
nearly all of training camp and is still learning to run the 
offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had 80 plays and he had eight critical assignment errors,  
which is way too high. He needs to get us into the right play, the 
right formation and make the right read,'' Coslet said. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers suggest that the offense should have won by more  
than an 18-17 margin. Cincinnati had overwhelming advantages in 
first downs (25-13), total yards (419-224) and time of possession 
(37 minutes to 23), but won by only one point. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the same problem the offense had under Jeff Blake --  
moving the ball well, then freezing up inside the 20-yard line. On 
the Bengals' first two possessions, they drove 66 and 90 yards but 
had to settle for field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was frustrated,'' Smith said. ``I took my helmet off and  
banged it off the bench because we don't need field goals, we don't 
want field goals. We've got to get the ball in the end zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was still celebrating the victory on Monday, breaking into  
a smile every time he thought about it. By the time practice had 
resumed Wednesday, things were back to normal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bruce is still yelling at me,'' Smith said. ``The offensive  
line was on me a little bit. Nobody's going to let me relax at 
all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
