<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disneyland Trainer France Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Van Arsdale France, the sunny optimist  
who created the training program that taught Disneyland employees 
how to sell happiness with a smile, has died at 87. 
</P>
<P>
	France, who died Thursday of pneumonia, was hired before  
Disneyland opened in 1955 to create the training program, called 
the University of Disneyland. 
</P>
<P>
	Walt Disney told France to come up with lessons that would help  
employees avoid a carnival image. The result was France's employee 
training manual, which became legendary in the retail industry 
because of its instructions to treat customers as guests who were 
buying the product of happiness. 
</P>
<P>
	France was so cheerful, fellow employees at the self-described  
Happiest Place on Earth called him Disneyland's Jiminy Cricket. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, Van was as much a part of Disneyland as the castle or  
the carousel,'' said former Disneyland President Jack Lundquist. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Disneyland's employees included the comic Steve  
Martin, who got his start at the Main Street Magic Shop, and former 
Nixon press secretary Ron Ziegler, who worked the Jungle Cruise. 
</P>
<P>
	When France's eyesight began to fade 15 years ago, France took  
the bus to work. His experiences led him to write ``The Bus and I: 
The Diary of a Reformed Autoholic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all in your attitude,'' he once said. ``Riding a bus is  
better than Zen. You become adjusted to other people and 
circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote scores of self-help books for the elderly and ``A  
Window on Main Street,'' a memoir about his years at Disneyland. 
</P>
<P>
	France went into semi-retirement in the 1980s. He continued to  
work as a consultant until his death. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by two children and several grandchildren.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
