<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Courts Hispanic Vote in Wash. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- Courting the Hispanic vote with children  
too young to cast a ballot but old enough to talk to their parents, 
Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush read to students and 
played marbles Friday at a Yakima elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31 million Hispanics living in the United States are the  
fastest-growing minority group and potentially influential voting 
bloc, which polls show tend to favor Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's muy importante,'' Bush, the governor of Texas, said when  
asked how critical the Hispanic vote would be in next year's 
presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Friday, he received star billing in Seattle at the  
National Federation of Republican Women's last convention before 
the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates cheered his presentation of himself as one of ``a  
rising generation of Republican leaders who are not just explaining 
problems, we are solving them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Welfare reform, crime bills and economic expansion are hallmarks  
of Republican leadership, he said in a speech that contained no 
specific policy proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	He called for limited, but compassionate government, with help  
for those who need it, but lower taxes and a leaner, less 
regulation-happy bureaucracy. He also called for worldwide free 
trade and warned against isolationism. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's wife Laura, a member of the group's Texas chapter, will  
speak on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, Bush spent about 90 minutes at the 500-student  
Garfield Elementary School, which is 76 percent Hispanic and 81 
percent minority overall. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief media availability, Bush said he favored changes to  
current guest-worker laws, which would make it easier for foreign 
workers to enter this country temporarily, and that he opposed a 
new amnesty program for illegal immigrants in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are heavily debated topics in agricultural Yakima County,  
where growers depend on migrant labor. Growers have said they would 
like changes in guest-worker laws that would improve access to 
legal workers from Mexico. Some migrant worker advocates have 
opposed such changes and are seeking a new amnesty program instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there ought to be amnesty at this time,'' Bush  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who exhibited the same ease with children that his father,  
former President George Bush, seems to have, selected a book called 
``The Very Hungry Caterpillar'' to read to a group of first-graders 
at Garfield. 
</P>
<P>
	He watched others work on computers and then made a couple of  
shots in the weekly marble tournament here. He told the students 
that when he attended Sam Houston Elementary School, ``I thought I 
was a pretty cool marble shooter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He missed his first shot, however, but made up for it on a  
second try. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
