<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM, Suzuki Plan Car for Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- American automaker General Motors Corp. will  
produce a small passenger vehicle it has developed with Suzuki 
Motor Corp. for sale in the Asian market starting in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The new model, called the YGM-1, is based on Suzuki's new small  
car platform and GM's design engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	Both GM and Suzuki, which is 10 percent owned by the U.S.  
automaker, said Friday they haven't decided where in Asia the YGM 
will be manufactured and refused to say how many vehicles they 
expect to produce a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still studying locations,'' said Rudolph A. Schlais  
Jr., president of GM Asia Pacific. But he added the automakers hope 
to make a decision soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshio Saito, chairman of Suzuki, said the company's Kosai plant  
southwest of Tokyo is ``one of the possible options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schlais said the car is likely to be sold in Japan and  
Australia, but that the companies are also looking into other 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The YGM will be GM's first passenger car to be manufactured in  
Asia for the Asian market. The car will be aimed at buyers between 
the ages of 30 and 35. 
</P>
<P>
	Schlais said the YGM reflects GM's commitment to the Asia  
region, which he estimates will become the second largest 
automotive market in the next 10 years, with sales approaching 20 
million vehicles a year. 
</P>
<P>
	GM aims to raise its market share in the region from 4 percent  
to 10 percent over the next five years. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
