<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader To Visit Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- President Jiang Zemin will discuss China's bid to  
enter the World Trade Organization with leaders of Britain, France 
and Portugal next week and will sign an oil agreement during a 
visit to Saudi Arabia, Chinese Foreign Ministry officials said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang leaves Monday on a two-week trip, first to the three  
European countries and then to Morocco, Algeria and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights protests are expected during Jiang's visit to  
Europe, which has become routine when Chinese leaders travel to 
Western countries. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news briefing today, Guan Chengyuan, deputy head of the  
Western European section of the ministry, hinted that the trip 
wasn't expected to seal a deal on China's bid to enter the WTO. The 
European Union, the United States and Canada are pressing China to 
open its markets wider before it can join the trade rules-making 
body. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit's purpose is ceremonial, Guan said, ``not to reach an  
agreement on detailed issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang will be accompanied by Foreign Trade Minister Shi  
Guangsheng, who recently resumed negotiations with the EU on 
China's WTO bid. 
</P>
<P>
	China broke off WTO talks with the EU and the United States  
after NATO accidentally bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on 
May 7. Talks with the United States resumed recently after a break 
of more than four months. 
</P>
<P>
	Guan refused to comment when asked whether the bombing was still  
troubling relations with NATO countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang's visit to London and Cambridge will be the first by a  
Chinese head of state to England. He will leave for Paris on Oct. 
22 and begin a two-day visit to Portugal on Oct. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Portuguese colony of Macau set to return to Chinese  
control on Dec. 20, China wants to show its hopes for a smooth 
transfer of power, Guan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The second part of Jiang's trip is designed to show China's  
desire for good ties with Islamic countries in the Arab world, said 
a ministry official with the division of West Asian and North 
African Affairs. China also wants to talk about buying more Saudi 
oil and the possibility of joint development of a refinery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
