<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marshall Looking for Perfect Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Small school. Undefeated season. Top 10  
finish. Marshall is looking to steal Tulane's act. 
</P>
<P>
	Tulane rose from the obscurity of Conference USA last year to go  
undefeated, win the Liberty Bowl and finish ranked No. 7. It has 
given Marshall hope that small can indeed make it big. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 15 Marshall, which hails from the little-recognized  
Mid-American Conference, is 6-0 following Thursday night's 38-13 
victory over Toledo. With four of five remaining games against 
teams with losing records, Marshall also is looking for a perfect 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tulane probably paved the way for some smaller schools to jump  
into the bigger arena quickly and get some recognition,'' Marshall 
receivers coach Gunter Brewer said. ``We feel like here we've been 
a great secret for a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The similarities don't end with the two programs.  
</P>
<P>
	Tulane quarterback Shaun King finished in the top 10 in  
balloting for the Heisman Trophy last year. Marshall believes it 
has a legitimate candidate in Chad Pennington. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennington has completed 63 percent of his passes for 1,962  
yards and 17 scores. He ranks second in Division I-A passing 
efficiency behind Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	His 393 yards against Toledo gave him 11,316 for his career,  
moving him ahead of Tennessee's Peyton Manning into eighth place on 
the NCAA's passing list. 
</P>
<P>
	Want more? In 1997, Pennington broke Tim Couch of Kentucky's  
NCAA record for sophomores with 39 TD passes. 
</P>
<P>
	With 95 career touchdown passes, he is looking to become just  
the 11th college quarterback to throw for 100 scores. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a lot of poise and accuracy,'' Toledo coach Gary  
Pinkel said. ``He's a veteran now. He does a lot of checks at the 
line. He can throw any kind of ball. He's a class act all the 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pennington doesn't want himself or Marshall to ride anyone's  
coattails. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were saying we were the '99 version of Tulane. But we  
just want to be the '99 version of Marshall,'' he said. ``We don't 
want to be compared to anybody. We want to set our own standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Tulane had a losing record just a few years earlier,  
Marshall has enjoyed a decade of success. Its 107 victories in the 
1990s are a record for any decade in Division I-A or I-AA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thundering Herd also have Division I-A's longest overall  
winning streak at 10 games and the best home winning streak of 28 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall has three road games left this season. While the  
Thundering Herd are 10-3 on the road since 1997, surprises 
occasionally happen. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago Marshall started 8-0 and was on the verge of cracking  
the Top 25 for the first time before it was upset by 2-5 Bowling 
Green. 
</P>
<P>
	So don't blame Thundering Herd players if they refrain from  
jumping for joy. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a team we have to stay focused and realize we're no better  
than our last performance,'' Pennington said. ``We need to keep 
pressing forward and realize that there are some crazy things that 
go on in college football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall and Toledo have met in the title game the past two  
seasons with the Thundering Herd winning both times to earn an 
automatic berth in the Motor City Bowl in Pontiac, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	There is talk that Marshall should consider bypassing the Motor  
City if it wins the rest of its games to play in a more prestigious 
bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bob Pruett isn't willing to turn his back on the bowl that  
has welcomed his team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to get involved in that. If we can get to the  
Ford Motor City Bowl, we'll be extremely pleased. That means we'll 
have won the conference,'' he said. ``We're very honored and 
tickled that we got to go there twice, and I hope we get to go 
again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
