<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls' Armstrong To Have Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Bulls guard B.J. Armstrong will have  
arthroscopic surgery on his left knee, a procedure that could keep 
him out of action for 2-4 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once he has the procedure, we will get the swelling down, get  
his strength back, get his range of motion back,'' Bulls trainer 
Fred Tedeschi said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who wanted to avoid the operation, is disappointed.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was able to practice (Wednesday and Thursday), but I still  
felt the irritation,'' he said. ``I don't know if I can do that for 
82 games with that irritation there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who signed with the Bulls as a free agent in August,  
was a member of the 1991, 1992 and 1993 championship teams. 
</P>
<P>
	An 11-year veteran, Armstrong has had operations on both his  
knees. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you keep playing and you keep jumping and bouncing and  
running and cutting, you know you only have so many jumps,'' he 
said. ``When they told me that at 18, I didn't understand. But at 
32 I understand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Toni Kukoc and guard Randy Brown have also been hurting  
during the past week of two-a-day practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Kukoc sat out Wednesday morning's practice with swelling in his  
right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulls coach Tim Floyd said he has no plans to back off from the  
workload. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have an awful lot of young guys who need reps and  
there's no other way to get them,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
