<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cincinnati Wants Gun Suit Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The city on Friday appealed a judge's  
dismissal of its lawsuit against firearms manufacturers, which 
demanded reimbursement for the costs of providing police, 
emergency, court and prison services for shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Robert Ruehlman of Hamilton County Common Pleas Court  
dismissed the lawsuit Oct. 7, ruling that it was vague or not 
supported by law or prior court decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first dismissal of a suit brought against gun makers  
by a municipality. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley Chesley, representing the city, said Cincinnati deserves  
the opportunity to review documents and take statements from gun 
industry officials so a jury can examine safety issues and 
marketing practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The City Council voted 5-4 on Wednesday to file the appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed against gun manufacturers, a distributor  
and three trade associations. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven other municipalities and two states are pursuing  
similar lawsuits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
