<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Charged With Marine's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine officer was charged with  
negligent homicide in the death of a corporal during a hike in 
July, with an investigator saying he marched his group too fast, 
with not enough time for breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Victor A. Arana, 28, faced an Article 32 hearing Thursday,  
which is similar to a civilian grand jury. The hearing will be 
concluded at a later date at the request of Arana's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Arana also has been charged with dereliction of duty and failing  
to obey a lawful order, according to a statement from Camp Lejeune, 
where the hearing took place. 
</P>
<P>
	A camp spokesman, Lt. Nick Ritzcovan, said such charges are rare  
following a training exercise death. ``Obviously it doesn't happen 
very often,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arana, whose hometown was not available, is formerly the  
commanding officer of the unit at the base's School of Infantry to 
which Lance Cpl. Giuseppe Leto, 21, was assigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Leto, of New Milford, Conn., had insisted on completing the  
night conditioning hike July 8 even though he showed signs of 
heat-related stress, authorities said. But after he finished, he 
wandered off and collapsed. He wasn't found until two hours later, 
and efforts to revive him failed. Base spokesman Capt. James Rich 
did not know the result of an autopsy. 
</P>
<P>
	Arana marched his men faster than specified in training  
guidelines, didn't allow enough time for breaks during the hike, 
and went home when the march was completed rather than remaining 
with the unit, according to the investigator's report. 
</P>
<P>
	A Marine sergeant was faulted for not promptly taking a head  
count at the completion of the hike. That likely would have 
revealed that Leto had wandered off, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report at least appears to be very candid in its  
content,'' said Roland Moots, the Leto family's attorney. ``I'll be 
meeting with the Leto family next week, and at that time, we'll 
have a better idea where we're going with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigator, Lt. Col. Joseph D. Provenzano, also  
recommended changes in training procedures that would permit more 
effective monitoring of Marines experiencing heat-related 
illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Provenzano interviewed more than 30 Marines who were on the  
hike. Both Arana and the sergeant cited in the report declined to 
give statements. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
