<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Keyes Rejects Electability Argument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- Commentator Alan Keyes said Friday that  
people who reject his Republican presidential campaign simply 
because they believe he has little chance of winning are ``very 
stupid'' and are sacrificing their vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Haven't you figured out yet if you never vote for what you  
believe, it can't possibly win?'' Keyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes spoke during a taping of Iowa Public Television's ``Iowa  
Press.'' The program airs Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	He was questioned about conservatives who find his fiery message  
appealing but worry about wasting their votes on a candidate with 
little chance of actually winning the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who give in to that logic are either very stupid or  
they're insincere,'' Keyes said. ``To put not too fine a point on 
it, that position is stupid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes offers a conservative message, saying that the nation's  
moral fiber is crumbling, and he has one of the most eloquent 
speaking styles of any of the candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last election cycle, Keyes got 7 percent of the vote in  
Iowa's leadoff caucuses, and most polls rank him about at that 
level this time. That's led many conservatives to look to other 
candidates who can make a stronger case that they can win the GOP 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see it all the time,'' Keyes said. ``I'll say it very  
bluntly to them. I say it to my audiences. 'How stupid can you 
be?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes said he has had success winning over audiences after he  
makes that case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once people pause, I've never had an audience that once I've  
said that, the light bulb didn't go on,'' Keyes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes also campaigns on a conservative theme,  
but contends that he has the money to compete with the Republican 
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Keyes dismissed that 
argument. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think money has an impact,'' Keyes said. ``I'm not sure it's  
as decisive as people say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes noted that he spent little on Iowa's caucuses in the last  
election and got 7 percent of the vote. Forbes spent over $4 
million and got 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``That tells you something,'' Keyes said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
