<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Worries Shock Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The biggest jump in wholesale prices in nine  
years and new worries by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
about the sky-high stock market sent shock waves through U.S. and 
global markets on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors from Tokyo to Wall Street were unnerved, first by  
Greenspan's comments about the threat of a possible ``bursting 
bubble'' of stock prices and then by a government report showing a 
surge in inflation at the wholesale level. Prices for energy, food, 
tobacco and new cars all rose in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average ended the day down 266.90  
points, or 2.6 percent, at 10,019.71, its biggest point drop in 
more than a year. Friday's decline put the average down 1,306 
points from its Aug. 25 high, a drop of 11.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets were primed to react in a negative fashion to  
Greenspan's comments, given that investors are on heightened alert 
to possible future Fed interest rate increases. The central bank 
has already boosted its federal funds rate, the interest commercial 
banks charge each other, twice this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists said a third rate increase on Nov. 16, when Fed  
policy-makers next meet, is all but certain, especially if upcoming 
statistics show the economy still growing strongly with rising 
inflation pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in Tokyo quickly noted Greenspan's cautionary words on  
the stock market Thursday night, with the Nikkei average falling 
178.69 points, a loss of 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The events Friday were reminiscent of the impact another late  
night Greenspan speech had in December 1996 when the Fed chief 
first worried that investors could be in the grips of ``irrational 
exuberance,'' a comment that sent stocks diving around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Dow average has soared by 57 percent since that time,  
Greenspan has returned with regularity to worries that American 
investors and the economy at large are vulnerable to a stock market 
``bubble,'' inflated prices that could plunge quickly and without 
warning. 
</P>
<P>
	``History tells us that sharp reversals occur abruptly, most  
often with little advance notice,'' Greenspan said this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether Dutch tulip bulbs or Russian equities, the market  
price patterns remain much the same,'' Greenspan said. He was 
referring to last year's plunge in Russian markets that rocked 
investors worldwide and to the 17th century plunge in inflated 
tulip bulb prices, one of the most famous speculative market 
frenzies of all time. 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists said Greenspan is becoming increasingly  
worried that the long period of U.S. prosperity is lulling 
investors and the banks that lend them money into a false sense of 
security that will spell serious trouble during a major market 
correction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Greenspan is worried about the other side of the wealth  
mountain,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo in 
Minneapolis. ``It has been fun climbing up the mountain, but a 
major correction could have a wrenching effect on the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Jones, economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co., said he  
believed the Fed will boost interest rates another quarter-point in 
November and then push rates up twice more in the first half of 
next year, pressing ever more firmly on the monetary brakes to slow 
economic activity and relieve rising inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration sought to reassure Americans that the  
1.1 percent jump in the Producer Price Index, which measures 
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was a temporary 
blip and not an indication of trouble down the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still feel the overall, basic fundamentals in the economy  
are quite strong,'' said Gene Sperling, director of the National 
Economic Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said they do not believe that a string of Fed rate  
hikes will derail the current expansion, which is already the 
longest in peacetime history, unless inflation zooms higher than 
expected, forcing the Fed to slam even harder on the brakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said another reason for the timing of Greenspan's remarks  
on the markets may be his worries about overconfidence generated by 
investment books such as ``Dow 36,000'' which argues that 
fundamental changes in the economy can keep the Dow rising to even 
greater heights. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan in a speech Friday also voiced optimism that economic  
growth can continue, despite the potential threat of disruptions 
from the Year 2000 computer date changeover. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
