<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Downed Lines Kill 5 in Florida  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Five pedestrians were electrocuted by downed power  
lines in Florida Friday, as Hurricane Irene drenched the state with 
up to 18 inches of rain. Scores of streets in Miami were flooded 
and 1.4 million people had no power. In neighboring Broward County, 
where streets also had 2 to 6 inches of water, three teen-agers and 
a woman in her 50s were electrocuted in an intersection after a 
power line fell, said Broward County Fire Rescue spokesman Todd 
LeDuc. Minutes later a child was electrocuted in another part of 
the county. 

</P>
<P>
	Ailing Doctor Rescued at South Pole  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) -- A U.S. military plane rescued  
an American doctor from the South Pole on Saturday, five months 
after she found a lump in her breast but remained stranded by 
subzero temperatures. The LC-130 Hercules from the New York Air 
National Guard's 109th Airlift Wing left McMurdo station on the 
Antarctic coast and took roughly three hours to reach the 
Amundsen-Scott South Pole Research Station. After a 22-minute stop 
to pick up Dr. Jerri Nielsen, 47, the plane returned to McMurdo, 
making the 1,600-mile roundtrip flight in six hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbine Killer's Parents Plan Suit  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The parents of Columbine High School gunman Dylan  
Klebold alleged Friday that Jefferson County authorities are partly 
responsible for the April school shooting rampage that left 15 
people dead. An attorney for Thomas and Susan Klebold served notice 
of their intent to sue the county's sheriff and two other sheriff's 
officials for negligence. The Klebolds say authorities never told 
them about the potentially violent tendencies of the other gunman, 
Eric Harris, 18, and his relationship with their 17-year-old son. 
The pair hurled bombs and scattered gunfire throughout the school, 
killing 12 students and a teacher before committing suicide. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore's Payroll Beats Them All  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As he runs for president, Al Gore pays more  
for staff than any other candidate, an analysis of his latest 
campaign spending report shows. The Democrat has spent $14.6 
million and had $10.3 million in the bank through Sept. 30. He 
raised $24.9 million, but $534,293 came from his general election 
fund for legal and accounting expenses to pay a share of 
fund-raising costs. Bradley has raised less than Gore, $19.2 
million. But he has spent less as well, $8.5 million, giving him a 
larger bank account -- $10.7 million. Gore, for example, has spent 
twice as much on polling, $387,844 to $173,189. 

</P>
<P>
	Chile Braces for Pinochet Protests  
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Supporters of Gen. Augusto Pinochet  
rallied on Friday for the release of the former dictator. 
Meanwhile, police braced for a weekend of protests to mark the 
first anniversary of his arrest in Britain. Both foes and 
supporters of the 83-year-old general announced plans to observe 
Saturday's anniversary with rallies in several Chilean cities. One 
year later, Pinochet's arrest in London continues to stir emotional 
-- and potentially violent -- reactions in his South American 
homeland. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Dives 266.90, Closes at 10,019.71  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrials briefly fell below  
10,000 today on news of an inflationary spurt and a warning about 
stock market exuberance from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan. The Dow ended down 266.90 points at 10,019.71, its worst 
closing level since early April. The selloff followed a morning 
report showing that prices at the wholesale level rose 1.1 percent 
in September, the largest increase in nine years. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 2,400-687. The Nasdaq was at 2,731.79, down 
75.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain Memorials Scheduled  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A memorial service for basketball great Wilt  
Chamberlain was scheduled for 10 a.m. tomorrow at The City of 
Angels Church of Religious Science near Marina del Rey. A second 
memorial service will take place Thursday at Mount Carmel Baptist 
Church in Philadelphia, just blocks from the high school where 
Chamberlain first achieved fame on the basketball court. The 
7-foot-1 center, whose dominance changed the game, died Tuesday of 
heart failure at his Bel-Air home. He was 63. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Blank Mets 1-0  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tom Glavine quietly pitched the Atlanta Braves  
to the brink of another World Series. Glavine pitched seven 
innings, making an unearned run in the first stand up, and the 
Braves silenced boisterous Shea Stadium with a 1-0 victory over the 
Mets in Game 3 of the NL Championship Series on Friday night. 
Atlanta, which leads the best-of-7 series 3-0, can advance to its 
first World Series since 1996 when John Smoltz pitches against New 
York's Rick Reed on Saturday night, looking to finish off a Braves' 
sweep. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
