<HEADLINE> Bonds Turn Higher on Stock Selloff / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose sharply Friday, breaking a  
three session losing streak, as investors sought safety of 
government-backed debt amid a major selloff in stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 27/32 point, or  
$8.43 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 6.26 percent from Thursday's 6.32 
percent, which was the highest for 30-year Treasurys since hitting 
6.42 percent on Oct. 22, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasurys initially fell Friday morning on a surprisingly sharp  
rise in prices at the wholesale level, but bonds later rallied as 
stocks plunged and investors sought a haven for their money. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were unsettled by comments Thursday night by Federal  
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who warned investors may be 
underestimating risks in the market. On top of those jitters, the 
government reported Friday morning that the Producer Price Index 
spiked 1.1 percent in September, the largest increase in nine 
years. The increase in the index that measures inflation pressures 
before they reach the consumer, was much worse than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities were up 5/32 point to  
7/32 point while intermediate maturities rose 7/16 point to 23/32 
point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.04 percent as the  
discount rose 0.03 percentage point from Thursday to 4.91 percent. 
Six-month yields were 5.15 percent, as the discount was unchanged 
at 4.95 percent. One-year yields were 5.40 percent as the discount 
fell 0.04 percentage point to 5.10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate rose to 5.31 percent from 5.25 percent  
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 109 15/32 from 110 19/32 late 
Thursday. The average yield to maturity was unchanged at 6.06 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
