<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Piazza Banged Up Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Piazza's sore left hand took a beating in  
Game 3 of the NL Championship Series on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, who missed the final two games of the first-round series  
with a swollen left thumb, was hit on the knuckle of his left 
pinkie by Gerald Williams' backswing. 
</P>
<P>
	He also sustained a slight concussion when Bret Boone collided  
with him trying to score in the first inning. Piazza held the ball, 
and Boone was out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still a little woozy,'' Piazza said. ``I've had worse. It  
was a good play, it was a clean play. He got me pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza remembered Williams hitting him before.  
</P>
<P>
	``He got me last year, too,'' Piazza said. ``Armando (Benitez)  
throws pretty hard. I think he was swinging with a little bit 
extra.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHANGING ORDER:* Mets manager Bobby Valentine shook up his  
lineup, inserting rookie Melvin Mora, who had his first major 
league home run in Game 2, in center field and changing the batting 
order. 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman John Olerud and second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo  
swapped spots in the lineup, Olerud batting second and Alfonzo 
third, and slumping third baseman Robin Ventura was dropped to No. 
6, behind Benny Agbayani, who started in right field. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, Valentine said, was to space out the left-handed  
hitters with three right-handed bats between Olerud at No. 2 and 
Ventura at No. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said he didn't plan to move Alfonzo back to No. 2 in  
Game 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any reason to,'' he said. ``Do you think that's  
why we didn't get any hits? Someone might be silly enough or dumb 
enough to think that, but not me.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JUST ANOTHER GAME:* Rick Reed, who starts Game 4 for the Mets  
on Saturday night says he won't be shaken by the significance of 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider it a big game,'' Reed said. ``I'm going to  
approach it as an ordinary game. I can't go in with that kind of 
attitude and put more pressure on myself than there already is. So 
I think I'm going to try to approach it as an ordinary game and see 
what happens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to get caught up in it being the big game.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TENSION TIME:* John Smoltz has always flourished in the  
postseason for Atlanta, and he believes it's because of how the 
games are viewed 
</P>
<P>
	``When a runner gets on base in the regular season, it's no big  
deal,'' he said. ``When a runner gets on first in the postseason, 
it's a rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is magnified.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHO'S WHO:* Walt Weiss started at shortstop for Atlanta but in  
the pregame lineups distributed in the press box, he was identified 
as ``Al Weiss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al Weis, a utility infielder, was the MVP for the Mets when they  
won the World Series in 1969. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
