<HEADLINE> 'Rainbow Warrior' Executed in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POINT OF THE MOUNTAIN, Utah (AP) -- A man whom prison officials  
said called himself ``The Rainbow Warrior'' -- a killer of 
homosexuals -- was executed by injection today for stabbing another 
man to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Held by thick leather straps and with intravenous lines running  
to his arms, Joseph Mitchell Parsons was relaxed as he spoke his 
last words. 
</P>
<P>
	``My love to my family and friends. And Woody, the Rainbow  
Warrior rules!'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prison spokesman Jack Ford said Parsons referred to himself as  
``The Rainbow Warrior'' in a letter to family, and 'Woody' is the 
nickname for his fellow death row inmate and friend Doug Lovell. 
</P>
<P>
	The rainbow flag is a symbol for the gay community.  
</P>
<P>
	In Texas on Thursday, a man who nicknamed himself ``Animal'' was  
executed by injection for raping and killing an 18-year-old high 
school cheerleader, one of three people killed during a daylong 
murder spree in 1986. Jerry McFadden, 51, made no final statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Parsons, 35, was picked up by Richard Ernest while hitchhiking  
outside Barstow, Calif., in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ernest was killed and robbed hours later.  
Parsons said he stabbed Ernest in self-defense after the other man 
made a sexual advance, but prosecutors said the wounds appeared to 
have been inflicted while Ernest was sleeping. 
</P>
<P>
	Parsons was the sixth man executed in Utah since the Supreme  
Court reinstated capital punishment in 1972. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
