<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Court Strikes School Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- A new property tax setup created to pay for  
New Hampshire's schools was ruled unconstitutional Friday, renewing 
the possibility that the Live Free or Die State will have to 
institute an income tax. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court ruled that the way the tax was to be  
phased in amounted to an unfair break for richer communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jeanne Shaheen said it was unfortunate the court didn't  
give the new system a chance to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``By striking down the statewide property tax, the court has  
endangered our ability to keep schools operating,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision creates a huge hole in the budget -- more than half  
of the $825 million promised for education this year was to come 
from the property tax. Schools had been getting money under the 
plan since July. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it obviously puts the income tax more back into  
play,'' said state Sen. Clifton Below, a Democrat who sponsored an 
income tax bill last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers were forced to come up with the new school-funding  
system after New Hampshire's high court ruled in 1997 that the 
state unfairly relied on local property taxes, which vary widely 
from town to town. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers considered an income tax to pay for schools, but the  
governor promised a veto. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire and Alaska are the only two states with no general  
income tax or sales tax, and anti-tax sentiment in New Hampshire 
runs high. 
</P>
<P>
	So lawmakers came up with a careful compromise -- a new system  
that relied mainly on a uniform statewide property tax of $6.60 per 
$1,000 of property value. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 towns with lower tax rates -- mostly those with more  
expensive property -- had to raise the rates to the statewide level 
and send the extra money to the state, which was to have 
distributed it to poor towns. 
</P>
<P>
	To soften the blow, the Legislature phased in the increase over  
five years in these richer communities. The state said the phase-in 
would avoid economic disruption -- including bankruptcies and 
foreclosures -- that would occur with abrupt tax increases. 
</P>
<P>
	But some poorer communities went to court to challenge the plan,  
saying the phase-in was unconstitutional because it gave tax breaks 
to entire towns without regard to whether individual taxpayers 
needed it. 
</P>
<P>
	The court agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is neither reasonable nor fair to award automatic tax  
exemptions to a majority of taxpayers in affected `property rich' 
communities who do not need them in order to assist those who would 
surely qualify,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court did not throw out the rest of the plan, including  
smaller taxes and tax increases. But it gutted the main source of 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision allows the Legislature to re-enact the property tax  
without the phase-in. It also could renew a push for an income tax. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991015.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 14:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tide Face Rebels in SEC Showdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- This game could be bigger than it already  
is for No. 11 Alabama and No. 22 Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider that both teams might be undefeated if not for  
unexpected losses on the same day about a month ago. Alabama and 
Ole Miss both blew leads in the final minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Saturday's game could still go a long way in determining  
the Southeastern Conference Western Division. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think this is the only game that will be definitive  
for us the rest of the season,'' Ole Miss coach David Cutcliffe 
said. ``Every game we play from here on out will be a big game. 
This game is obviously big because we already have a conference 
loss and they don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their 34-31 overtime loss to Vanderbilt on Sept. 18, the  
Rebels (5-1, 2-1 SEC) are off to their best start since 1990 and 
still have the opportunity to play the two teams that are sharing 
the SEC West lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama (4-1, 3-0) is tied for the SEC West lead with  
12th-ranked Mississippi State (6-0, 3-0), which has the weekend off 
and its best start in 55 years. The Rebels play their 
regular-season finale in Starkville on Thanksgiving night. 
</P>
<P>
	After a last-second loss to Louisiana Tech, Alabama's athletic  
director resigned. That left a cloud over coach Mike DuBose, who 
admitted he lied earlier in the year about an alleged affair with a 
department employee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crimson Tide have rebounded with victories over Arkansas and  
Florida. This will be Alabama's first game since a 40-39 overtime 
victory that snapped the Gators' 30-game home winning streak two 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm anxious to see if we've put the Florida game behind us,''  
DuBose said. ``Our football team and our staff have done a good job 
handling the adversity. Now how do you handle success?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's game in Oxford has been sold out since early in the  
summer, and the game will be televised nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama hasn't lost to Ole Miss on the field since 1988. A 19-14  
Crimson Tide victory in 1993 was ruled a forfeit victory for Ole 
Miss by the NCAA. The Crimson Tide has dominated the series 37-7-2 
</P>
<P>
	Ole Miss plans to put its defensive focus on stopping Alabama  
running back Shaun Alexander. Maybe the Rebels, who rank second 
nationally in rushing defense, can at least slow him. 
</P>
<P>
	In every game this season, Alexander has rushed for more than  
100 yards and has also scored 13 touchdowns -- 10 rushing and three 
receiving. In Alabama's only loss, he had a season-high 173 rushing 
yards and scored twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alexander continues to get better as the game goes on,''  
Cutcliffe said. ``He's good running the ball, he's good catching 
the ball. He is not easily tackled and not easily contained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ole Miss has allowed just 45 yards rushing a game. But the  
Rebels haven't faced any back as talented as Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to buckle down and key on him,'' Ole Miss linebacker  
Al Rice said. ``It will be their running game against our running 
defense ... just break it down and come to play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
