<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Accuses HUD of Manipulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee chairman says the Housing  
and Urban Development Department hired high-priced lawyers in an 
attempt to slant an investigation against the agency's inspector 
general, who has questioned Secretary Andrew Cuomo's policies. 
</P>
<P>
	HUD officials said they acted appropriately in seeking the best  
counsel in a discrimination complaint filed by the most senior 
black member of the inspector general's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Fred Thompson, chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs  
Committee, on Thursday issued a General Accounting Office report 
concluding that HUD had violated normal contracting procedures in 
hiring outside attorneys to look into the discrimination case. He 
said the attorneys had billed the government approximately $300,000 
for an inquiry that typically costs $3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said HUD had brought in lawyers more likely to be  
critical of Inspector General Susan Gaffney, who has clashed openly 
with Cuomo over HUD policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has clearly been an extraordinary effort to discredit  
this longtime public servant and to portray her as something she is 
not,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	HUD spokesman David Egner disputed the $300,000 figure, saying  
it was ``flat out wrong to say HUD has paid or will pay anything 
more than the $100,000 specified in its contracts for this 
investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	HUD's chief procurement officer, V. Stephen Carberry, also said  
it was appropriate to seek investigators with special expertise 
because ``charges of discrimination involving a high official are a 
serious matter that require a serious investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case involved a complaint filed by Deputy Assistant  
Inspector General Philip X. Newsome that Gaffney, in not selecting 
him for a promotion, discriminated against him because he is black. 
</P>
<P>
	The department initially contracted with a government-listed  
investigative firm to look into the complaint, at a cost of $2,700. 
</P>
<P>
	But GAO, looking into it at Thompson's request, found senior HUD  
officials stopped that inquiry in August 1998 and contracted with 
two outside law firms to investigate the specific charges and 
whether there was more systematic discrimination in the office. The 
firms were Day, Berry &AMP; Howard, LLP, and Williams &AMP; Connolly. 
</P>
<P>
	This decision ``was a significant deviation from HUD's standard  
Equal Employment Opportunity process,'' said GAO, the investigative 
arm of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Newsome has since taken his case to a federal court.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., head of the Congressional Black  
Caucus, defended HUD's decision to hire Deval Patrick -- a former 
Clinton administration assistant attorney general for civil rights 
-- to look into alleged racial problems in the inspector general's 
office. ``Anything less would have been a failure by HUD to meet 
its legal and moral obligations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gaffney has been at odds with Cuomo's top aides over attempts to  
reorganize HUD operations and initiate new housing and empowerment 
programs. There were also disputes over her office's selection of 
three cities run by black mayors as sites for an effort to uncover 
housing program corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Senate hearing in March, Gaffney said Cuomo was a ``very  
ambitious man'' who ``looks at me as a threat, as a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Secretary Saul Ramirez replied then that Gaffney had  
taken a ``destructive, attack approach'' to HUD. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
