<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stern: NBA Not Global-Ready Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- The NBA will work to develop a minor league  
system in the United States before looking to establish an overseas 
presence, commissioner David Stern said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way we now see the development of basketball around the  
world is encouraging,'' Stern said, ``but the NBA must develop a 
minor league in our country first, either expanding our 
relationship with the CBA or perhaps consider starting a league of 
our own in the next year to 18 months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He emphasized there is ``no specific program'' for expansion  
abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no current plans to have an NBA league on any  
particular continent, though we have received expressions of 
interest from Asia, South America and, to a lesser extent, 
Europe,'' Stern said. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke at a news conference before the semifinals of the  
McDonald's Championship, which he billed as ``an unofficial global 
club championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stern said he would like to see NBA teams play more games  
outside North America, but ``unless we invent some new ideas, the 
calendar for our interaction is limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month in Vancouver, Stern told reporters the NBA might  
place a developmental league abroad within five years, apparently 
signaling a shift in the league's position on overseas expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, the NBA insisted it preferred to support the  
development of foreign leagues and would not want to place its own 
product into those markets for fear of diminishing the home-grown 
commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, deputy commissioner Russ Granik said the early  
returns from preseason games have been positive on the NBA's effort 
to open up the game by limiting physical play. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game looks more fluid, there are more fastbreaks, more  
possessions, more shots,'' Granik said. ``We thought we would have 
a problem with a huge increase in the number of fouls. It's been 
about three or four (per game), which is not as bad as we feared 
might happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA is coming off the lowest-scoring season in its history,  
one in which only the Sacramento Kings averaged 100 points. The 
league-wide average of 91 points a game was the lowest since the 
shot clock was introduced in 1954-55. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
