<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knight Ridder Earnings Jump 34 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Knight Ridder, the nation's  
second-largest newspaper publisher, reported Friday that higher ad 
revenues and lower newsprint costs drove profits up 34 percent in 
the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight Ridder earned $76.2 million, or 78 cents a share, in the  
three-month period ending Sept. 26, up from $57 million, or 58 
cents a share, in the comparable period a year ago. Analysts 
surveyed by First Call/Thompson Financial had expected earnings of 
74 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The year-earlier earnings included $7 million in expenses  
associated with the company's move to San Jose, where its flagship 
newspaper, the San Jose Mercury News, is located. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 4.2 percent to $784.7 million from $752.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Knight Ridder cited a 19 percent drop in newsprint costs and a  
nearly 4 percent increase in advertising revenue across all its 
markets for the improved results. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Knight Ridder earned  
$225.7 million, or $2.31 a share, little changed from the $225.3 
million, or $2.29 a share, of a year earlier. The nine-month 
figures for both periods include several one-time gains and losses. 
Without those factors, per-share earnings rose almost 18 percent 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-month revenue rose 4 percent to $2.37 billion from $2.28  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight Ridder publishes 31 daily newspapers with a readership of  
9.2 million daily and 13 million Sunday. It also operates 45 Web 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Knight Ridder fell $1.50 to $56.75 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
