<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Arnold Injures Knee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers wide receiver Jahine  
Arnold is likely out for the season after slightly tearing the 
anterior cruciate ligament in his knee at practice Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold will have more tests before the Packers confirm his  
season is over. Arnold, who has not been active for a game this 
season, was one of the stars during the preseason for the Packers, 
catching five passes for 156 yards and two touchdowns. Both 
touchdown receptions were for 67 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	His preseason performance assured the Packers that if there was  
an injury to their top three wide receivers -- Antonio Freeman, Bill 
Schroeder or Corey Bradford -- Arnold could fill in. 
</P>
<P>
	But Arnold, who earned a reputation as a fragile player during  
three injury-filled seasons in Pittsburgh, confirmed the Packers' 
worst fears about him by getting injured during practice before 
ever suiting up in a game. He missed the 1997 season and most of 
1998 with a variety of ailments. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold was widely expected to play Sunday, perhaps helping  
Desmond Howard return kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The feeling from the coaching staff was that if we did have  
injury to another player, (Arnold) would step right in and you 
don't miss a beat,'' Packers coach Ray Rhodes said. ``In the 
preseason, he showed tremendous athletic ability and speed and made 
a lot of huge plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Arnold out, the Packers' receiving corps includes Freeman,  
Schroeder, Bradford, Howard and rookie Donald Driver, who also 
impressed during training camp and made the final roster. Green 
Bay, which usually activates four receivers for a game, also has 
rookie receiver Tyrone Goodson on the practice squad. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
