<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unser Jr.'s Daughter Undergoes Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The 12-year-old daughter of former Indy  
500 winner Al Unser Jr. is to return home Saturday after tests this 
week at Johns Hopkins in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Cody Unser has been battling transverse myelitis, a rare  
disorder that struck her in February and left her paralyzed from 
the chest down. The problem occurs when nerve impulse transmission 
up and down the spinal cord is blocked. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor said I'll walk again, but it will take time,'' Cody  
said in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The symptoms first appeared when Cody was playing basketball at  
her middle school and began to feel excessively tired and noticed 
her legs ``felt tingly.'' She was taken to a hospital and sent home 
after being evaluated. The next day, she could not walk, and 
returned to the hospital, paralyzed below her chest. 
</P>
<P>
	She then spent more than three weeks at the Barrow Neurological  
Institute in Phoenix before returning home. 
</P>
<P>
	Cody remains paralyzed but is able to walk with the aid of  
braces and has learned to scuba dive, her family said in a news 
release. She is pursuing seventh grade studies at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The tests at the Johns Hopkins Transverse Myelopathy Center  
began Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically she's just getting evaluated to confirm the  
diagnosis, to see what's functioning still,'' Marjorie Centofanti 
of Johns Hopkins media relations said Friday. ``She's had tests of 
nerve activity. She's now in with a physical therapist, to make the 
most of what remains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In September, paperwork was filed on Cody's behalf establishing  
the Cody Unser First Step Foundation, a nonprofit group aimed at 
raising research funds and awareness of transverse myelitis and 
spinal cord injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors don't know what causes transverse myelitis. It develops  
rapidly over several hours to several weeks, but most patients show 
fair to good recovery, according to information from the Transverse 
Myelitis Association. It may develop after certain types of acute 
infections or other problems. It also can develop on its own, 
possibly as the result of abnormal activation of the immune system 
against the spinal cord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
