<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Down After Fed Head Comments / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened sharply lower today  
following a warning from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
against excessive optimism by stock traders. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Industrial Average is down 52 points just minutes  
after the opening bell. Losers on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 5-2. The Nasdaq is also down, losing 63 points in early 
trading, while the S&AMP;P 500 is down seven points. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to bankers last night after markets closed,  
Greenspan urged continued vigilance in managing risk at a time of 
prosperity, robust economic expansion and roaring stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan has warned for years against excessive economic  
optimism that can lead to risky business decisions and his comments 
Thursday followed recent warnings by federal regulators that signs 
of risk are spreading in the banking industry despite high earnings 
and hefty assets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Economists have been unable to anticipate sharp reversals in  
confidence,'' Greenspan told a Washington conference organized by 
the Office of the Comptroller. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a minimum, risk managers need to ... set aside somewhat  
higher contingency resources ... to cover the losses that will 
inevitably emerge from time to time when investors suffer a loss of 
confidence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan also said that the decline in equity premiums that has  
kept U.S. stock prices rising in recent years could be temporary. 
</P>
<P>
	There are several negative influences for Wall Street this final  
session of the week, beginning with Greenspan remarks about 
riskiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Then add today's wholesale inflation report, showing the biggest  
increase in the Producer Price Index in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets have added to their earlier losses, but bond  
prices have stemmed their initial slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Also keep in mind that today is a so-called ``double witching''  
expiration session on Wall Street, meaning we should see more than 
the usual volatility in the market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
