<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rocker, Chipper Hear It at Shea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *BY HAL BOCK   	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chipper Jones, who beat up the New York Mets  
with his bat, and John Rocker, who started a verbal war with their 
fans, heard it at Shea Stadium before Game 3 of the National League 
Championship Series Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	During batting practice, Jones was razzed with chants of  
``Lar-ry, Lar-ry,'' by fans who hoped they would irritate him by 
using his given name instead of the nickname he prefers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker seemed to relish all the jeers his appearance generated.  
</P>
<P>
	Rocker emerged from the dugout knowing he would receive a rude  
reception from the early-arriving fans, one of whom held up a sign 
proclaiming, ``I Want To Fight John Rocker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pitcher walked slowly along the third-base stands, smiling,  
tipping his cap and waving to the fans. He even stopped to sign 
autographs for a couple of kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``It thrills me to no end that I can get in their heads like  
that,'' he said. ``If they were quiet, I would wonder what I was 
doing wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a pre-game interview on NBC, Rocker said the worst part of  
playing in New York was dealing with the fans who throw objects 
from the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only place it happens out of 30 ballparks around  
country, people making derogatory comments, throwing batteries and 
change, trying to do bodily harm. I just think someone needs to 
speak out and say that we don't need to hear those things or fear 
for our safety at a simple baseball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHANGING ORDER:* Mets manager Bobby Valentine shook up his  
lineup, inserting rookie Melvin Mora, who had his first major 
league home run in Game 2, in center field and changing the batting 
order. 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman John Olerud and second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo  
swapped spots in the lineup, Olerud batting second and Alfonzo 
third, and slumping third baseman Robin Ventura was dropped to No. 
6, behind Benny Agbayani, who started in right field. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, Valentine said, was to space out the left-handed  
hitters with three right-handed bats between Olerud at No. 2 and 
Ventura at No. 6. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JUST ANOTHER GAME:* Rick Reed, who starts Gamne 4 for the Mets  
Saturday night says he won't be shaken by the significance of the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider it a big game,'' Reed said.''I'm going to  
approach it as an ordinary game. I can't go in with that kind of 
attitude and put more pressure on myself than there already is. So 
I think I'm going to try to approach it as an ordinary game and see 
what happens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to get caught up in it being the big game.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TENSION TIME:* John Smoltz has always flourished in the  
postseason for Atlanta, and he believes it's because of how the 
games are viewed 
</P>
<P>
	``When a runner gets on base in the regular season, it's no big  
deal,'' he said. ``When a runner gets on first in the postseason, 
it's a rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is magnified.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHO'S WHO:* Walt Weiss started at shortstop for Atlanta but in  
the pregame lineups distributed in the press box, he was identified 
as ``Al Weiss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al Weis, a utility infielder, was the MVP for the Mets when they  
won the World Series in 1969. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
