<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Companies Vie for College Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- College students who might have been  
scrambling for job interviews just a few years ago are being wooed 
by company recruiters with pizza parties, picnics and expense-paid 
trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely a job seeker's market now,'' said Linda Bates  
Parker, director of the Career Development Center at the University 
of Cincinnati. ``Even four years ago, the students would have had 
to hold the parties and hope the companies would come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the economy strong and the job market tight, other colleges  
and universities around the nation are seeing a similar boom in 
recruitment -- and not just for students with engineering majors, 
high-tech skills or top grades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Employers are engaging students more directly with parties and  
sponsoring prize giveaways and contests,'' said Cynthia Applin, 
director of Career Planning and Placement at Case Western Reserve 
University in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Ajay Kachwaha, a senior majoring in finance at the University of  
Cincinnati, said he hasn't started his job search yet but already 
has been invited to several recruiting events. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult not to become a little complacent,'' he said.  
``I'm grateful to be graduating now, because even five years ago, I 
would have had to work a lot harder to find a job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Enterprise Rent-A-Car, based in St. Louis, held a remote-control  
car race to attract students. The company gave T-shirts to the 
winners and raffled off the cars after a recent race at UC. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Chalker, who directs recruiting efforts for the Troy,  
Mich.-based Delphi Automotive Systems, said his company sponsors 
international career symposiums to create name recognition and get 
information about the company out to students. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I started 10 years ago, companies were in control of the  
recruiting process,'' he said. ``Students sent out resumes and had 
to sell themselves to a company. Now companies are trying to sell 
themselves to students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norita Rehrig, assistant executive director of the National  
Association of Colleges and Employers in Bethlehem, Pa., said 
internships and co-ops are being used more and more as feeder 
programs for entry-level hiring with many interns being urged to 
return after graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know of at least one company that flew its interns to Disney  
World,'' she said. ``But while a lot of companies are coming up 
with more creative ways to attract students, those that also 
maintain a long-term presence on campus will be the most 
successful.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
