<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ogunleye, Dayne Facing Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Adelwale Ogunleye and Ron Dayne both passed  
on the riches of the NFL to return to school for their senior 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Although neither's season has gone according to expectations,  
both still claim they made the right choice. Others might see it 
differently. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana lost Ogunleye, a defensive end and the school's career  
leader in sacks and tackles for losses, for the season when he 
sustained severe knee ligament damage in the 34-17 victory over 
Northwestern last week. Ogunleye's draft stock will almost 
certainly fall, though it's too early to say how much. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could come back from this injury as good as ever,'' Indiana  
coach Cam Cameron said. ``There's no way to know right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne returned to Wisconsin for a chance at a national  
championship and to take a shot at the NCAA major college rushing 
record. Two losses have squashed any title hopes, and a string of 
good-but-not-great rushing performances have put Dayne's quest for 
Ricky Williams' record in jeopardy as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I get it, that would be great,'' Dayne said of the record.  
``If not, it won't be the end of the world. I still got a lot of 
great things out of coming back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne needs 864 yards over Wisconsin's final five games to break  
Williams' record. That computes to an average of 172.8 yards per 
game, a number he has reached only once this season against 
defenses designed to stop him. 
</P>
<P>
	The tailback, who has endured a number of minor injuries and two  
poor performances this season, would have entered last spring's 
draft on the strength of a dominating performance in Wisconsin's 
win over UCLA in the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Dayne is averaging only slightly better than 4.0  
yards per carry during the Badgers' first three Big Ten games. But 
a surge in productivity could put Wisconsin in the running for a 
New Year's Day bowl game and Dayne back in the Heisman Trophy race. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana (3-3, 2-1 Big Ten) will be gunning for Dayne on Saturday  
at Camp Randall Stadium. But the loss of Ogunleye, who was having 
another exceptional season, will hurt the Hoosiers' chances of 
beating the 17th-ranked Badgers (4-2, 2-1) for the first time since 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always said that if it happens, no matter what, I won't  
regret the decision,'' Ogunleye said. ``Life is not just football. 
I think this injury proves it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without Ogunleye, Indiana's pass rushers will be hard-pressed to  
generate any problems for quarterback Brooks Bollinger behind 
Wisconsin's mammoth, experienced offensive line. Senior Chris 
McIntosh said the line has taken Saturday's game as a personal 
challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really need to get our job done this week, both on passing  
and running downs,'' said McIntosh, himself a sure NFL draft pick. 
``We always feel like we can be doing a better job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Indiana's run defense has been depleted, its pass defense  
is still the best in the Big Ten, allowing just 162.7 yards per 
game. That's not good news for the Badgers, who have struggled to 
throw the ball under the best of circumstances this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully we'll be able to get some throwing of the ball done  
and open it up for Ron,'' offensive coordinator Brian White said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez, who had knee surgery two weeks  
ago and is unable to walk, will watch the game from the press box, 
the school announced late Friday. Alvarez monitored the Badgers' 
20-17 overtime win over Minnesota last week from his hospital bed 
at the Mayo Clinic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
