<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spirits Not Dampened by Hurricane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Sue Gallup was living proof that the party  
spirit in this laid-back resort city was drenched but not dampened 
Friday by Hurricane Irene. 
</P>
<P>
	At Jimmy Buffett's Margaritaville Cafe, loud cheers greeted the  
return of electricity after the storm center passed nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in a red tropical-print shirt and sipping a pink drink,  
Ms. Gallup, who is from Canterbury, N.H., was happy to be in town 
for the annual Jimmy Buffett convention, whether or not its 
namesake singer showed up. (He did last year.) 
</P>
<P>
	``This is fun. This is wonderful,'' said the loyal Parrothead,  
the nickname preferred by Buffett fans. ``It's actually more 
exciting than having it sunny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten inches of rain flooded the Duval Street tourist strip and  
most other streets on the island, but the high water couldn't keep 
visitors away, even though they were asked to leave the Florida 
Keys on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get busier when the power goes out,'' said Margaritaville  
bartender Doug Gober. ``There's nothing to do but drink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While tourists homed in on the bars, business owners rushed to  
reopen by sweeping away floodwaters and leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we get electricity, we're going full speed ahead,''  
kitchen manager Gus Trippner said at Kelly's Caribbean Bar and 
Grill, owned by actress Kelly McGillis. ``We have generators hooked 
up to the freezer and iceboxes. The rest of it is praying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The storm intruded just before the start of the tourist season  
for this gay-friendly resort, which has long been an outpost for 
the offbeat and was the home of Ernest Hemingway. The Halloween 
week Fantasy Fest draws thousands of costumed revelers to masked 
balls, costume competitions, street fairs and other events. 
</P>
<P>
	Odile and Hans Von Gunten, tourists from Paris, spent their time  
people watching during the storm. ``We have never seen this,'' Ms. 
Von Gunter said. ``The people are interesting because they act like 
this is normal.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
