<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases Arab Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEITUNIYA, West Bank (AP) -- Israel freed 151 Arab security  
prisoners today, moving its peace agreement with the Palestinians 
back on track after minor delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheering relatives greeted convoys of buses at drop-off points  
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Prisoners leaned out of windows, 
flashing victory signs, their hands still tied with plastic cuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mother, he's out,'' a teen-age boy shouted into a cellular  
phone when he saw his brother on one of the buses. 
</P>
<P>
	Prisoner releases are an emotional issue for both sides.  
Palestinians consider the inmates heroes in the struggle for 
independence, while a majority of Israelis still strongly oppose 
freeing those who killed Israelis in terror attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the latest interim peace agreement, Israel freed 199  
security prisoners in September and pledged to release another 
group of 151 on Oct. 8. The second release was delayed by 
last-minute disputes over who is eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those freed today were 109 Palestinians and 42 inmates  
from Arab countries. Seventy-five were serving life sentences, 
among them 44 who had killed fellow Arabs on suspicion of 
collaboration with Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	One prisoner, Nasser Abu Hmeid, killed nine suspected  
collaborators. Israel radio said he was released at the personal 
request of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu Hmeid, 27, said he had mixed feelings. ``Thousands of my  
brothers are still in jail, living in very terrible conditions,'' 
he said. ``Israel is turning these releases into a big deal, but 
the important people are still behind bars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most prisoners belonged to Arafat's Fatah movement, while 10  
were members of Hamas and Islamic Jihad, militant groups that 
oppose the peace agreements. Israel initially refused to free 
Islamic militants, but then softened its criteria. 
</P>
<P>
	At a dropoff point near the village of West Bank of Beituniya,  
relatives waited anxiously for a bus carrying prisoners, some 
studying lists of names in newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Five Jewish extremists gathered nearby, chanting ``Death to  
terrorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the protesters, Noam Federman, said that Israel ``should  
take them (the prisoners) to the central square ... and hang them 
all.'' Israeli troops moved between the two groups to prevent 
friction. 
</P>
<P>
	Near the West Bank town of Hebron, teen-ager Mohammed Sakhouri  
waited for the prisoners with a cellular phone pressed to his ear, 
to share the moment with his mother waiting at home. ``Mother, he 
is out,'' Mohammed shouted when he spotted his brother, Shukri, 33, 
on a bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Shukri Sakhouri, who was sentenced to life for killing a  
suspected collaborator and wounding Israelis, hugged and kissed his 
7-year-old son, Ashraf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that President Arafat will make every effort to have  
the other prisoners released, because everyone one of us is looking 
to be free,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were disappointed. One woman, Hasiba Shehade, leaned  
against a car and cried when told that her son, Ahmed, serving a 
life term for killing a suspected collaborator, was not among those 
freed. Her son had switched his allegiance in jail from Fatah to 
the Islamic Jihad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand this,'' she said. ``The man who carried out  
the operation with him, from Fatah, was released in the first 
batch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Authority official Hisham Abdel Razek, who has  
negotiated the releases with Israel, said the prisoners from 
Jordan, Egypt, Lebanon, Iraq and Libya would be given a special 
reception at a camp for Arafat's bodyguard unit, Force 17, in Gaza 
City later today. Arrangements would then be made to return them 
home, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next step of the peace agreement, Israel is to open a  
land route for Palestinians between the West Bank and Gaza Strip on 
Sunday. The so-called safe passage, seen as a step toward 
Palestinian statehood, allows Palestinians for the first time to 
travel relatively freely. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
