<HEADLINE> Vietnam Resort Plan May Be Scrapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALAT, Vietnam (AP) -- A $706 million plan to build Vietnam's  
biggest tourist resort may be dismantled after the Singapore 
consortium slated to finance it postponed its investment 
indefinitely, according to Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	The project's demise would be a serious blow to Lam Dong, the  
central highlands province for which it was planned. Provincial 
leaders had hoped money spent by an anticipated 300,000 additional 
tourists each year would triple local incomes after a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	An executive at LKN Management Service Co., a member of the  
project's Singapore-based consultancy team, said domestic financial 
constraints faced by consortium members mean ``there will be no 
further movement'' on the Dankia project in the foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal to build the Dalat Dankia Resort was approved by Hanoi  
in January 1998 after nearly six years of talks. Work hasn't 
started on the 5,750-acre project, which would include two golf 
courses, a theater, a botanical garden and a zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Singapore investors are NatSteel Resorts International, a  
unit of NatSteel Ltd.; Singapore Leisure Industries; and LKN 
Construction, a unit of Lim Kah Ngam Ltd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
