<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Providence Mayoral Ratings Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Another corruption scandal has hit City  
Hall, and yet the mayor's approval ratings are going up, up, up. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact is, people in Providence are feeling mighty good about  
their city, and many give credit for its renaissance to Mayor 
Vincent A. ``Buddy'' Cianci Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest city in the smallest state has gone from an urban  
eyesore, once known for its mobsters and strip joints, into a 
welcoming destination for tourists and conventioneers. Newspaper 
travel sections run features on the city, and the TV series 
``Providence'' opens with a romantic view of the skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a doubt, the 58-year-old Cianci has some rough edges. A  
decade ago he got in trouble for an assault. He is known to use 
foul language to upbraid city employees. And political opponents 
have accused him of not always playing fair. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is also adored as the man who made Providence a media  
star -- the Seattle of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone loves Buddy,'' said Jeanne Dupuis, who lives in  
Scituate but wants to move to Providence, largely because of the 
city's rebirth. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has breathed life back into the city. Ten years ago it was  
like a ghost town,'' she said as she was leaving The Arcade 
shopping mall. 
</P>
<P>
	This city of 160,000 started to die in the 1940s and '50s with  
the closing of textile and jewelry factories. Later on, suburban 
shopping malls bled retail life out of much of downtown. But 
Providence has undergone an astonishing metamorphosis under Cianci. 
</P>
<P>
	He was behind the creation of Waterplace Park, a system of  
canals and brick walkways formed by rerouting two rivers. Iron 
pedestrian bridges and gondola rides give the area a Venice-like 
atmosphere. The city also has an arts and entertainment district 
where artists who live and work in new loft studios get tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	A $460 million, 160-store shopping mall opened last summer on  
edge of downtown, a block from the $350 million convention center 
and hotel that were completed in 1994. Other projects include a new 
skating rink and $300 million in transportation improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the city's revival has been funded by federal dollars,  
which Cianci has proved a master at landing. The city's new look 
is, in turn, bringing in lots of dollars from tourists and 
conventioneers, 4 million of whom visited Providence last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I'm at the top of my game,'' said Cianci, a chain  
smoker with a gap-tooth smile. ``I love the city and I love my 
job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A new statewide poll gives the mayor a 75 percent approval  
rating -- higher than that of any other Rhode Island politician. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a remarkable feat for Cianci, who was first elected in  
1974 as a Republican but is now an independent. During his first 
administration, 30 city employees and contractors were indicted on 
charges including extortion and fraud. Twenty-two were convicted 
and 17 went to jail. Cianci himself denied any knowledge of 
corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, he pleaded no contest to beating up a man he suspected  
of having an affair with his estranged wife. He got no jail time 
but had to resign under a city ordinance. He ran again in 1990 and 
won by a narrow margin. He has been re-elected twice since and 
plans to run again in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	And again, investigators are sniffing around City Hall.  
</P>
<P>
	Four city tax officials have been indicted this year on  
corruption charges, and more arrests are expected. Although Cianci 
has not been accused of any wrongdoing, a grand jury has subpoenaed 
his campaign finance records and other documents. 
</P>
<P>
	But few people in Providence seem disturbed by the federal  
investigation. In fact, there's a joke going around that every 
indictment is worth another five points for Cianci in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Cianci seems unfazed by the investigation and the stream of  
stories it has spawned. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more they whack at me, the more my ratings go up,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
