<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Lindros Tone Speaks Volumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The anxiety index is rising for the  
Philadelphia Flyers, who have begun a season of great expectations 
with the worst five-game start in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't walk away from this thinking that there isn't a high  
level of anxiety in here,'' captain Eric Lindros warned Friday. 
``There certainly is. There's a lot going on here. A lot is at 
stake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those are ominous words from the Flyers' franchise player, who  
has labeled this season as pivotal to his future and that of the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to see the direction that the team goes,'' Lindros said  
before the season, referring to his status as a potential free 
agent next summer. ``I want to see what happens this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A dismal 0-4-1 start can't help.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's urgency to win a game,'' left wing John LeClair said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, who have lost key forwards Rod Brind'Amour and Keith  
Jones for up to two months with injuries, lost 5-4 in overtime to 
the Montreal Canadiens on Thursday night. It is the first winless 
five-game start in 32 years of the franchise's existence. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss also came one day after team chairman Ed Snider met for  
nearly six hours with general manager Bob Clarke, coach Roger 
Neilson and the front office staff at the team's New Jersey 
training facility. Neilson, who replaced Wayne Cashman at the end 
of the 1997-98 season, is fielding questions about job security 
after only five games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't be worried about that,'' Neilson said. ``We've played  
five games in an 82-game schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players know about the meetings, so it's impossible to keep  
the speculation from trickling down to the locker room. Lindros, 
who has spoken publicly in support of Neilson, said he wouldn't 
make the case to Clarke or anyone in the front office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't go upstairs,'' Lindros said. ``I don't get involved in  
that. I talk to you guys. I haven't been upstairs in years. And 
never once when I went upstairs was it about something like that. 
That's not my responsibility. We're given a game plan and as 
players, we've got to perform it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They have done a poor job of it so far.  
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers were shut out in their first two losses. Lindros and  
LeClair have regained their scoring touch, but defensive lapses and 
shaky goaltending have become the new culprit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough situation. Everybody knows it,'' said defenseman  
Eric Desjardins, who is minus-6 in two games and looks sluggish 
after offseason knee surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers blew a 4-2 second-period lead Thursday night to the  
Canadiens, who were missing eight regulars due to injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have them,'' Lindros said, referring to Brind'Amour  
and Jones. ``So get over it. Other teams are missing players, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson scolded his team Friday for the third time in five days  
for its lack of communication and inability to move the puck out of 
its own zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't happy this morning when we talked to the team,''  
Neilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	But there have been no tantrums yet. At this point, the anger in  
the locker room hasn't boiled over into finger-pointing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you think anybody here likes what's going on?'' LeClair  
said. ``You can't get mad, you've got to do something about it. The 
embarrassment factor alone should be motivation enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke met with his scouting staff again Friday and worked the  
phones, perhaps trying to find a way to plug the holes with a 
trade. He turned over nearly half the roster with trades last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what to expect,'' Lindros said. ``I don't know  
what he's going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Vanbiesbrouck, who is nursing a strained hip, will be back  
in goal on Saturday in Detroit. Neilson's decision to start rookie 
Brian Boucher backfired Thursday night. Boucher was shaky, allowing 
three goals between his legs in his NHL debut. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, desperately needing a victory, haven't won in  
Detroit since Nov. 1988 (0-8-2). 
</P>
<P>
	``It just gets better, doesn't it?'' Lindros said. ``You turn it  
around, break that string and turn over a new leaf. It's got to 
start some time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
