<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Coordinates To Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPERE, Finland (AP) -- Abandoning decades of go-it-alone  
policies, leaders of the 15 European Union nations debated steps 
today to coordinate their fight against illegal immigration and 
organized crime across Western Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU leaders gathered for the start of a two-day meeting in  
this once-flourishing industrial town of 190,000 in southern 
Finland. Participants said they were taking a first step toward 
better legal cooperation between the EU nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are centuries of difference in criminal laws. You cannot  
pull up legal systems by the root,'' British Home Secretary Jack 
Straw told reporters. ``You have to improve cooperation and joint 
recognition'' of legal systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU nations have long been hesitant to deploy a single system  
of law enforcement, but the idea of international coordination has 
recently been taking on increasing significance. 
</P>
<P>
	The calls for cooperation are driven in part by the rise of  
extreme right-wing parties, which have in some EU countries made 
gains on mainstream parties by playing on public complaints about 
crime and immigration. 
</P>
<P>
	Closer EU unity in recent years is behind many of the problems.  
Open borders make movement easier for criminals and illegal 
immigrants. But governments have been slow to improve police 
cooperation or create a legal framework to deal with crimes like 
money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	To get around varying legal systems from country to country, new  
emphasis will be on mutual recognition of court systems, equal 
access to courts for any EU national and measures to ensure 
comparable sentencing from country to country. 
</P>
<P>
	During the summit, leaders will discuss several reform  
blueprints by EU Justice and Home Affairs Commissioner Antonio 
Vitorino. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposals include ideas to streamline family and child  
custody laws -- issues that affect partners of different 
nationalities who must often deal with two sets of laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders also will take up the problem of refugees, thousands  
of whom have flooded EU countries to escape upheaval in places like 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, they discussed a plan for a special fund to help those  
nations that take most immigrants, notably Germany. The aim is to 
prevent so-called ``asylum shopping'' -- newcomers choosing a 
country of residence, then moving on to the next if they fail to 
meet requirements to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm strengthened in the belief we will reach concrete  
results,'' Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen, whose country now 
holds the EU presidency, said before the summit. 
</P>
<P>
	At a dinner later today, the leaders were scheduled to debate a  
proposal that the EU open membership talks with six more nations -- 
Bulgaria, Romania, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia and Malta. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU Executive Commission proposed this week that the union  
begin talks with those countries. They had been rejected in 1997 
while talks with Cyprus, Estonia, Slovenia, Poland, Hungary and the 
Czech Republic got the go-ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	A final decision about whether to open the additional talks is  
expected at a mid-December summit in Helsinki. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
