<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caterpillar Earnings Down 35 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Caterpillar Inc. reported that a continued  
slump in heavy machinery sales lowered its third-quarter earnings 
by 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The heavy equipment manufacturer said today that it earned $219  
million, or 61 cents a share, compared to $336 million, or 92 cents 
a share during the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were a penny over the expectations of Wall Street  
analysts, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Caterpillar 
stock was down 38 cents to $55.25 a share in New York Stock 
Exchange trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter sales were $4.72 billion, down 8.9 percent from  
$5.17 billion a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Caterpillar reported a drop in heavy machinery sales in North  
America and Asia during the quarter. As a result, the company 
lowered its overall estimated sales and revenue for 1999, saying it 
now expects a decline of about 5 percent, Caterpillar Chairman and 
CEO Glen Barton said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But Barton said he expects higher sales in 2000. Analysts also  
have predicted that global economic recovery will result in higher 
earnings next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``While sales of large machines remained weak, truck engine  
sales continued at historic high levels,'' and demand for large 
engines is improving, Barton said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of the year, Caterpillar earned $707  
million, or $1.97 per share, down 42 percent from $1.21 billion, or 
$3.28 per share, in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue came to $14.68 billion, down 5.7 percent from $15.57  
billion. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
