<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 244.74 at 10,041.87  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials briefly plunged below 10,000  
today as stocks tumbled amid news of a spurt in inflation and 
another warning about market exuberance by Federal Reserve Chairman 
Alan Greenspan. Just before the close, the Dow was down 244.74 at 
10,041.87. Moments later, the barometer of 30 major companies 
dipped below 10,000 for the first time since April, slipping to 
9,998.18. The drop yanked the Dow's gain for the year below 10 
percent and put the average about 1,300 points below its Aug. 25 
closing high of 11,326.04, when the Dow was up more than 23 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Irene Lashes Florida Keys  
</P>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- A slow and soggy Hurricane Irene lashed  
the Florida Keys with 75 mph winds and 10 inches of rain today, 
then headed up the state's Gulf Coast on a course that could mean 
more misery for flood-stricken North Carolina. The weak hurricane 
is expected to come ashore late tonight between Naples and Fort 
Myers on the southern Gulf Coast with a 5- to 7-foot storm surge. 
The storm drenched Cuba's tobacco fields yesterday and caused 
scattered building collapses in Havana, where at least two people 
were killed. 

</P>
<P>
	Army Chief Rules Pakistan  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan's coup leader drew up plans  
today for imposing order on the country's political chaos, raising 
Pakistanis' hopes the military takeover can sweep away years of 
corrupt government and economic decline. Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, 
whose troops brought down the elected government three days ago, 
also met with an envoy from President Clinton in a bid to win at 
least tolerance of his military regime, despite U.S. calls for him 
to restore democracy. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Outlines Anti-Hunger Measures  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- On World Hunger Day, Vice President Al Gore  
dropped in on a local soup kitchen today to promise a healthy 
school breakfast for every child and food stamps for legal 
immigrants if he is elected president. Fourteen million children 
are among the 36 million Americans who go hungry each day. His 
hunger-fighting platform was rushed out ahead of a long-scheduled 
address on child poverty next week by rival Bill Bradley. 

</P>
<P>
	Habibie's Election Bid Falters  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Riot police used tear gas and batons  
to disperse thousands of anti-government demonstrators Friday as 
harsh criticism mounted of President B.J. Habibie, eroding his 
chances of retaining his post in a vote next week. About 30 
protesters were hospitalized and 10 policeman were injured Friday 
in clashes that closed Jakarta's business district for hours. The 
turmoil raised the prospect of further instability in Indonesia, 
already reeling from political unrest and its worst economic crisis 
in decades. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanians Clash With Peacekeepers  
</P>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a shower of stones,  
tear gas and percussion grenades, French-led troops and foreign 
police drove back hundreds of ethnic Albanians trying to storm 
across a bridge to the Serb side of this Kosovo town today. More 
than 100 people were injured in the melee, the most violent clash 
here in a month, NATO said. Mitrovica's Albanians say NATO forces 
are keeping them from their homes, schools and a mine in the Serb 
part of town. But allowing them to cross would spark far greater 
violence because of ethnic hatred. 

</P>
<P>
	Diarrhea Vaccine Pulled From Market  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Just a year after the government approved it,  
the world's only vaccine against the leading cause of childhood 
diarrhea was pulled off the market today because of fears it may 
increase infants' risk of a dangerous bowel obstruction. The 
government advised doctors in July to temporarily stop vaccinating 
babies against rotavirus after counting 20 infants who developed 
bowel obstruction shortly after swallowing the vaccine. An 
estimated 1 million U.S. infants had been vaccinated. 

</P>
<P>
	Apple Computer Rescinds Price Hike  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc. told customers today that it  
has reversed an irksome decision to retroactively hike prices on 
some computers that customers already had ordered and paid for. 
Several Web sites for Macintosh fans posted a memo today from The 
Apple Store, Apple's Web site for online sales. It informed 
customers that Apple had decided to honor the original price 
``after a good night's sleep and digesting emails from many upset 
customers.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Indians Fire Manager Mike Hargrove  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Mike Hargrove, who managed the Cleveland  
Indians to two World Series appearances but failed to win a title, 
was fired today following his team's latest collapse, a team source 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves and Mets Play Game 3 Tonight  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets send ace Al Leiter to the  
mound tonight as they try to narrow the gap in Game 3 of the NL 
Championship Series against the Atlanta Braves. The Braves won the 
first two games in Turner Field. Atlanta counters with lefty Tom 
Glavine. It will be the first NLCS game at Shea Stadium since Game 
7 in 1988 against Los Angeles. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  




  	   	
</P>
