<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Stocks Regulator Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The chief regulator of Russia's stock market  
resigned Friday following a series of court rulings that undermined 
foreign shareholder rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmitry Vasiliev said his resignation as chairman of the Federal  
Securities Commission was for personal reasons, but didn't 
elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his appointment in 1996, Vasiliev had been seen as a  
champion of Western investors, who have purchased Russian shares 
only to discover in some cases that their legal rights to the 
assets were shaky. 
</P>
<P>
	In one instance, a court in St. Petersburg ruled this week that  
foreign investors must return to the state millions of dollars 
worth of shares in the Lomonosov porcelain factory. 
</P>
<P>
	Vasiliev protested that ruling, saying it weakened the rights of  
foreign shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in the western city of Vyborg, near the border with  
Finland, some 400 paper mill workers rallied Friday to protest a 
court ruling that upheld foreign shareholders' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Mill workers have been blocking representatives of Britain's  
ALCEM company, which holds a controlling stake in the factory, from 
entering the premises. The protests led to clashes with police 
during which 11 workers were injured, the Interfax news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	ALCEM bought the controlling stake last June from another  
British company, Nimonor Investment Ltd. ALCEM then appealed to a 
St. Petersburg court to help it take control of the factory. The 
court ruled in favor of the foreign owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers oppose the new ownership because of reports that up  
to 2,000 employees will be laid off. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
