<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3M Buying Out Dyneon Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) -- 3M Co. announced plans to pay Hoechst AG  
$300 million for its share in the companies' Oakdale-based Dyneon 
joint venture. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced Thursday and expected to close by the end of  
the year, calls for the transfer of Hoechst's 46 percent of the 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Formed by 3M and Hoechst in August 1996, Dyneon is a leader in  
the production of special plastics used as coatings in automotive, 
aerospace and electronics markets. It had 1998 sales of about $350 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	No jobs are expected to be lost or gained from the move. Dyneon  
employs 120 people in Minnesota and 700 worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	3M had 1998 sales of $15 billion. The German company Hoechst had  
sales last year of nearly $25 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
