<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoltz Shows He Can Do It All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Smoltz has already been though enough  
changes this season. For now, let's hold off on a switch to the 
Atlanta Braves' bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, who always thought he would make a pretty good closer,  
gave a tantalizing glimpse of his potential in Game 2 of the NL 
championship series. Making the first relief appearance of his 
major league career, he blew away the New York Mets in the ninth 
inning to preserve a 4-3 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	But the winningest pitcher in postseason history will be back in  
his familiar role Saturday, starting for the Braves in Game 4 at 
Shea Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would make a great closer,'' manager Bobby Cox said ``But  
in my mind, he's one of the greatest starters that ever teed it up 
out there, too. I'd rather have John, if he's healthy, be a starter 
and go out there 33, 34 times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the playoffs, there's hardly any pitcher the Braves would  
prefer to have on the mound than Smoltz, who has a career record of 
12-3 and thrives on the idea of pitching in high-pressure games. 
</P>
<P>
	But this has been a trying season for the 32-year-old  
right-hander, whose tender elbow -- twice surgically repaired -- 
caused him to doubt just how many pitches he had left. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz went on the disabled list two times and seemed to shake  
the persistent pain only when he altered his pitching motion, 
throwing with more of a three-quarters delivery rather than 
straight over the top. He also experimented with new pitches, 
actually dabbling with a knuckleball that puts less pressure on his 
elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	``John Smoltz is always up to the challenge,'' Chipper Jones  
said. ``It doesn't matter whether it's opening day or Game 7 of the 
World Series. Starting or relieving, it doesn't matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox was thinking along the same lines when he sent Smoltz to the  
bullpen for Game 2. After Rocker escaped an eighth-inning jam by 
striking out John Olerud and Robin Ventura, Smoltz jogged in to 
pitch a perfect ninth, getting Bobby Bonilla on a called third 
strike to end the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just knew what John could do,'' Cox said. ``And what a spot  
to come in, with that type of pressure. He's very able to do those 
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four or five years ago, when the Braves were struggling to find  
a closer to follow their magnificent starting rotation, Smoltz 
volunteered to move to the bullpen. Cox rejected the offer and was 
glad he did when Smoltz won the Cy Young in 1996 with a 24-8 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning only 11 games this season, Smoltz knew he might  
start only once in any given series. So he brought up the bullpen 
idea again. 
</P>
<P>
	``After we clinched the (NL East) division, John came in and  
said he would do anything I wanted him to do,'' Cox recalled. ``He 
didn't know if he was going to be the No. 3 (starter) or 4 man. He 
said he would start and pitch two games. Or he would relieve in 
every ball game if I wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz explained his offer like this: ``When you pitch for this  
team, your ego has to disappear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few other top starters have carved highly successful careers  
in the bullpen, notably Dennis Eckersley, Rick Aguilera and Dave 
Righetti. 
</P>
<P>
	After nine seasons with double-figure wins, the Eck became a  
closer in 1987 and went on to record 390 saves, the third-highest 
total in major league history. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera was a solid starter for his first five seasons, but has  
spent nine of the last 10 years working out of the bullpen. He has 
289 saves, putting him 12th on the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	Righetti pitched a no-hitter for the New York Yankees in 1983,  
switched the bullpen the following year and finished his career 
with 252 saves. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of great starters became great closers,'' Cox said.  
``John could certainly do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not likely to happen anytime soon. The Braves already have  
Rocker, who has been downright dominating in the postseason, and 
former closer Kerry Ligtenberg could return in 2000 after missing 
this season with an elbow injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz, who made 380 career starts before his first relief  
appearance, is back in a starting frame of mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've still got a job to do,'' Smoltz said. ``That's pitch Game  
4. Whatever I did the game before will be erased if they beat me in 
Game 4.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
