<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Told of U.S. Torture Instances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration informed a U.N.  
committee today there are instances of torture in the United 
States. ``Abuses occur despite the best precautions and the 
strictest prohibitions,'' said the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Areas of concern include instances of police abuse, excessive  
use of force, brutality and death of prisoners in custody, said the 
report to the U.N. Committee Against Torture. 
</P>
<P>
	Others are overcrowding in prisons, physical and sexual abuse of  
inmates and lack of adequate training and oversight for police and 
prison guards, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``No government can claim a perfect record,'' it said.  
</P>
<P>
	But, Assistant Secretary of State Harold Koh said, ``torture  
does not occur in the United States except in aberrational 
situations and never as a matter of policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The beating of motorist Rodney King by four Los Angeles police  
officers in 1991 and the harsh treatment recently of Abner Louima, 
a Haitian immigrant, by New York City police officers were among 
the incidents cited. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, concerns were raised about the excessive use of force by  
federal agents at Ruby Ridge, Idaho, and in Waco, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report, prepared principally by the State and Justice  
departments, assured the U.N. committee that torture is a criminal 
offense, perpetrators are prosecuted and victims are entitled to 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the federal government may take civil action against  
police misconduct under a 1994 law. As a result, the Justice 
Department's civil rights division filed lawsuits against the 
Philadelphia and Steubenville, Ohio, police departments. 
</P>
<P>
	This led to consent decrees requiring reforms in the  
supervising, training and disciplining of police officers, as well 
as in investigating complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was the first by the United States to the U.N.  
committee under an international convention against torture, which 
was ratified in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, meanwhile, has contributed more than $12.6  
million to the U.N. Fund for the Victims of Torture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every unit of government at every level within the United  
States is committed, by law as well as by policy, to the protection 
of the individual's life, liberty and physical integrity,'' the 
report said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
