<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Killers' Parents To Sue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The parents of Columbine gunman Dylan Klebold  
alleged Friday that Jefferson County authorities are partly 
responsible for the school shooting rampage that left 15 people 
dead. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney representing Thomas and Susan Klebold served notice  
of their intent to sue Sheriff John Stone and two other sheriff's 
officials for negligence. 
</P>
<P>
	Families of 13 victims also have filed notices of plans to sue  
the county and the school district in the wake of the April 20 
rampage at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the lawyers who have filed these notices review the  
cases and realize that there is no legal liability on behalf of the 
county, sheriff or any other county employees that have been 
named,'' said Bill Tuthill, an assistant Jefferson County attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	The Klebolds allege authorities failed to inform them about the  
potentially violent tendencies of the other Columbine gunman, Eric 
Harris, 18, and his relationship with their 17-year-old son. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's deputies were notified of certain actions taken by  
Harris, including threats made by the teen. Likewise, a Web site 
allegedly authored by Harris was brought to the attention of 
sheriff's officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The Klebolds said if they had been notified of the  
investigators' findings, they probably would have demanded that 
their son ``be excluded from all contacts with Eric Harris.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The failure ``was so reckless, willful and wanton as to have  
caused the Klebolds to be subject to substantial damage claims, 
vilification, grief and loss of enjoyment of life,'' the notice 
stated. 
</P>
<P>
	Klebold and Harris hurled bombs and scattered gunfire throughout  
Columbine, killing 12 students and a teacher before they committed 
suicide in the worst school shooting in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbine families had 180 days to file notices of plans to sue.  
The deadline is Sunday, but court and school offices will be 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not suits. These are notices that are required as a  
prerequisite if one decides to file a suit,'' said Tuthill, who 
added that he was surprised the Klebolds submitted a notice. 
</P>
<P>
	In the notice, the Klebolds said they submitted the filing  
because they have been sued by the parents of slain student Isaiah 
Shoels, and believe that other victims' families may file claims 
against them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
