<DOCNO> APW19991015.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 16:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore's Payroll Beats Them All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As he runs for president, Al Gore has no  
shortage of people offering advice. He pays more for staff than any 
other candidate, an analysis of his latest campaign spending report 
shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's huge political machine has eaten up about a fourth of the  
money he'll be allowed to spend until next summer's national 
convention -- and the first delegates won't be picked for another 
three months. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Gore has spent as much on salaries -- $2.2 million --  
as Texas Gov. George W. Bush has spent to run his campaign 
headquarters, including rent, office equipment and taxes in 
addition to payroll. Gore's Democratic opponent, Bill Bradley, 
spent $1.5 million on salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got to cut back his overhead,'' said Candice Nelson, an  
associate professor of political science at American University. 
``In any campaign, a candidate wants to spend the bulk of his money 
talking to voters and not on salaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has spent $14.6 million and had $10.3 million in the bank  
through Sept. 30. He raised $24.9 million, but $534,293 came from 
his general election fund for legal and accounting expenses to pay 
a share of fund-raising costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has raised less than Gore, $19.2 million. But he has  
spent less as well, $8.5 million, giving him a larger bank account 
-- $10.7 million. Gore, for example, has spent twice as much on 
polling, $387,844 to $173,189. 
</P>
<P>
	And between July 1 and Sept. 30, Bradley took in $7.3 million  
worth of contributions to $6.8 million for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Both candidates are accepting federal matching funds for their  
campaigns, which limits the amount of money they can spend to 
around $40 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, on the other hand, continues to set fund-raising records.  
He raised $20.2 million during the last three months, bringing his 
total to $57.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent $12.8 million over the period, more than doubling his  
campaign expenditures. Overall, Bush now has spent $19 million, 
including $7.1 million on fund raising and $2.9 million on travel. 
</P>
<P>
	But he still has $37.7 million in the bank. And since he is not  
taking federal funds, he can raise and spend as much as he wants. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have to watch his money,'' Nelson said. ``He can  
spend as much as he needs to. Even doing that, he will have enough 
left over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush even has spent more money than Steve Forbes, who has pumped  
$16.3 million into his own campaign and raised another $4.5 
million. He spent almost $19 million, including $4 million on 
advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col said much of the money has  
gone to build campaign operations in 10 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to have grassroots organization,'' Dal Col said.  
``We're the only campaign that's organized in all the early 
states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, meanwhile, has moved his campaign headquarters from  
Washington, D.C., to Nashville, Tenn., a move seen as a way to cut 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without the move, spokeswoman Kiki Moore noted that the  
campaign's spending has leveled off; the vice president spent $6 
million between April 1 and June 30. Bradley, on the other hand, 
boosted his campaign spending from $2.8 million between April and 
June . 
</P>
<P>
	``Our investments have been made and our campaign is up and  
operational in key states around the country,'' Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the Gore campaign doesn't expect to run out of money.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is great belief and commitment that we will have the  
financial resources and the appropriate budget management for Al 
Gore to win the nomination and be a well-prepared general election 
candidate who wins the presidency,'' Moore said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
