<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Urges Calm Y2K Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The threats of massive computer failures from  
the Year 2000 date change have been eliminated but the economy 
could still be buffeted if businesses and consumers alter their 
spending patterns because of unwarranted fears, Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said that massive amounts of preparation in getting  
computers ready for the date change have left him confident that 
when Jan. 1, 2000 rolls around, American businesses will be ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``The probability of a cascading of computer failures in mission  
critical systems is now negligible,'' Greenspan said in remarks to 
the National Italian American Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said that he was still concerned about potential economic  
impacts if businesses and consumers alter their buying patterns in 
significant ways. 
</P>
<P>
	For this reason, Greenspan said it was important for authorities  
to get out the most up-to-date reliable information so that 
business and consumers can make their economic judgments based on 
facts and not rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Accurate, credible and timely information on the general state  
of readiness will be essential to reducing uncertainties in the 
months ahead,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	In that way, businesses will be able to base their decisions on  
inventory stockpiling on accurate information and not overstock out 
of unfounded fears. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan in previous speeches has voiced concerns about  
production bottlenecks leading to inflation pressures if a large 
number of businesses feel the need to have sizable inventories on 
hand at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that consumer reactions will also be critical to  
determining whether the computer change will have a major impact on 
economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``The potentially most important piece of the Y2k puzzle for the  
rest of the year is the uncertain response of the American consumer 
as year-end approaches,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, only a ``small number of households, driven by fear of  
the unknown, tell pollsters that they are planning to build large 
stockpiles of food, water, fuel and cash as the millennium 
approaches,'' Greenspan said. But he expressed concern about a 
rising level of consumer worries as the news media focuses more 
attention on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is too compelling a story for audiences that thrive on  
countdowns to the unknown,'' Greenspan said. ``As attention 
heightens and rumors inevitably mushroom, it is important that what 
is known and what is not known be clearly articulated by those of 
us in both public and private leadership positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said in the final analysis, ``facts are the only  
antidote for rumors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said if the authorities dealing with the computer switchover  
do their job properly, the economy will be able to make the 
transition smoothly with a minimum amount of economic disruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we avoid fear-induced, significant economic responses in  
the months ahead, the century date change will hopefully replicate 
the saga of the 'dog that did not bark,' '' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan in his prepared remarks made no specific mention about  
how the economy is performing at present or the sizable 1.1 percent 
jump in wholesale prices that had been reported earlier in the day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
