<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Fines Broncos $25,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The NFL announced Friday it has fined the Denver  
Broncos $25,000 for failing to make a ``timely and full 
disclosure'' last week of the hip injury quarterback Bubby Brister 
suffered in practice two days before last Sunday's game against the 
Oakland Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury occurred Oct. 9 after the Broncos submitted their  
official personnel reports on Wednesday and Thursday. The team was 
obliged under NFL policy to announce it as soon as possible to the 
media as well as the league and the Raiders, the NFL said in a news 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of notifying the media on Friday or Saturday, the  
Broncos ``simply left messages for the league office and the 
Raiders on Saturday about Brister's injury,'' the league quoted NFL 
executive vice president Jeffrey Pash, who imposed the fine, as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL said its policy directs clubs to pay particular  
attention to key players such as quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos spokesman Jim Saccomano said the team would appeal the  
fine and declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Brister didn't play against Oakland, and Broncos coach Mike  
Shanahan said Friday that he would be unable to play Sunday against 
the Green Bay Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last November, the NFL fined the Broncos $15,000 for not  
disclosing a rib injury that limited starting quarterback John 
Elway to five plays off the bench in a game against the San Diego 
Chargers. Elway had practiced all week but did not come out of the 
locker room for kickoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan did not appeal that fine, and the day after it was  
issued the Broncos released an injury report that listed 22 players 
-- almost half the roster. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
