<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Drop to 5-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Banks led the slide Friday as European stocks  
closed at a five-month low. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, Lloyds TSB was one of the worst blue-chip performers,  
followed by NatWest Bank. In Frankfurt, shares in both Deutsche 
Bank and Dresdner Bank fell and in Paris, BNP and Societe Generale 
also declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts blamed stronger-than-expected U.S. producer price data,  
which resulted in an opening drop of 240 points in the Dow Jones 
industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	European stocks were also affected by remarks from Federal  
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan Thursday that U.S. stocks might be 
overvalued. U.S. banks were hard hit, with the Fed expected to 
raise interest rates at its November meeting. The European Central 
Bank is expected to follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Other European decliners included BP Amoco and other oil stocks,  
following fresh decreases in crude prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 614 European companies fell 5.30  
points, or 1.7 percent, to close at 298.48. The Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index -- which includes 310 companies in countries that joined 
the single currency -- closed 4.54 points lower at 314.86. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 56.95 points to 3638.82,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 72.50 points at 3592.55. 
</P>
<P>
	In European markets, the worst performers were Zurich, with the  
SMI index losing 2.4 percent, and London with a drop of 132.1 
points, or 2.2 percent, to 5,907.3 in the blue-chip Financial 
Times-Stock Exchange 100-Share index. 
</P>
<P>
	The plunge in the FTSE 100-Share index was its steepest in  
percentage terms since Sept. 3, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The German market was buoyed by auto stocks, and Frankfurt's  
Xetra DAX index closed with a loss of 0.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, the Paris CAC-40 index fell 1.3 percent;  
Milan's MIBtel index fell 1.7 percent; and Amsterdam's AEX Index 
closed down 1.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts predicted further losses as concern about the outlook  
for global interest rates persists. Highly valued technology stocks 
are expected to be knocked back, and cyclicals, which had begun to 
recover earlier in the year, may relapse as investors fear declines 
in the global economy. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
