<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 168.44; Nasdaq Down 52.99 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks tumbled today, nearly sending the Dow  
Jones industrial average below 10,000, amid news of a spurt in 
inflation and a warning by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
against excessive optimism by investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow was off 168.44 at  
10,118.18. An early 241-point plunge pushed the Dow to the lowest 
level since April and about 1,200 points below the Aug. 25 closing 
record of 11,326.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also bounced from their morning lows,  
but continued to hold sharp losses for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index was down 52.99  
at 2,753.85 after halving an early 102-point plunge. The Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500-stock index was down 22.09 at 1,261.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff followed a morning report that revealed prices at  
the wholesale level spiked 1.1 percent in September, the largest 
increase in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in the Producer Price Index, which measures  
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was much worse 
than expected. Many analysts were anticipating that prices would 
rise 0.5 percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in a speech to bankers Thursday night, Greenspan  
issued his latest call for investor sobriety at a time of robust 
economic expansion and roaring stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Both developments aggravated market fears that the Federal  
Reserve will raise interest rates for the third time this year in a 
bid to fight inflation by slowing the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	This afternoon, in a prepared speech on the Year 2000 date  
change, Greenspan made no mention of today's inflation report or 
the overall financial backdrop. Fed policy makers hold their next 
meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, which could see demand for loans hurt by  
rising interest rates, led today's decline. Among the Dow's 30 
components, American Express was down 5 15/16 at 136 1/16, and J.P. 
Morgan was down 3 3/4 at 107 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the day's downward trend, Sun Microsystems surged 5  
11/32 to 94 3/4 in active Nasdaq trading after the maker of powerful 
business computers posted better than expected profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumber advancers by more than a 3-to-1  
margin overall. Trading slowed from the morning's hectic pace, with 
586.03 million shares changing hands on the New York Stock 
Exchange, down from 608.94 million at the same point on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 5.00 at  
414.31. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets also took a big hit today. In Europe, Britain's  
FT-SE 100 fell 2.2 percent, Germany's DAX index fell 0.7 percent 
percent and France's CAC-40 fell 1.3 percent. Japan's Nikkei stock 
average fell 1.0 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
