<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Original One-Person Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The subject matter of one-person shows sure has  
changed from the days when biographical portraits of such greats as 
Mark Twain, Emily Dickinson and Clarence Darrow were the norm. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider ``Fully Committed,'' a cheeky, slightly caustic  
commentary by Becky Mode about a peculiar aspect of New York life. 
The play, now at off-Broadway's Vineyard Theater, chronicles the 
harried life of a young man who takes reservations at the hottest 
restaurant in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	It's only a job, you might say, but what a job! The high-stress  
factor rises every time the phone rings at this unnamed but trendy 
establishment. The caller might be flunky for supermodel Naomi 
Campbell, demanding a reservation for 16, or the coked-out, 
complaining maitre'd, who fails to recognize celebrities, or a 
steely sweet socialite requiring a specific table -- one that 
already has been taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Mode hilariously depicts the pressures that frazzle Sam, a  
would-be actor, played by Mark Setlock, who also portrays all the 
persistent callers by shifting his voice and his body language. 
</P>
<P>
	As victim and abuser, Setlock gets the Jekyll and Hyde aspects  
of the evening down perfectly. He is an ingratiating, versatile 
actor, building a natural sympathy for eager-to-please Sam and a 
dislike for the poor guy's tormentors. 
</P>
<P>
	At 75 minutes, ``Fully Committed'' -- the phrase Sam is  
instructed to use when explaining the restaurant is entirely booked 
-- is just the right length. Anything longer would jangle the 
audience, particularly with that reservation phone line going off 
every other minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimming is in order at ``Chesapeake,'' particularly in Act 1 of  
Lee Blessing's inventive, if overly talky saga of one man's quest 
for revenge. The play, at Second Stage, is original and timely, 
considering the fuss made by New York's mayor over the Brooklyn 
Museum's latest art exhibition. It also is quite funny. 
</P>
<P>
	The plot concerns a performance artist and his desire to get  
back at a politician who threatens to cut off government funds for 
the arts. The artist's instrument for poetic justice: a dog, the 
politician's Chesapeake Bay retriever named Lucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Things don't go according to plan, but half the fun of  
``Chesapeake'' is its surprising second act, so details will not be 
revealed here. What can be confirmed is the virtuosity of actor 
Mark Linn-Baker, a terrific comedian. The man can play just about 
anything, a statement confirmed by what occurs in Blessing's 
astonishing entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hedwig and the Angry Inch'' is not a one-person show, but it  
might as well be, considering the demands made on the title 
character. The long-running musical has just taken a leap, a 
dangerous one, in fact. 
</P>
<P>
	Ally Sheedy, one of filmdom's most unconventional and  
interesting actresses, has joined the cast as Hedwig, the 
transsexual rock diva who changes gender -- from male to female -- on 
the rocky road to a questionable pop career. 
</P>
<P>
	The results are mixed, with Sheedy not up to the considerable  
demands of Stephen Trask's tough score. Her singing voice is modest 
and gives out about two-thirds of the way through the evening. Yet 
Sheedy is a game performer, quirky and determined, who brings a 
vulnerability to the role originally played by its creator, John 
Cameron Mitchell. 
</P>
<P>
	The character begins life as a boy in Communist East Berlin,  
before the fall of the Wall, and after a botched sex-change 
operation ends up a woman in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is no doubt that Sheedy is a woman, a fact which  
lessens the bizarre quality of Hedwig's tale. In the end, despite 
Sheedy's valiant efforts, this cast change is a provocative idea 
that never quite lives up to its anticipation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
