<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Presents Public Service Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Associated Press Managing Editors  
association presented its 1999 Public Service Awards to The 
Star-Ledger, Newark, N.J., and The Wenatchee (Wash.) World on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Star-Ledger in the 50,000-and-over circulation category, was  
selected for an in-depth examination of the New Jersey State Police 
and racial profiling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wenatchee World won in the under-50,000 circulation category  
for an investigation which found that although the percentage of 
minorities had increased dramatically in the area over 15 years, 
employment of minorities in local government had been minimal, 
despite affirmative action programs. 
</P>
<P>
	APME past President Robert G. McGruder, executive editor of the  
Detroit Free Press, and the head of the judging panel, presented 
the plaques at the APME conference here. 
</P>
<P>
	The other judges were William E. Ahearn, vice president and  
executive editor of The Associated Press, Pam Johnson, president of 
APME and vice president news and executive editor, The Arizona 
Republic, Phoenix and former APME presidents Reid MacCluggage, 
editor and publisher, The Day, New London, Conn., and David Hawpe, 
vice president and editorial director of the Courier-Journal of 
Louisville, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	The other finalists in the 50,000-and-over category were the  
Detroit Free Press, the Sun-Sentinel, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., The 
Hartford (Conn.) Courant, the Los Angeles Times, the Pittsburgh 
Post-Gazette, the Saint Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press, The Salt Lake 
Tribune, Salt Lake City, the San Francisco Examiner and the 
Waterbury (Conn.) Republican American. 
</P>
<P>
	The other under-50,000-circulation finalists were The  
Courier-News, Bridgewater, N.J., the Southeast Missourian, Cape 
Girardeau, Mo., The Recorder, Greenfield, Mass. and the Hattiesburg 
(Miss.) American. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
