<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nemechek Turns 198 mph Lap for Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) -- Joe Nemechek, running the fastest  
qualifying lap at Talladega Superspeedway in 10 years, was nearly 
breathless after his pole-winning effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning his third pole of the season and fifth of his career,  
``Front Row Joe'' turned a lap of 198.331 mph in qualifying Friday 
for the Winston 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek, who completed his fast lap on the high-banked,  
2.66-mile oval with about 15 drivers still waiting to qualify, 
said, ``I'll tell you what, if they can beat that, they can have 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pole-winning lap couldn't approach the track record of  
212.809, set by Bill Elliott with an unrestricted engine in the 
spring of 1987. By the following year, NASCAR had begun requiring 
carburetor restrictor plates to slow the cars at Talladega and 
Daytona. 
</P>
<P>
	Each time the speeds began to inch too close to 200, the  
sanctioning body cut horsepower by making bigger holes in the 
restrictor plate. But the engine-builders continue to make inroads, 
as illustrated by recent results at Talladega. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek's lap is the fastest since Elliott's 199.388 in 1990.  
Since then, the top qualifying speeds have been mostly under 195 
until last fall when Bobby Labonte bumped it to 196.153. Ken 
Schrader upped the ante in the spring to 197.765. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek, who will replace Schrader next season, said, ``We've  
just worked really hard on our speedway program this year. We 
qualified fourth here in the spring and we won the pole at Daytona 
(in July) with this same car. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got into a wreck in Daytona with two laps to go and had to  
put on a new front end, so we didn't know how fast it was going to 
go. But the car was great and the motor shop obviously found us 
some more power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for his breathless fast lap, Nemechek said, ``It got a little  
rough because the cars are running so close to the ground. But that 
was all we had. If somebody else could run faster, well, so be 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ricky Rudd's 198.265 made it the same front row for Sunday as in  
July at Daytona. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why the speeds have climbed so high, Rudd said, ``The guys  
working on the cars are real creative and the guys in the engine 
shop are finding more horsepower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kenny Wallace, Schrader's teammate, was close behind Rudd at  
198.105, taking a ride as rough as Nemechek's. 
</P>
<P>
	``For some reason, and I don't know why, the cars seems to  
riding a lot rougher,'' Wallace said. ``Maybe because I ran a 198 
lap. But I'll tell you, it was not enjoyable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace, younger brother of Winston Cup star Rusty Wallace, said  
an expected rule change will probably bring the speeds down for the 
restrictor-plate races next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I hear, they're going to make us use stiffer  
springs,'' Wallace said. ``That'll keep the rear end of the car 
maybe 5 inches higher in the air in qualifying and that will 
probably allow NASCAR to slow us down by 5 mph without having to 
deal with the motors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rudd smiled when asked about the rough ride, saying, ``I've been  
here before and rattled my teeth. I couldn't even see because of 
the vibration. It was a real violent ride. But today it wasn't so 
bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of hate to see the rules change now that we've finally  
been able to figure it out. The majority of the guys in the garage 
area will tell you it rattles your teeth, but some are riding 
comfortably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schrader was fourth at 197.358, followed by rookie Tony Stewart  
(197.114), Sterling Marlin (197.001), Wally Dallenbach (196.822), 
Terry Labonte (196.427) and Mark Martin and Rusty Wallace (both 
196.262). 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Gordon, heading into Sunday with a two-race winning string,  
was 14th (195.724) and series points leader Dale Jarrett was 17th 
(195.397). Bobby Labonte, who is second in the driver standings, 
222 points behind Jarrett with five races remaining, qualified 11th 
(196.242). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
