<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irish, Trojans a Huge Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Southern Cal-Notre Dame is usually  
billed as the nation's top intersectional rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	But Notre Dame hasn't been holding up its end of the deal  
lately. 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish have lost three straight to the Trojans, each in a  
heartbreaking fashion. Two of those losses have kept the Irish out 
of the Bowl Championship Series, and now the seniors are faced with 
the prospect of leaving Notre Dame without ever beating USC. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they all realize what those losses have done. You're  
talking about maybe having the opportunity to go to a bowl game in 
both those occurrences (in '96 and '98). Those were devastating 
losses for us,'' said Notre Dame coach Bob Davie, who's 0-2 against 
the Trojans. ``This is a great rivalry if we hold up our end of the 
bargain and come out and play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the Irish (3-3) lost to USC (3-2), they did it  
without quarterback Jarious Jackson. The Irish quarterback had to 
sit out the 10-0 loss -- which snapped Notre Dame's eight-game 
winning streak -- because of a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our opportunity to definitely go to a BCS bowl and to  
be injured the last play of the game before was heartbreaking,'' 
Jackson said. ``But now I get my chance to play against these 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last thing USC wants to see is a motivated Jackson.  
</P>
<P>
	After the offense struggled during a 1-3 start, the Irish have  
come together the last few weeks, mostly because of Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks ago, he wasn't even rated nationally for passing  
efficiency, but he climbed to No. 3 this week with 155.88 rating 
points. His 281 yards of offense per game ranks 16th in the 
country, and he just finished the second-best five-game streak of 
any quarterback in Notre Dame history with 1,313 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	His 233.7 yards passing a game ranks second in school history  
behind Joe Theismann's 242.9 in 1970, and his 61.8 completion 
percentage is ahead of Kevin McDougal's Irish record 61.6, set in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've had confidence since Day One, but everybody is  
starting to click,'' wide receiver Joey Getherall said. ``Jarious 
is playing out of his mind right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things aren't going quite as well for the Trojans after losing  
to Arizona 31-24 last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their running game, led by Chad Morton with 401 yards, was  
held to minus-20 yards in the loss, while Arizona gained 550 yards 
against one of the Pac-10's best defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a very, very proud team that is frustrated now,'' said  
USC coach Paul Hackett. ``We're disappointed. What we've seen all 
along is an excellent football team that hasn't happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Trojans might not need much of a running game to play  
Notre Dame tough, especially if they can get it done through the 
air. 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish secondary has been solid, though unspectacular, and  
has had problems covering explosive receivers like USC's Jay 
Soward. While the Trojans will be without quarterback Carson 
Palmer, who broke his collarbone against Oregon three weeks ago and 
won't return until at least November, Mike Van Raaphorst has 
completed 55 percent of his passes for just less than 200 yards a 
game this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Soward) is a definite first-round draft pick, and I remember  
last year you felt him every time he was on the field,'' Davie 
said. ``He's not a big tall guy like (Michigan's David) Terrell or 
(Michigan State's Plaxico) Burress, but he's the difference-maker. 
You wanted to know where No. 18 was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sophomore tackle Jordan Black, who will get his first taste of  
the rivalry Saturday, said it's disgusting to think about the Irish 
losing three straight to the Trojans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time a team has beaten Notre Dame three straight games,  
we've just got to be offended by that,'' he said. ``You've got to 
just have a nasty attitude about it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
