<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chimpanzee in Custody Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST COVINA, Calif. (AP) -- He's been described as ``a good  
citizen'' and ``a political prisoner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moe the chimpanzee, the subject of an emotional custody dispute,  
is having his day in court and it's creating a local sensation. 
</P>
<P>
	An army of lawyers is fighting over whether Moe, who has bitten  
a couple of people, should remain in quarantine or be allowed to 
return to his surrogate parents, St. James and LaDonna Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Davises rescued him from the wilds of Africa 30 years ago  
when his mother was killed by poachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want our family back together,'' a weeping St. James Davis  
told reporters outside the local courthouse on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Picketers -- mostly neighbors who have lived on the same street  
as Moe for years -- marched with signs saying, ``Bring Moe Home,'' 
``West Covina Loves Moe'' and ``Moe is a political prisoner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He causes a lot less problems than the kids in the  
neighborhood,'' said Susan Stewart, calling Moe ``a good citizen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had tried to evict Moe from West Covina in the 1960s  
but a judge let him stay, saying the chimp ``doesn't have the 
traits of a wild animal and was somewhat better behaved than some 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moe went on to become a local celebrity, appearing at ribbon  
cuttings, helping sell cookies for the Girl Scouts, even appearing 
in a movie or two. 
</P>
<P>
	His troubles began in August 1998 when a worker fixing something  
in Moe's cage accidentally caused an electrical shock to the chimp. 
Moe panicked, escaped and ran through the neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Animal control officers tried to calm him, neighbors said, but  
police roared up with flashing lights and sirens and Moe became 
more agitated. He bit a police officer and an animal control 
worker. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, a community relations officer asked to visit Moe.  
Sheryl Ortiz was told not to go too close, according to the 
Davises, but she stuck her finger into Moe's cage. At first he 
sucked on the finger, then he bit off the tip. 
</P>
<P>
	They explained that because he likes red licorice, he thought he  
was biting into a piece of the candy when he saw her red nail 
polish. 
</P>
<P>
	Moe has been taken to the Wildlife Way Station to be  
quarantined. 
</P>
<P>
	Municipal Court Judge Carol Williams Elswick postponed all  
action until Nov. 19, expressing hope that the parties will reach 
an out-of-court settlement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
