<DOCNO> APW19991015.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 00:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Close Calls For Red Sox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Call it the Curse of the Bambino's Wall.  
</P>
<P>
	Twice, the Boston Red Sox hit long drives to right field that  
looked like they might be home runs. Twice, the balls hit the very 
top of the fence and bounced back into play. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than solo home runs, Jason Varitek and Troy O'Leary both  
wound up stranded on third base Thursday night in Boston's 3-2 loss 
to the New York Yankees in Game 2 of the AL championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was a big break for us,'' Yankees right fielder Paul  
O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill patrols the same position that Babe Ruth once played on  
the same Yankee Stadium field. If the Red Sox, now trailing 2-0 in 
the best-of-7 series, didn't believe in the Ruthian jinx, surely 
they do now. 
</P>
<P>
	It was as if Ruth, whose sale from the Red Sox to the Yankees  
after the 1919 season seemingly sent Boston into an eight-decade 
slide without a World Series title, reached out and swatted away 
the two potential home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Told that it appeared the two balls missed going out by less  
than a foot combined, Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said, ``That's 
about right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought Varitek's ball went up in the air and one that  
O'Leary hit was close, too,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was scoreless in the second inning when Varitek hit a drive  
over O'Neill's outstretched glove. O'Neill looked up in the stands, 
thinking the ball was gone, before seeing it on the grass. 
</P>
<P>
	Varitek got a triple, but David Cone retired the next two  
batters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox trailed 3-2 in the eighth when O'Leary led off with  
a drive that also barely missed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sure that was a home run,'' Cone said. ``But when it hit  
the wall, I thought we had a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few more inches, and the Red Sox might be heading back to  
Fenway Park with a 1-1 split. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think on not so cool a night, those balls are home runs,''  
Varitek said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARIANO THE MAGNIFICENT:* Nearly three months ago, Mariano  
Rivera allowed a run. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's been all zeros after that.  
</P>
<P>
	Since that game against Tampa Bay on July 21, the Yankees closer  
has pitched 36 2-3 innings in 32 games without letting an opponent 
cross the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera worked around two hits to pitch a scoreless ninth  
Thursday night, getting a save in the Yankees' 3-2 victory. He 
struck out Damon Buford with runners on first and third to end it. 
</P>
<P>
	``To tell you the truth, nothing is going through my mind,''  
Rivera said. ``I've got to get an out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't worry in that situation,'' he said. ``If you worry,  
you'll lose the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Buford: ``He's a great pitcher and a great closer.''  
</P>
<P>
	The previous night, he pitched two shutout innings and earned  
the victory in a 4-3, 10-inning win in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera has pitched six scoreless innings during the playoffs  
against Texas and Boston. Overall, he has allowed only two earned 
runs in 41 innings in postseason play -- that's an 0.44 ERA, the 
best in major league history among pitchers with at least 30 
innings in postseason play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a number of successful closers who have pitched for  
me'' including John Wetteland, Lee Smith and Tom Henke, New York 
manager Joe Torre said. ``He has been consistent as any closer I've 
ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not seen anything like it and hope I continue to say  
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre was concerned about his other relievers who have gotten  
little work in the playoffs because of the success of the starters. 
In the first four games, Orlando Hernandez went eight innings 
twice, Andy Pettitte pitched 7 1-3 innings and Roger Clemens went 
seven. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Ramiro Mendoza, Mike Stanton, Hideki Irabu and  
Allen Watson didn't pitch in the three-game sweep over Texas or in 
Game 1 against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a problem because you don't know how sharp they're  
going to be,'' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HUSH UP:* The up close sounds of the game turned into the  
sounds of silence for Boston Red Sox manager Jimy Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was wired for sound by Fox Television during Wednesday  
night's first game of the AL championship series, won by the New 
York Yankees 4-3 in 10 innings. He said he wouldn't do it again 
after a discussion on strategy was broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't do it anymore,'' Williams said before Thursday night's  
second game. ``I just don't feel right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he understands the value of bringing baseball closer to  
fans by broadcasting discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're just trying to put people who have never been in the  
dugout, will never be in a dugout, give them an opportunity to see 
maybe what happens a little bit,'' he said. ``I have a respect for 
them for that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't necessarily like to do that and I won't do that  
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Rivera entered Game 1 to start the ninth inning, Williams  
asked coach Dave Jauss the prospects of stealing a base on the 
reliever. The agreement with Fox, he said, precludes broadcasting 
conversations about strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Weisman, Fox's executive producer for baseball, said  
Williams and Jauss discussed that strategy if leadoff hitter Jason 
Varitek reached base. After Varitek grounded out, the conversation 
was broadcast, Weisman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know when they played it,'' Williams said. ``I wasn't  
watching TV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I spoke to Jimy about it and he has no problem,'' Weisman  
said. ``The information about Rivera's move to the plate, anybody 
in the stands can time it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said Williams had an on-off switch ``and, believe me, he  
turned it off throughout the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, it seems, until further notice.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AROUND THE BASES:* New York's Game 3 pitcher Roger Clemens left  
for Boston before Game 2. He's scheduled to pitch Saturday at 
Fenway Park against Pedro Martinez. ... The National Anthem for 
Game 4 will be sung by Lynn Saberhagen. Her husband, Bret 
Saberhagen, is scheduled to start that game for Boston. ... Yankees 
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch was back in the starting lineup for 
Game 2 after X-rays on his right foot were negative. He fouled a 
ball of his foot in the ninth inning of the opener. 
  	   	
</P>
