<HEADLINE> Town Hopes Plea Brings Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YUTAN, Neb. (AP) -- A man accused of killing his wife and staging  
a fiery auto accident to cover up the crime pleaded no contest to 
murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Schnabel, who entered the plea Thursday, could get up to  
life in prison in the slaying of his wife, Sandy, a high school 
volleyball coach. Her beaten body was found under their burning 
minivan at their home May 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnabel, a 42-year-old landscape designer, had claimed she died  
in an accident. He was arrested in front of friends and relatives 
after his wife's funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said he beat his wife in the head at their home and  
then staged the accident. Blood spatters were found on the walls 
and ceiling of the kitchen and the living room. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnabel had taken out a $200,000 life insurance policy on his  
wife about a year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was set for Nov. 30.  
  	   	
</P>
