<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged in Anti-Turkey Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A prominent Armenian-American activist has been  
charged with helping lead a group that plotted bomb attacks against 
Turkish targets in the United States over the past two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourad Topalian, 56, chairman of the Armenian National Committee  
of America, was arrested Thursday on conspiracy, weapons and 
explosives charges. He could face 31 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment accuses him of directing a different group, whose  
members called their efforts ``the Cause,'' which stole weapons and 
explosives used in a 1980 car bombing outside the Turkish mission 
to the United Nations in New York City where three people were 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment also mentions two 1981 California bombings -- at  
the Orange County Convention Center in Anaheim and the Turkish 
consulate in Beverly Hills -- in which no one was hurt, but it does 
not specify whether Topalian was involved. 
</P>
<P>
	He pleaded innocent and was freed on $100,000 bond. Topalian  
returned to U.S. District Court on Friday to surrender his 
passport, and declined to comment after a brief hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment said the attacks were aimed at drawing attention  
to Armenian claims that 1.5 million people were slaughtered in 1915 
as part of a campaign of genocide aimed at forcing the Armenian 
population from the eastern Ottoman Empire. Turkey says there was 
no systematic campaign of slaughter and that many Armenians fled 
during World War I and the civil unrest that followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Topalian allegedly sent people to Massachusetts and Beirut,  
Lebanon, for weapons and bomb training. The indictment said he 
demonstrated how to use submachine guns at a camp in Franklin, 
Mass., in 1976 and 1977. He also allegedly showed others in his 
group how to use dynamite and blasting caps. 
</P>
<P>
	Aram Hamparian, executive director of the Washington-based  
Armenian National Committee of America, declined to comment Friday 
on the indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just learning the facts of the case,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The investigation of Topalian began with the 1996 discovery of  
weapons and explosives in a suburban storage garage that was opened 
after the rent went unpaid for six months. Police found more than 
100 pounds of high explosives in the garage. 
</P>
<P>
	Before becoming vice president for development at Cuyahoga  
Community College this year, Topalian worked as a consultant to the 
president of Citibank Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	He attended a March 1996 White House coffee session with other  
political and community leaders to discuss issues with President 
Clinton, the White House confirmed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
