<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team To Probe E. Timor Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The United Nations' top human rights official  
named a five-member team Friday that will travel to East Timor and 
investigate allegations of atrocities following the territory's 
vote for independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Robinson, the U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights,  
pledged a ``spirit of cooperation'' toward Indonesia, which has 
rejected the international inquiry and says its own national rights 
commission should investigate abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We owe it to the people of East Timor to investigate seriously  
and objectively the terrible reports of human rights violations and 
establish responsibility for any crimes committed,'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will start by examining the existing evidence in Geneva  
this month, she added, but will not go to the region before next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The group will be led by Sonia Picado of Costa Rica, a member of  
the country's legislative assembly. The other members are A.M. 
Ahmadi, a former Indian chief justice; Mari Kapa, deputy chief 
justice of Papua New Guinea; German lawmaker Sabine 
Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger and Judith Sefi-Attah of Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	An emergency session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission last  
month voted 32-12 for the international inquiry, calling for an 
``adequate representation of Asian experts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team will report its conclusions to U.N. Secretary-General  
Kofi Annan by Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timor was engulfed in violence and anarchy after its people  
voted overwhelmingly Aug. 30 to separate from Indonesia. 
Pro-Indonesian militias, backed by the army, went on a looting and 
killing spree, burning down villages and driving tens of thousands 
of people from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson has said the scale of atrocities could warrant the  
creation of an international tribunal, similar to those established 
to prosecute war crimes from the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be certainly within the power of the commission of  
inquiry to make recommendations for a tribunal or any other 
appropriate response,'' she said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Indonesia refusing to cooperate, there are fears that the  
U.N. inquiry will only be able to gather evidence on the ground and 
collect testimony from eyewitnesses in East Timor, but won't be 
able to corroborate the testimony with Jakarta's military files and 
personnel to establish a chain of command. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
