<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Irene Nears Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Hurricane Irene brought rain and high wind  
to the Florida Keys today after drenching Cuba's tobacco fields and 
causing scattered building collapses in Havana, where at least two 
people were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Though barely a hurricane with winds of 75 mph, the storm cut  
power intermittently in this resort city as Irene's center passed 
nearby during the morning. Up to 10 inches of rain flooded some 
main streets and most secondary roads in Key West and two 
neighboring islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Torrential rains pounded the lower third of the Florida  
peninsula as the storm crawled across the straits separating Cuba 
from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're experiencing some strong tropical storm conditions right  
now from Key West all the way up the Keys as far as Ocean Reef 
right now,'' Billy Wagner, Monroe County Emergency Management 
director, said this morning. Big Pine Key had a gust recorded at 
103 mph, the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	The weak hurricane was expected to come ashore on the mainland  
by early evening in the Everglades, sending a 5- to 7-foot storm 
surge into Key Largo, and pass over Lake Okeechobee before pushing 
into the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters had worried about Irene sending more rain to parts  
of North Carolina flooded by Hurricane Floyd, but said early this 
afternoon that a shift to the east in the may spare the Carolinas 
by keeping the storm off the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	A tropical storm warning covered 280 miles of the Atlantic  
Coast, a storm warning or hurricane watch covered 235 miles along 
the Gulf Coast, and a tornado watch was in effect for South 
Florida. Street flooding, downed tree limbs and outages were 
reported across the state. 
</P>
<P>
	As the storm approached, Collier County, the southernmost Gulf  
Coast county on the Florida mainland, closed public schools and 
government offices today. MacDill Air Force Base in Tampa arranged 
to fly its six refueling tankers to safety in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters said rainfall totals could top 15 inches.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a well-organized hurricane, and there's a huge swath  
of storms and rain to the east'' of its center, said Richard Pasch, 
a hurricane specialist at the National Hurricane Center outside 
Miami. In the city, there was local flooding and authorities asked 
employers to send workers home early. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. EDT, Irene's center was located about 25 miles  
southwest of Flamingo on the southern tip of Florida's peninsula. 
It was moving northeast at 10 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in Monroe County, which covers the Keys, ordered a  
mandatory evacuation of mobile homes and recreational vehicles. 
Schools were closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been raining throughout the night; we've been getting  
quite a few inches of rain and the wind has picked up enormously 
from when I came in at (midnight),'' said David Holliman, a 
security guard at the Lower Keys Medical Center in Key West. ``The 
trees are swaying quite a bit ... and it's getting worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four shelters were opened in the Keys: two in Key West and one  
each in Marathon and Key Largo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We worked all day yesterday. By the time we finished, it was  
too late to go north,'' said Jose Guadarrama, a mobile home 
resident who arrived at the shelter this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In Key West, the collapse of a concrete seawall at the  
oceanfront Key Ambassador Best Western allowed waves to wash over 
the road, pulling chairs, shoes and seaweed in their wake. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a treasure hunt out here,'' said hotel auditor  
Brandon Boyce. Driving rain seeped through the roof or shutters. 
``We've got trash cans everywhere trying to catch it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A possible path toward eastern North Carolina had been unwelcome  
news there, since rivers only recently receded below flood stage 
following Hurricane Floyd's 20-inch deluge last month, blamed for 
49 deaths and record damage. The state was also battered by 
Hurricane Dennis less than three weeks earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Irene left Cuban territory after soaking Havana on Thursday  
evening. Early reports were that the island escaped relatively 
unscathed. 
</P>
<P>
	As of this morning, authorities were reporting two storm-related  
deaths and one other person missing in Havana. Another missing 
person was missing east of Havana on Cuba's northern coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Havana Mayor Conrado Martinez said that 149 buildings were  
damaged by the heavy rains, including 13 that collapsed, and power 
outages were scattered around the city. 
</P>
<P>
	About 130,000 people from western and central Cuba, many of them  
students in government boarding schools, were evacuated as the 
hurricane approached. Classes across the region were suspended. 
Stores, government offices and banks in Havana closed shortly after 
noon Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the western city of Pinar del Rio, laborers worked made sure  
water didn't leak into warehouses storing the tobacco leaves grown 
to make Cuba's famous cigars. Cattle and livestock in the rural 
region were moved to higher ground, and there was some damage 
reported to plantain, tobacco, rice and other crops in Pinar del 
Rio and the small Isle of Youth south of the main island. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
