<HEADLINE> Chimp Paternity Mystery Solved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The mystery in the monkey house has finally  
been solved: Three unexplained chimp births at the Los Angeles Zoo 
were blamed on a vasectomy that didn't work. 
</P>
<P>
	Keepers of the chimpanzee exhibit were shocked earlier this year  
when three females gave birth even though two of their male 
neighbors were too young, three had undergone vasectomies and the 
only other one was too old. 
</P>
<P>
	It turns out that an amorous 11-year-old Shaun got a bad  
vasectomy in 1996.	   ''So Shaun was having a real good time,'' laughed Lora LaMarca, 
the zoo's marketing director. 
</P>
<P>
	The paternity mystery drew international media attention and  
helped boost zoo attendance by 10 percent. The DNA results were 
announced on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' during a visit by 
the surviving chimp babies, Jean and Jake. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterinarians analyzed samples of blood and hair to prove beyond  
a reasonable doubt that Shaun was daddy to Jean, Jake and the late 
Toshi, who was killed in May when play in the pen got too rough. 
</P>
<P>
	The vasectomies were part of the zoo's attempt to stop the  
monkey business in the chimpanzee exhibit, which was on the verge 
of becoming more congested than the San Diego Freeway at rush hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Zoo veterinarians handed out birth control pills, but the  
females passed them around and everyone chomped them down, 
including males and babies. Contraceptive implants weren't strong 
enough to stop the population boom. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was off to the operating room for the exhibit's three  
capable males to have their sperm-carrying vas deferens ducts 
snipped. It's a procedure that's virtually 100 percent effective in 
humans. 
</P>
<P>
	But apparently not in chimpanzees.  
</P>
<P>
	It's likely that the ducts weren't completely severed during the  
operation. Another possibility was that the severed tubes grew back 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	``We removed almost an inch of the cord and folded it over and  
tied it,'' said Charles Sedgwick, the zoo's chief veterinarian. 
``That's a pretty good challenge for Mother Nature to have that 
thing grow back after you do that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
