<HEADLINE> Oats Higher; Soybeans Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices were lower in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices initially rose on unexpectedly strong export  
sales, but quickly reversed course. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and wheat futures prices were hurt by news of poor exports  
of those crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Dry weather is expected in much of the United States today,  
allowing farmers to continue their fall harvest. But forecasters 
are calling for scattered showers this weekend across the corn 
belt, possibly causing temporary delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1 cent to $2.54 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 1/4 cents to $1.99 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 3/4 cents to $1.09 1/2 cents a bushel; and November soybeans fell 1 3/4 
cents to $4.96 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures prices fell and pork futures were mixed in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	December live cattle fell .12 cent to 71.10 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 81.05 cents a pound; 
December lean hogs fell .50 cent to 46.90 cents a pound; and 
February frozen pork bellies rose .15 cent to 64.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
