<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Blacks Favor Seat Belt Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a benchmark survey that will be used to  
track blacks' support of seat belt laws, lawmakers and safety 
advocates found that only a small minority of blacks oppose police 
stopping cars for seat belt violations, despite concerns about 
racial profiling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone who is going to break the law who happens to be  
wearing a uniform does not need (a seat belt) law as a reason to 
pull someone over,'' said New Jersey Assemblyman Herbert Conaway, a 
Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine out of 10 of blacks reported they had ``almost no problems  
at all'' with seat belt laws in their state, according to a survey 
commissioned by the National Black Caucus of State Legislators and 
the Air Bag &AMP; Seat Belt Safety Campaign. And 86 percent said seat 
belt laws are needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Every state but New Hampshire has some type of seat belt law.  
</P>
<P>
	In 16 ``primary belt law'' states and the District of Columbia,  
police may legally stop motorists if they suspect their only 
violation is not fastening a seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	In those states, 74 percent of the blacks surveyed favored the  
law. However, 9 percent said they do have some problem with it, 
ranging from simple disagreement to believing the law contributes 
to race-related harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone survey of 1,100 black adults has a margin of error  
of 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, a July survey of 800 adults of all races showed  
69 percent of motorists in primary belt law states favor their 
laws. That survey, also commissioned by the Air Bag &AMP; Seat Belt 
Safety Campaign, had a margin of error of 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, 22 percent of those surveyed felt that race was a factor  
in being stopped for not wearing a seat belt. But 32 percent said 
they believed incidents of black motorists being unfairly stopped 
had increased in their state in the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy-three percent said they didn't believe race was a factor  
in being stopped, and 43 percent said there had been no change in 
the frequency of black motorists being stopped in their states. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., praised the survey in a statement  
but said additional ``comprehensive study'' is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be difficult to balance the results of a limited  
study against the massive body of anecdotal data on the 'driving 
while black' issue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But pollster Salis Lee, who oversaw the study, stood by the  
results because of the large number of blacks he surveyed. Other 
national studies sometimes include just several hundred blacks, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we go along, we will develop other questions to track the  
trends and perceptions about the law,'' Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil rights groups and the Justice Department have alleged that  
some law enforcement officials practice racial profiling in 
stopping motorists for traffic and other violations based solely on 
their race. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a 1997 Centers for Disease Control study, car  
crashes are the leading cause of death among blacks younger than 15 
and the second leading cause of death among those 15 to 24. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
